INSERT INTO "public"."questions" ("id", "exam", "category", "topic", "question", "answer", "explanation") VALUES (1, 'core1', '1.0 Mobile Devices', '1.1 Laptop Hardware', 'What type of battery chemistry is most common in modern laptops and why?', 'Lithium-Ion (Li-ion) and Lithium-Ion Polymer (LiPo) — no ''memory effect'' and high energy density', 'Laptop batteries are commonly Li-ion or LiPo. Unlike older NiCad batteries, they have no ''memory effect,'' meaning you don''t need to fully discharge before recharging. However, repeatedly charging the battery diminishes its overall capacity over time. Battery form factor varies by laptop model.'), (1, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.8 Network Environments', 'A _____ is a network typically found in your home or workplace.', 'Local area network (LAN)', 'A LAN is a network confined to a small geographic area such as a home, office, or building, typically owned and managed by a single organization.'), (2, 'core1', '1.0 Mobile Devices', '1.1 Laptop Hardware', 'What is a SO-DIMM and where is it used?', 'Small Outline Dual In-line Memory Module — used in laptops and mobile devices', 'SO-DIMMs are about half the width of a standard DIMM and are designed for space-constrained devices like laptops. Some laptop memory is soldered directly to the system board, making it non-upgradeable and requiring a full board replacement if it fails.'), (2, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.8 Network Environments', 'A _____ connection connects your home or workplace to the Internet.', 'Wide area network (WAN)', 'A WAN spans large geographic areas and is commonly used to connect LANs to the Internet or to other remote sites via service provider links.'), (3, 'core1', '1.0 Mobile Devices', '1.1 Laptop Hardware', 'What are the three common laptop storage form factors?', '2.5" magnetic disk (HDD), 2.5" SSD, and M.2', 'Traditional laptop HDDs use 2.5" spinning platters. SSDs come in 2.5" (replacing HDDs directly) and M.2 form factors. M.2 drives are smaller, require no SATA data or power cables, and use a single screw for installation — similar to RAM installation. Desktop HDDs use 3.5" form factor.'), (3, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.6 Network Topologies', 'A _____ topology is also known as a hub-and-spoke topology.', 'Star topology', 'In a star (hub-and-spoke) topology, all endpoints connect to a central device such as a switch or hub, which forwards traffic between them.'), (4, 'core1', '1.0 Mobile Devices', '1.1 Laptop Hardware', 'What are two ways to migrate from a laptop HDD to an SSD?', 'Clean install (OS + apps on SSD) or disk imaging/cloning (copy everything from HDD to SSD)', 'A clean install means installing the OS fresh on the SSD, then reinstalling applications and moving documents — time-consuming but clean. Disk imaging/cloning copies everything from HDD to SSD exactly, requiring imaging software (sometimes included with the SSD). Drive-to-drive imaging copies directly without an intermediate image file.'), (4, 'netplus', '2.0 Network Implementation', '2.4 Physical Installations', 'The term ____ is used to describe the service-related entry point for a provider.', 'Demarc or demarcation point', 'The demarc marks the boundary between the service provider''s equipment and the customer''s internal wiring, defining where provider responsibility ends.'), (5, 'core1', '1.0 Mobile Devices', '1.1 Laptop Hardware', 'What is NFC and what is its typical communication range?', 'Near-Field Communication — approximately 4 centimeters or less', 'NFC enables short-range wireless data transfers and authentication. It''s common on mobile phones and smartwatches for payments (tap to pay) and is also used in hospital workstations, warehouses, and manufacturing for authentication without typing a password.'), (5, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.8 Network Environments', 'The ______ ______ model is used to condense the core and distribution layers into one layer.', 'Collapsed-core', 'A collapsed-core design merges the core and distribution layers of the traditional three-tier model into a single layer, common in smaller networks where a full three-tier design is unnecessary.'), (6, 'core1', '1.0 Mobile Devices', '1.1 Laptop Hardware', 'How are Wi-Fi antennas typically positioned in a laptop?', 'Antenna wires wrap around the laptop screen frame — placed high for better signal', 'Laptops typically have multiple antennas: one for Wi-Fi main, one for Wi-Fi auxiliary, and one for Bluetooth. They are routed around the display panel (screen bezel) to position them as high as possible for better signal reception. This is important to know when replacing a laptop screen.'), (6, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.8 Network Environments', 'A _____ is a virtualized piece of hardware that connects the virtual machine operating system to the network.', 'Virtual NIC (vNIC)', 'A vNIC is a software-emulated network interface presented to a VM by the hypervisor, allowing it to communicate over virtual switches and physical networks.'), (7, 'core1', '1.0 Mobile Devices', '1.2 Connecting Mobile Devices', 'What are the differences between Micro-USB, Mini-USB, and USB-C?', 'Micro-USB: smallest/most common older Android connector; Mini-USB: slightly larger, older; USB-C: 24-pin double-sided, current standard, reversible', 'Micro-USB was the dominant Android standard for many years. Mini-USB preceded it and is slightly larger. USB-C is the current standard — it''s a 24-pin double-sided connector that can carry USB 2.0/3.0/3.1/4 signals, DisplayPort, HDMI, and Thunderbolt depending on the device.'), (7, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.8 Network Environments', 'Fibre Channel is typically found inside a _____.', 'Storage area network (SAN)', 'SANs use high-speed protocols like Fibre Channel to provide block-level access to consolidated storage, presenting remote storage to servers as if it were local.'), (8, 'core1', '1.0 Mobile Devices', '1.2 Connecting Mobile Devices', 'What is Apple''s Lightning connector and what are its advantages over Micro-USB?', 'Apple proprietary 8-pin digital connector for iPhone/iPad — reversible, higher power output, simpler design', 'Lightning uses 8-pin digital signals and is proprietary to Apple''s iPhone and iPad devices. Compared to Micro-USB, it offers higher power output for faster charging, can be inserted in either orientation (reversible), and has a simpler, more durable design. It is being replaced by USB-C on newer Apple devices.'), (8, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.8 Network Environments', 'The term used to reference the smallest piece of the network is ______ ______.', 'Network segment', 'A network segment is the smallest portion of a network, typically a single broadcast or collision domain bounded by Layer 2 or Layer 3 devices.'), (9, 'core1', '1.0 Mobile Devices', '1.2 Connecting Mobile Devices', 'What is Bluetooth used for on mobile devices?', 'Short-range PAN (Personal Area Network) for connecting peripherals, tethering, headsets, health monitors, and smart devices', 'Bluetooth creates a Personal Area Network for high-speed, short-distance communication. Common uses: smartphones (tethering, headsets), automobile integration, smartwatches, external speakers, health monitors. It operates in the 2.4 GHz ISM band and is designed for connecting nearby personal devices.'), (9, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.8 Network Environments', 'The _____ technology uses labels to switch traffic.', 'Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS)', 'MPLS prepends short labels to packets so routers can forward them based on the label rather than performing full IP lookups, enabling fast, traffic-engineered WAN paths.'), (10, 'core1', '1.0 Mobile Devices', '1.2 Connecting Mobile Devices', 'What signals can a USB-C connector carry besides USB data?', 'DisplayPort, HDMI, Thunderbolt — USB-C is a physical connector, not a protocol', 'USB-C describes only the physical connector shape. The actual signal depends on the device. A single USB-C port can carry USB 2.0/3.x/4 data, video via DisplayPort or HDMI, Thunderbolt 3/4, and power delivery. Always check the device specifications to know which signals are supported.'), (10, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.8 Network Environments', 'The _____ _____ architecture is found in data centers to provide low-latency connectivity to servers.', 'Spine leaf', 'In a spine-leaf fabric, every leaf switch connects to every spine switch, giving any server-to-server path a predictable two-hop, low-latency route — ideal for east-west data center traffic.'), (11, 'core1', '1.0 Mobile Devices', '1.2 Mobile Device Accessories', 'What is the difference between a docking station and a port replicator?', 'Docking station adds functionality and may include expansion card slots; port replicator simply replicates existing ports, typically via USB', 'A docking station extends a laptop''s interfaces by adding more ports, desktop adapter cards, and additional functionality — avoiding cable issues when at a desk. A port replicator is similar but simpler — it does not commonly have expansion card slots and usually connects via USB.'), (11, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.8 Network Environments', 'Which network type is locally owned and managed by an organization and used to connect the organization''s LAN together? (A) MAN (B) CAN (C) WAN (D) PAN', 'B. CAN', 'A campus area network (CAN) is locally owned and managed by an organization to connect multiple LANs together. A MAN spans a metropolitan area but is owned by a third party. A WAN provides wide-area connectivity but is owned by a service provider. A PAN connects personal devices in extremely close vicinity.'), (12, 'core1', '1.0 Mobile Devices', '1.2 Mobile Device Accessories', 'What is a digitizer stylus and where is it commonly used?', 'A pen-like input device that communicates directly with the tablet for precise graphical input — e.g., Apple Pencil on iPad', 'A digital stylus is more advanced than a finger for touch input. It communicates directly with the device''s digitizer, supporting pressure sensitivity and programmable buttons. Must be compatible with the specific tablet (e.g., Apple Pencil for iPad). Used for drawing, note-taking, and graphic design.'), (12, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.6 Network Topologies', 'Which network topology design has a centralized switch connecting all of the devices? (A) Star topology (B) Full mesh topology (C) Partial mesh topology (D) Hybrid topology', 'A. Star topology', 'A star (hub-and-spoke) topology has a centralized switch connecting all devices outward like a star. Full mesh is decentralized so any link failure does not affect switching. Partial mesh is typical between core/distribution/access layers. Hybrid combines several topologies such as star and mesh.'), (13, 'core1', '1.0 Mobile Devices', '1.3 Mobile Device Networks', 'What were the key improvements introduced with 3G cellular technology?', 'Upgraded data connectivity enabling GPS, mobile TV, video on demand, and video conferencing — typically several megabits per second', '3G (3rd Generation), introduced in 1998, provided incremental data speed improvements over 2G. The bandwidth improvements enabled new functionality: GPS navigation, mobile television, video on demand, and video conferencing. Speeds were usually several megabits per second.'), (13, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.8 Network Environments', 'Which protocol can be typically found inside a PAN? (A) Bluetooth (B) MPLS (C) SDWAN (D) vNIC', 'A. Bluetooth', 'Bluetooth is a common networking protocol found inside a personal area network (PAN). MPLS uses labels to switch packets across WANs. SDWAN is a virtual WAN architecture that uses software to manage connectivity. A vNIC connects a virtual machine to a virtual switch.'), (14, 'core1', '1.0 Mobile Devices', '1.3 Mobile Device Networks', 'What is LTE and what download speeds does it support?', 'Long Term Evolution — a ''4G'' technology based on GSM/EDGE supporting 150 Mbit/s standard, 300 Mbit/s with LTE Advanced', 'LTE (Long Term Evolution) is the 4G standard based on GSM and EDGE (Enhanced Data Rates for GSM Evolution). Standard LTE supports download rates of 150 Mbit/s. LTE-A (LTE Advanced) supports up to 300 Mbit/s. LTE is widely deployed worldwide.'), (14, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.8 Network Environments', 'When computers are logically grouped on a LAN based upon a functional department in the organization, what is the group called? (A) Backbone (B) CAN (C) PAN (D) Workgroup', 'D. Workgroup', 'A workgroup is a logical grouping of computers on a LAN based upon a department''s function. A backbone connects multiple network segments together. A CAN connects multiple buildings in close proximity. A PAN connects personal devices in close proximity, often using Bluetooth.'), (15, 'core1', '1.0 Mobile Devices', '1.3 Mobile Device Networks', 'What are the key characteristics of 5G networking?', '5th generation cellular launched 2020 — higher frequencies, up to 10 Gbps, significant IoT impact with lower latency and larger data transfers', '5G was launched worldwide in 2020. It operates at higher frequencies than 4G, achieving theoretical speeds up to 10 Gbps (slower sub-6 GHz speeds of 100-900 Mbit/s are more typical). It has significant IoT impact: bandwidth is less of a constraint, enabling faster monitoring, larger data transfers, and additional cloud processing.'), (15, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.6 Network Topologies', 'Which is the primary benefit to using a star topology? (A) Equal access (B) Simplicity (C) Easy to troubleshoot (D) Redundancy', 'C. Easy to troubleshoot', 'A star topology is easy to troubleshoot since each host has its own connection. Equal access is a benefit of ring topologies. Bus topologies are simpler in design. Redundancy is found in mesh networks, not star topologies.'), (16, 'core1', '1.0 Mobile Devices', '1.3 Mobile Device Networks', 'What is a SIM card and what information does it contain?', 'Subscriber Identity Module — a unique identifier card containing SIM ID, phone number, carrier info, and storage for contacts/messages', 'A SIM (Subscriber Identity Module) is typically a small physical card that uniquely identifies a cellular device. It contains the carrier''s network information, the SIM ID, the phone number, and can store contacts and messages. Replacing the SIM gives the phone a new number. eSIM is an embedded version that cannot be physically removed.'), (16, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.8 Network Environments', 'What type of logical connection does MPLS create to connect networks together? (A) Peer-to-peer (B) Client-server (C) East-west (D) Circuit', 'D. Circuit', 'MPLS creates a circuit to logically connect networks. Peer-to-peer is a bidirectional connection for sharing files. Client-server is a one-direction connection from client to server. East-west describes traffic flow within the same network or data center.'), (17, 'core1', '1.0 Mobile Devices', '1.3 Mobile Device Networks', 'What is the Bluetooth pairing process?', 'Enable Bluetooth on both devices → set to discoverable → select discovered device → enter/confirm PIN → test connectivity', 'To pair Bluetooth devices: (1) Enable Bluetooth on both devices (Settings/Bluetooth on Android/iOS), (2) Set both to discoverable mode, (3) Select the discovered device from the list, (4) Enter or confirm the PIN (must match on both), (5) Test that devices can communicate. Future connections should be automatic.'), (17, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.8 Network Environments', 'Which type of network is used exclusively for storage traffic? (A) CAN (B) SAN (C) MAN (D) LAN', 'B. SAN', 'A storage area network (SAN) is used exclusively for storage traffic. A CAN connects buildings in close proximity. A MAN connects clients within a metropolitan area such as a city. A LAN connects hosts within a building or residence.'), (18, 'core1', '1.0 Mobile Devices', '1.3 Mobile Device Networks', 'How does GPS determine location and what infrastructure does it require?', 'Uses timing differences from 30+ orbiting satellites — needs at least 4 satellites to determine longitude, latitude, and altitude', 'GPS (Global Positioning System) was created by the U.S. Department of Defense and uses over 30 satellites in orbit. It determines precise location by calculating timing differences from at least 4 satellites to triangulate longitude, latitude, and altitude. Mobile devices also use Wi-Fi positioning and cellular towers to supplement GPS for faster and more accurate indoor location.'), (18, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.8 Network Environments', 'Which type of traffic flow is routed from your internal network to the Internet? (A) North-south (B) East-west (C) WAN (D) MAN', 'A. North-south', 'North-south traffic describes flow from an internal network to the Internet or other routed destination. East-west traffic stays within the internal network or data center and is not routed externally. WAN and MAN describe network types, not traffic flow.'), (19, 'core1', '1.0 Mobile Devices', '1.3 Mobile Device Management', 'What is MDM and what can it control on mobile devices?', 'Mobile Device Management — centralized management of apps, data, camera, remote control, screen locks, corporate email, and two-factor authentication', 'MDM allows IT administrators to manage both company-owned and user-owned (BYOD) mobile devices from a central console. It can enforce policies on apps, data, and cameras; configure corporate email automatically; require two-factor authentication; allow or restrict app installation; and force screen locks/PINs.'), (19, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.6 Network Topologies', 'Which topology incorporates some redundancy of equipment and connections to provide fault tolerance but is not completely fault-tolerant? (A) Bus (B) Mesh (C) Ring (D) Hybrid', 'D. Hybrid', 'A hybrid topology combines mesh with star (hub-and-spoke) to provide fault-tolerant design at lower cost than full mesh — partially redundant but not completely fault-tolerant. Full mesh provides complete fault tolerance. Ring and bus are susceptible to total network failure if any link fails.'), (20, 'core1', '1.0 Mobile Devices', '1.3 Mobile Device Management', 'What is the difference between BYOD, COPE, and CYOD?', 'BYOD: employee-owned device; COPE: company-owned, personally enabled; CYOD: choose your own device (company buys user''s choice)', 'BYOD (Bring Your Own Device): employee owns the device, must meet company requirements, difficult to secure. COPE (Corporate Owned, Personally Enabled): company buys the device, used for both work and personal — company keeps full control. CYOD (Choose Your Own Device): similar to COPE but the employee chooses the model.'), (20, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.6 Network Topologies', 'Which topology should be selected if you have a central office that needs to communicate with several branch offices for WAN connectivity? (A) Point-to-point (B) Point-to-multipoint (C) Mesh (D) Bus', 'B. Point-to-multipoint', 'Point-to-multipoint connects a central office with several branch offices; common technologies include frame relay and MPLS. Point-to-point typically connects two offices. Mesh and bus topologies are not used for WAN connectivity.'), (21, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.1 Introduction to IP', 'What are the key differences between TCP and UDP?', 'TCP: connection-oriented, reliable, flow control, ordered delivery. UDP: connectionless, ''unreliable'', no retransmission, used for real-time apps', 'TCP (Transmission Control Protocol) establishes a formal connection, guarantees delivery with acknowledgments, manages out-of-order messages, and controls flow. UDP (User Datagram Protocol) is connectionless with no formal open/close, no error recovery or retransmission. UDP is preferred for real-time communication (streaming, gaming, VoIP) where retransmission would be worse than missing data.'), (21, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.8 Network Environments', 'Which network architecture allows for access or sharing of resources in a network by the same host? (A) Peer-to-peer (B) Client-server (C) LAN (D) Hybrid topology', 'A. Peer-to-peer', 'Peer-to-peer architecture allows the same host to both access and share resources. Client-server strictly defines clients (which access) and servers (which share). LAN is a network type, not a sharing model. Hybrid topology refers to combined topologies.'), (22, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.1 Introduction to IP', 'What are non-ephemeral vs. ephemeral port numbers?', 'Non-ephemeral: ports 0–1,023 (permanent server ports); Ephemeral: ports 1,024–65,535 (temporary client ports assigned at runtime)', 'Non-ephemeral (well-known) ports 0–1,023 are permanently assigned to server services. Ephemeral ports 1,024–65,535 are temporary port numbers assigned in real-time by client applications. When your browser connects to a web server, it uses an ephemeral port as the source port for the session.'), (22, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.8 Network Environments', 'Which is the major advantage of client-server network architecture? (A) Distributed security (B) Centralized management (C) Flexibility (D) Equal access', 'B. Centralized management', 'The major advantage of client-server architecture is centralized management. Distributed security is a peer-to-peer trait. The client-server relationship is rigid, not flexible. Equal access characterizes peer-to-peer architecture.'), (23, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.1 Common Ports', 'What port does FTP use and what are its limitations?', 'tcp/20 (active mode data), tcp/21 (control) — transfers files but sends credentials in plaintext', 'FTP (File Transfer Protocol) uses port 21 for control and port 20 for active mode data. It authenticates with a username/password and supports full file management. Limitation: credentials are sent in plaintext — use SFTP or FTPS for secure transfers.'), (23, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.6 Network Topologies', 'You are setting up a network connection that requires redundancy in the event a switch or single link fails. Which topology should you select? (A) Bus (B) Ring (C) Star (D) Mesh', 'D. Mesh', 'A mesh topology provides redundancy and protects the network if a switch or link fails. Bus and ring topologies are very susceptible to failure and require a fully functioning network. A star topology by itself does not offer redundancy.'), (24, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.1 Common Ports', 'What are the port numbers for SSH, Telnet, SMTP, and DNS?', 'SSH: tcp/22 | Telnet: tcp/23 | SMTP: tcp/25 | DNS: udp/53 (also tcp/53)', 'SSH (Secure Shell) provides encrypted console access on port 22. Telnet provides unencrypted console access on port 23 — not recommended for production. SMTP (Simple Mail Transfer Protocol) transfers email between servers on port 25. DNS (Domain Name System) resolves names to IPs on UDP port 53.'), (24, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.8 Network Environments', 'Where is the full mesh topology commonly seen in the three-tier design model? (A) Core layer (B) Distribution layer (C) Access layer (D) Routing layer', 'B. Distribution layer', 'Distribution layer switches are fully meshed for redundancy. The core layer is normally implemented with a star topology. The access layer is typically a partial mesh or hybrid. "Routing layer" is not a valid term in the three-tier design model.'), (25, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.1 Common Ports', 'What are the ports for HTTP, HTTPS, POP3, and IMAP4?', 'HTTP: tcp/80 | HTTPS: tcp/443 | POP3: tcp/110 | IMAP4: tcp/143', 'HTTP (Hypertext Transfer Protocol) serves web pages on port 80. HTTPS adds TLS/SSL encryption on port 443. POP3 (Post Office Protocol v3) downloads email to a client on port 110. IMAP4 (Internet Message Access Protocol v4) manages email on the server from multiple clients on port 143.'), (25, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.8 Network Environments', 'Which connectivity method is used within a small geographic area to connect an organization together? (A) MAN (B) LAN (C) SAN (D) PAN', 'A. MAN', 'A metropolitan area network (MAN) connects an organization across a metropolitan area. A LAN connects the immediate network. A SAN is used exclusively for storage. A PAN connects personal devices within an extremely close vicinity.'), (26, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.1 Common Ports', 'What are SMB, LDAP, and RDP ports?', 'SMB: tcp/445 (also NetBIOS udp/137, tcp/139) | LDAP: tcp/389 | RDP: tcp/3389', 'SMB (Server Message Block) on tcp/445 handles Windows file/printer sharing. NetBIOS uses udp/137 for name services and tcp/139 for session services. LDAP (Lightweight Directory Access Protocol) on tcp/389 stores/retrieves directory information (Active Directory). RDP (Remote Desktop Protocol) on tcp/3389 provides graphical remote desktop access.'), (26, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.8 Network Environments', 'Which virtual network element connects multiple VMs together? (A) Hypervisor (B) vSwitch (C) Load balancer (D) NFV', 'B. vSwitch', 'A virtual switch (vSwitch) connects multiple VMs together. A hypervisor is software that shares compute, network, and storage of physical hosts. A load balancer distributes load for a service. NFV is a virtualized network function such as a router or firewall.'), (27, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.1 Common Ports', 'What port does DHCP use and what is the DORA process?', 'udp/67 (server), udp/68 (client) — DORA: Discover, Offer, Request, Acknowledge', 'DHCP uses UDP port 67 on the server and port 68 on the client. DORA: (1) Discover — client broadcasts to find a DHCP server, (2) Offer — server offers an IP address, (3) Request — client requests the offered address, (4) Acknowledge — server confirms the lease.'), (27, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.8 Network Environments', 'When you tether a cell phone to your laptops using wireless, what is this an example of? (A) SAN (B) MAN (C) CAN (D) PAN', 'D. PAN', 'A personal area network (PAN) connects personal devices within an extremely close vicinity, such as tethering a cell phone to a laptop. A SAN is exclusively for storage. A MAN spans a metropolitan area. A CAN connects multiple LANs across a small geographic area.'), (28, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.2 Wireless Network Technologies', 'What Wi-Fi generation names correspond to 802.11ac, 802.11ax, and 802.11be?', '802.11ac = Wi-Fi 5 | 802.11ax = Wi-Fi 6 / Wi-Fi 6E | 802.11be = Wi-Fi 7', 'IEEE standards are referenced both by number and generation name. 802.11ac (Wi-Fi 5) operates on 5 GHz. 802.11ax (Wi-Fi 6) operates on 2.4/5 GHz; Wi-Fi 6E extends into the 6 GHz band. 802.11be (Wi-Fi 7) is the newest generation.'), (28, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.8 Network Environments', 'What is the term used to describe the common network used to connect multiple network segments at high speed? (A) Backbone (B) WAN (C) PAN (D) Workgroup', 'A. Backbone', 'A backbone connects multiple network segments at high speed. A WAN is typically used for Internet connectivity. A PAN connects personal devices in close proximity. A workgroup is a logical grouping of computers on a LAN based on department function.'), (29, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.2 Wireless Network Technologies', 'What are the three frequency bands used by 802.11 Wi-Fi?', '2.4 GHz, 5 GHz, and 6 GHz', 'Wi-Fi operates on 2.4 GHz (longer range, more interference), 5 GHz (faster, shorter range, less interference), and 6 GHz (only with Wi-Fi 6E/7, very fast, very short range, much less congestion).'), (29, 'netplus', '2.0 Network Implementation', '2.4 Physical Installations', 'What is a smart jack as it relates to WAN connectivity? (A) Demarc (B) NFV (C) Load balancer (D) Router', 'A. Demarc', 'The demarc (demarcation point) is the term used to describe a smart jack for a service provider. NFV is a virtualized network function such as a router or firewall. A load balancer distributes load for a service. A router typically connects to the smart jack for WAN connectivity.'), (30, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.2 Wireless Network Technologies', 'What is RFID and how does it work?', 'Radio-Frequency Identification — radar-based technology that powers tags with RF energy; the tag transmits its ID back', 'RFID is used everywhere: access badges, inventory/assembly tracking, pet/animal identification, and any item that needs tracking. RF energy is transmitted to the tag; the RF powers the tag and the tag transmits its ID back. Communication can be bidirectional and some tags can be active/powered.'), (30, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.8 Network Environments', 'Which protocol is used with dynamic multipoint VPN deployments? (A) mGRE (B) MPLS (C) SDWAN (D) vNIC', 'A. mGRE', 'Multipoint Generic Routing Encapsulation (mGRE) is used with dynamic multipoint VPN to facilitate connections. MPLS uses labels to switch packets and is an alternative to DMVPN. SDWAN is a virtual WAN architecture managed by software. A vNIC connects a VM to a vSwitch.'), (31, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.3 Network Services', 'What is a proxy server and what functions does it provide?', 'Intermediate server that makes requests on behalf of clients — provides access control, caching, URL filtering, and content scanning', 'A proxy server sits between clients and servers. The client makes requests to the proxy; the proxy makes the actual request and returns results. This enables access control, caching, URL filtering, and content/malware scanning.'), (31, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.1 OSI Model', 'Flow control can be found at which layer of the OSI? (A) Transport layer (B) Network layer (C) Data Link layer (D) Session layer', 'A. Transport layer', 'The Transport layer is responsible for flow control via TCP and UDP. The Network layer handles logical addressing of network nodes. The Data Link layer frames data and provides physical addressing. The Session layer sets up dialogue between two hosts.'), (32, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.3 Network Services', 'What is an NTP server and why is accurate time important in networking?', 'Network Time Protocol server on udp/123 — time accuracy is critical for encryption, logins, backups, and log timestamps', 'NTP servers listen on UDP port 123 and respond to time requests. Accurate time is critical: encryption certificates, login authentication, backup scheduling, and log timestamps all depend on synchronized clocks. Daily synchronization is common.'), (32, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.1 OSI Model', 'What is required before TCP can begin sending segments? (A) Three-way handshake (B) Port agreement (C) Sequencing of segments (D) Acknowledgment of segments', 'A. Three-way handshake', 'A three-way handshake synchronizes window buffer sizes between sender and receiver before TCP segments are sent. Ports are not "agreed upon" — they address Transport-layer traffic. Sequencing and acknowledgment are ongoing TCP functions, not prerequisites.'), (33, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.3 Network Services', 'What is SCADA/ICS and why does it require network segmentation?', 'Supervisory Control and Data Acquisition / Industrial Control Systems — manages critical infrastructure; must be isolated from outside access', 'SCADA/ICS systems control critical infrastructure: power generation, oil refining, manufacturing, logistics. They require extensive network segmentation and no direct external access because a breach could have catastrophic real-world consequences.'), (33, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.1 OSI Model', 'Which layer of the OSI is responsible for dialogue control of applications? (A) Application layer (B) Physical layer (C) Session layer (D) Network layer', 'C. Session layer', 'The Session layer sets up dialogue between two hosts. The Application layer handles API access and begins network communication. The Physical layer transmits data over light, electricity, or radio waves. The Network layer handles logical IP addressing.'), (34, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.3 Network Services', 'What is a UTM (Unified Threat Management) appliance?', 'Next-gen firewall combining: URL filter, malware inspection, spam filter, CSU/DSU, router, switch, firewall, IDS/IPS, bandwidth shaper, VPN endpoint', 'A UTM (Unified Threat Management) or all-in-one security appliance combines many security functions: URL filtering, content inspection, malware inspection, spam filtering, routing, switching, firewall, IDS/IPS, bandwidth shaping, and VPN endpoint in one device.'), (34, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.1 OSI Model', 'Which layer is responsible for compression and decompression? (A) Application layer (B) Physical layer (C) Session layer (D) Presentation layer', 'D. Presentation layer', 'The Presentation layer handles compression/decompression and encryption/decryption. The Application layer handles API access. The Physical layer transmits data over media. The Session layer sets up dialogue between hosts.'), (35, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.4 DNS Configuration', 'What are DNS A records and AAAA records?', 'A record: maps hostname to IPv4 address | AAAA record: maps hostname to IPv6 address', 'DNS A (Address) records are the most common query type — they define the IPv4 address of a host. AAAA (quad-A) records serve the same purpose for IPv6 addresses. Both types can exist on the same DNS server for the same hostname.'), (35, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.1 OSI Model', 'Which OSI layer is responsible for logical addressing? (A) Transport layer (B) Network layer (C) Application layer (D) Data Link layer', 'B. Network layer', 'The Network layer handles logical addressing; routers use it to determine paths to remote networks. The Transport layer handles flow control and virtual circuits. The Application layer handles API access. The Data Link layer frames data and uses physical addressing.'), (36, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.4 DNS Configuration', 'What is a CNAME record?', 'Canonical Name record — an alias pointing one hostname to another hostname (not an IP)', 'A CNAME record creates an alias so one hostname points to another. For example, ''ftp.example.com'' and ''chat.example.com'' can both CNAME to ''mail.example.com''. One physical server can provide multiple services under different names.'), (36, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.1 OSI Model', 'As information travels down the network stack from the Application layer to the Physical layer, what happens? (A) Datagrams (B) PDUs (C) Encapsulation (D) Decapsulation', 'C. Encapsulation', 'Information traveling down the stack is encapsulated by each layer. Datagrams describe upper-layer data. PDU is the general term for data at any OSI layer. Decapsulation removes encapsulation as data moves up from Physical to Application.'), (37, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.4 DNS Configuration', 'What are MX, TXT, SPF, DKIM, and DMARC DNS records used for?', 'MX: mail server | TXT: text info | SPF: authorized senders | DKIM: digitally signs outgoing mail | DMARC: policy for failed SPF/DKIM validation', 'MX (Mail Exchanger) identifies the mail server. TXT stores text info used for verification. SPF lists authorized mail servers to prevent spoofing. DKIM digitally signs outgoing mail, validated by mail servers. DMARC extends SPF/DKIM — defines policy (accept/quarantine/reject) for emails that fail validation and can send compliance reports.'), (37, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.1 OSI Model', 'Which sublayer of the Data Link OSI layer is responsible for identifying Network layer protocols and encapsulating them? (A) MAC (B) LLC (C) Data Link (D) Session', 'B. LLC', 'The Logical Link Control (LLC) sublayer manages access to Network layer protocols. The Media Access Control (MAC) sublayer handles physical addressing and framing for the media. The Data Link layer itself contains LLC and MAC. The Session layer handles dialogue control.'), (38, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.4 DHCP', 'What information does a DHCP scope define?', 'IP address range, excluded addresses, subnet mask, lease duration, DNS server, default gateway, and optional VOIP servers', 'A DHCP scope is configured on the DHCP server and defines a contiguous pool of IP addresses for a subnet. It includes: IP address range with exclusions, subnet mask, lease duration, and optional settings like DNS servers, default gateway, and VOIP servers.'), (38, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.1 OSI Model', 'Which is not a benefit to the OSI model? (A) Multivendor development with a standardized model (B) Prevents a change in one layer from affecting other layers (C) Allows various network hardware and software to communicate (D) Allows software to run at network speeds', 'D. Allows software to run at network speeds', 'The OSI model does not make software run at network speeds — that is up to the developer. It does enable multivendor development via standardization, isolate changes between layers, and allow diverse hardware and software to interoperate.'), (39, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.4 DHCP', 'What is DHCP address reservation?', 'Assigns a specific IP to a device based on its MAC address — also called Static DHCP or IP Reservation', 'DHCP address reservation ensures a specific device always gets the same IP address from DHCP by mapping a MAC address to an IP address in the DHCP server. Better than manual static IPs because the address is still managed centrally.'), (39, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.1 OSI Model', 'Which three upper layers operate together? (A) Application, Presentation, and Session (B) Presentation, Session, and Transport (C) Transport, Session, and Application (D) Network, Data Link, and Physical', 'A. Application, Presentation, and Session', 'The Application, Presentation, and Session layers (Layers 7-5) operate together to process datagrams. The Transport layer is the boundary between upper and lower layers. The lower layers (Network, Data Link, Physical) handle delivery.'), (40, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.4 VLANs and VPNs', 'What is a VLAN and how does it differ from a physical LAN?', 'Virtual LAN — a broadcast domain separated logically (not physically) on a switch; one switch can support multiple isolated networks', 'A LAN is a group of devices in the same physical broadcast domain. A VLAN creates the same separation but logically via software on a single switch. One physical switch can act as multiple isolated switches, improving security and organization without extra hardware.'), (40, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.1 OSI Model', 'Which 802 working group defines the LLC sublayer of the Data Link layer? (A) 802.2 (B) 802.3 (C) 802.15 (D) 802.11', 'A. 802.2', 'IEEE 802.2 defines the Logical Link Control (LLC) sublayer. IEEE 802.3 (Ethernet) and 802.11 (Wi-Fi) define MAC sublayer specifics. IEEE 802.15 covers wireless personal area networks (WPANs).'), (41, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.4 VLANs and VPNs', 'What is the difference between a client-to-site VPN and a site-to-site VPN?', 'Client-to-site: remote user connects on-demand via VPN software. Site-to-site: always-on tunnel between two locations via VPN concentrators', 'Client-to-site VPN allows individual remote users to securely connect to a corporate network on-demand. Site-to-site VPN connects two entire networks through a permanent encrypted tunnel via VPN concentrators/firewalls — always on.'), (41, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.1 OSI Model', 'Which concept describes transmitting multiple segments before the receiving host acknowledges the data? (A) Sequencing (B) Compression (C) Windowing (D) Encryption', 'C. Windowing', 'Windowing allows multiple segments to be transmitted before requiring an acknowledgment. Sequencing tags each segment so they can be reassembled at the Transport layer. Compression and encryption are Presentation-layer functions.'), (42, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.5 Network Devices', 'What is the difference between an unmanaged switch and a managed switch?', 'Unmanaged: plug-and-play, no VLANs, no management. Managed: VLANs, traffic prioritization (QoS), STP, port mirroring, SNMP', 'Unmanaged switches are simple plug-and-play with fixed configurations — inexpensive. Managed switches support VLANs (via 802.1Q), QoS traffic prioritization, Spanning Tree Protocol (STP) for redundancy, port mirroring for packet capture, and SNMP management.'), (42, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.2 Network Appliances', 'Which device will stop broadcasts from propagating the network? (A) Router (B) Switch (C) Hub (D) WAP', 'A. Router', 'A router by default does not forward broadcasts — it bounds the broadcast domain. Switches, hubs, and wireless access points all forward broadcasts within their broadcast domain.'), (43, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.5 Network Devices', 'What is PoE and what are the power differences between PoE, PoE+, and PoE++?', 'Power over Ethernet. PoE: 15.4W/350mA | PoE+: 25.5W/600mA | PoE++ Type 3: 51W, Type 4: 71.3W/960mA', 'PoE (802.3) provides 15.4W DC, 350mA — for IP phones/cameras. PoE+ provides 25.5W, 600mA — for more power-hungry devices. PoE++ Type 3: 51W, Type 4: 71.3W at 960mA — for laptops and high-power APs. PoE+ cannot power a PoE++ device.'), (43, 'netplus', '2.0 Network Implementation', '2.1 Routing Technologies', 'Which is used to determine the best path to a destination network? (A) Acknowledgment (B) Network address (C) Interface (D) Metric', 'D. Metric', 'The metric associated with each route in the route table determines the best path. Acknowledgments confirm receipt of segments. The network address is logical host addressing. The interface is the physical connection to the network.'), (44, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.5 Network Devices', 'What is an access point and how does it differ from a wireless router?', 'Access point is a bridge extending wired network to wireless — a wireless router combines router + access point in one device', 'An access point (AP) extends the wired network onto wireless, making forwarding decisions based on MAC addresses. A wireless router combines routing (IP subnets) and an AP. A standalone AP does not route — it simply bridges wired and wireless.'), (44, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.1 OSI Model', 'Which protocol data unit (PDU) is used to describe data at the Physical layer? (A) Datagrams (B) Bits (C) Frames (D) Segments', 'B. Bits', 'Bits is the PDU at the Physical layer. Datagrams describe upper-layer data. Frames are the Data Link PDU. Segments are the Transport PDU.'), (45, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.5 Network Devices', 'What is an ONT and what is its purpose?', 'Optical Network Terminal — connects ISP fiber to premises copper network; demarcation point between ISP and customer', 'An ONT connects the ISP''s fiber optic network to the customer''s copper/Ethernet network. It''s typically a box on the side of the building. One side belongs to the ISP; the other side belongs to the customer. It is the demarcation point (demarc) between ISP and customer responsibility.'), (45, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.1 OSI Model', 'Which OSI layers are responsible for framing data and transmitting the data? (A) LLC and Physical layers (B) Data Link and Physical layers (C) Network and Transport layers (D) Session and Transport layers', 'B. Data Link and Physical layers', 'The Data Link layer frames data and the Physical layer transmits it on the media. LLC is a sublayer of Data Link, not a peer layer. The other combinations do not handle framing or media transmission.'), (46, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.6 IPv4 and IPv6', 'What are the three RFC 1918 private IPv4 address ranges?', '10.0.0.0/8 (16.7M addresses) | 172.16.0.0/12 (1M addresses) | 192.168.0.0/16 (65,536 addresses)', 'RFC 1918 private ranges not routable on the public internet: Class A: 10.0.0.0–10.255.255.255, Class B: 172.16.0.0–172.31.255.255, Class C: 192.168.0.0–192.168.255.255. NAT is required to communicate with the internet from these ranges.'), (46, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.1 OSI Model', 'Which layer is responsible for creating a virtual circuit? (A) Presentation (B) Session (C) Transport (D) Network', 'C. Transport', 'The Transport layer handles flow control and creates virtual circuits (e.g., TCP). The Presentation layer handles compression and encryption. The Session layer handles dialogue control. The Network layer handles logical addressing.'), (47, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.6 IPv4 and IPv6', 'How does IPv6 addressing differ from IPv4?', 'IPv6 is 128-bit (vs IPv4''s 32-bit), written in hex groups — 340 undecillion addresses. First 64 bits = network prefix, last 64 bits = host', 'IPv4 uses 32-bit addresses (4.29 billion total — not enough). IPv6 uses 128-bit addresses providing 340 undecillion addresses. Written as eight groups of four hex digits separated by colons. The first 64 bits are the network prefix (/64) and the last 64 bits are the host address.'), (47, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.1 OSI Model', 'TCP and UDP reside at which layer of the OSI model? (A) Physical (B) Session (C) Network (D) Transport', 'D. Transport', 'Both TCP and UDP are Transport-layer (Layer 4) protocols. Physical handles bit transmission, Session handles dialogue control, and Network handles logical addressing.'), (48, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.6 Assigning IP Addresses', 'What is APIPA and when does it activate?', 'Automatic Private IP Addressing — assigns 169.254.x.x when DHCP is unavailable; link-local only (not routable)', 'APIPA automatically assigns an IP from 169.254.1.0–169.254.254.255 when no DHCP server responds. APIPA addresses are link-local — routers cannot forward them. Seeing a 169.254.x.x address usually indicates a DHCP problem.'), (48, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.1 OSI Model', 'What is the proper order of data encapsulation? (A) Datagram, segment, packet, frame, bits (B) Bits, frame, packet, segment, datagram (C) Segment, datagram, packet, frame, bits (D) Datagram, packet, segment, frame, bits', 'A. Datagram, segment, packet, frame, bits', 'Encapsulation moves top-down: datagram (upper layers) → segment (Transport) → packet (Network) → frame (Data Link) → bits (Physical).'), (49, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.6 Assigning IP Addresses', 'What is NAT (Network Address Translation) and why is it needed?', 'Translates private IP addresses to a public IP for internet communication — conserves IPv4 addresses and hides internal network structure', 'NAT allows many devices with private IP addresses to share a single public IP address. The router replaces the private source IP with the public IP and tracks sessions to return traffic correctly. PAT (Port Address Translation) is the most common form, using port numbers to track individual sessions.'), (49, 'netplus', '2.0 Network Implementation', '2.1 Routing Technologies', 'Which layer is responsible for routing data packets? (A) Physical (B) Data Link (C) Transport (D) Network', 'D. Network', 'The Network layer routes packets between networks. The Physical layer transmits bits. The Data Link layer frames bits for the local segment. The Transport layer handles virtual circuits and flow control.'), (50, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.7 Internet Connection Types', 'What are the characteristics of DSL internet?', 'Digital Subscriber Line over telephone lines — asymmetric (~200 Mbps down / 20 Mbps up), limited to ~10,000 feet from central office', 'DSL uses existing telephone lines for broadband internet. It''s asymmetric: download is faster than upload. Common speeds ~200 Mbps downstream / 20 Mbps upstream. Has a ~10,000-foot distance limitation from the central office — speeds improve if you''re closer to the CO.'), (50, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.1 OSI Model', 'Which IEEE standard specifies the protocol for CSMA/CD? (A) 802.2 (B) 802.3 (C) 802.5 (D) 802.11', 'B. 802.3', 'IEEE 802.3 (Ethernet) specifies CSMA/CD as its contention method. IEEE 802.2 specifies LLC encapsulation. IEEE 802.5 was the now-disbanded Token Ring spec. IEEE 802.11 covers wireless networking.'), (51, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.7 Internet Connection Types', 'What is satellite internet and what are its limitations?', 'Non-terrestrial internet via orbiting satellites — ~100 Mbps down / 5 Mbps up, high latency (~250ms traditional, 25-60ms Starlink), rain fade, line-of-sight', 'Satellite networking communicates with orbiting satellites. Traditional geostationary satellites have ~250ms latency. Starlink (LEO) advertises 25–60ms latency. Limitations: high cost, high latency, line-of-sight requirement, rain fade, and difficult remote sites.'), (52, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.7 Internet Connection Types', 'What is a WISP (Wireless Internet Service Provider)?', 'Terrestrial wireless internet for rural/remote areas — uses meshed 802.11, 5G home internet, or proprietary wireless; needs outdoor antenna', 'A WISP provides internet access using wireless technology for areas where cable/fiber is unavailable. Technologies: meshed 802.11, 5G home internet, proprietary wireless. Requires an outdoor antenna. Speeds range from ~10 to 1,000 Mbps.'), (53, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.7 Network Types', 'What are LAN, WAN, MAN, PAN, SAN, and WLAN?', 'LAN: local building | WAN: wide area/globe | MAN: metropolitan/city | PAN: personal (Bluetooth/NFC) | SAN: storage area network | WLAN: wireless LAN (802.11)', 'LAN: high-speed in a building. WAN: spans the globe. MAN: covers a city. PAN: your own private network (Bluetooth, NFC). SAN: block-level storage access for high efficiency. WLAN: wireless 802.11 within a building or limited area.'), (54, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.8 Network Tools', 'What is a cable crimper used for?', 'Attaches modular connectors to cable — metal prongs pushed through insulation; use correct connectors and maintain twists to termination', 'A cable crimper permanently attaches a modular connector to a cable. Metal prongs are pushed through insulation and the plug is pressed onto the cable sheath. Best practices: use quality tools, use correct connectors for the wire type, and maintain cable twists as close to the connector as possible.'), (55, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.8 Network Tools', 'What is a tone generator and inductive probe used for?', 'Traces cable paths — generator puts signal on wire, inductive probe detects tone without touching copper', 'A tone generator and probe identifies which cable goes where. The generator puts an analog tone on the wire; the inductive probe detects the tone without touching the copper. Essential for cable tracing in complex environments with many unlabeled cables.'), (56, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.8 Network Tools', 'What does a loopback plug do?', 'Tests physical ports by looping output back as input — available for Serial/RS-232, Ethernet, T1, and fiber', 'A loopback plug connects the output signal back to the input of the same port to verify the port functions correctly. Common types: Serial (DB9/DB25), Ethernet (RJ45), T1, and Fiber. They are NOT crossover cables.'), (57, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.1 Display Types', 'What are the differences between TN, IPS, and VA LCD panels?', 'TN: fastest response (gaming), poor viewing angles. IPS: excellent color/wide angles, more expensive. VA: good color, compromise between TN/IPS, slower response', 'TN (Twisted Nematic): fast response times for gaming but poor viewing angles and color shifts. IPS (In Plane Switching): excellent color and wide viewing angles but more expensive. VA (Vertical Alignment): good compromise with good color representation but often slower response times than TN.'), (58, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.1 Display Types', 'What is OLED and how does it differ from LCD?', 'Organic Light-Emitting Diode — each pixel emits its own light (no backlight), thinner, flexible, accurate color, used in phones/tablets/smartwatches', 'OLED pixels emit their own light via organic compounds — no backlight needed. This makes OLED thinner, lighter, flexible, and provides very accurate colors with deep blacks (pixel turns off completely). Higher cost than LCD. Common in smartphones, tablets, and smartwatches.'), (59, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.1 Display Attributes', 'What is display refresh rate and why does it matter?', 'Frames displayed per second (Hz) — movies: 24fps, TV: 30fps, gaming: 60fps+; HDMI 2.1 supports 4K@144Hz', 'Refresh rate determines how many images are shown per second. Higher rates reduce motion blur — important for gaming. HDMI 2.1 supports 4K at 144Hz; DisplayPort 2.1 supports dual 4K at 144Hz. The maximum is determined by both the video adapter and the display.'), (60, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.2 Network Cables', 'What cable categories support 1GbE and 10GbE, and what are the max distances?', '1GbE: Cat5/Cat5e at 100m | 10GbE: Cat6 at 55m(UTP)/100m(STP), Cat6A at 100m', '1000BASE-T (1 GbE) requires minimum Cat5 or Cat5e at 100 meters. 10GBASE-T (10 GbE) requires Cat6 (55m unshielded, 100m shielded) or Cat6A/augmented at 100m.'), (61, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.2 Network Cables', 'What is the difference between UTP and STP cabling?', 'UTP: no shielding, most common. STP: foil/braided shielding against EMI, requires grounding', 'UTP is the most common twisted pair — no additional shielding. STP adds shielding around pairs and/or the entire cable to protect against EMI. STP requires proper grounding. Abbreviations: U=Unshielded, S=Braided shielding, F=Foil shielding.'), (62, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.2 Network Cables', 'What is plenum-rated cable and when is it required?', 'Fire-rated cable using FEP or low-smoke PVC — required in air circulation spaces (plenum areas like drop ceilings) per building codes', 'Plenum-rated cable uses FEP (Fluorinated Ethylene Polymer) or low-smoke PVC that resists burning and doesn''t emit toxic smoke. Required by building codes when running cable through plenum spaces (areas used for air circulation). May be less flexible with a different bend radius.'), (63, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.2 568A and 568B Colors', 'What are the TIA/EIA 568B pin color assignments?', '1:W-Orange, 2:Orange, 3:W-Green, 4:Blue, 5:W-Blue, 6:Green, 7:W-Brown, 8:Brown', '568B (most common in North America): Pin 1: White/Orange, 2: Orange, 3: White/Green, 4: Blue, 5: White/Blue, 6: Green, 7: White/Brown, 8: Brown. 568A swaps orange and green pairs. Both ends must use the same standard — mixing 568A and 568B does NOT create a crossover cable.'), (64, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.2 Optical Fiber', 'What is the difference between multimode and single-mode fiber?', 'Multimode: up to 2km, LED, inexpensive. Single-mode: up to 100km, laser, expensive', 'Multimode fiber has a larger core, uses an inexpensive LED light source, and is limited to ~2km. Single-mode fiber has a smaller core, uses an expensive laser light source, and supports up to 100km without signal processing. Fiber is immune to radio interference and very difficult to tap.'), (65, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.2 Fiber Connectors', 'What are the three main fiber optic connector types?', 'ST: bayonet/push-and-twist | SC: push-to-lock, popular in data centers | LC: smaller/compact, clips in', 'ST (Straight Tip): bayonet push-and-turn connector. SC (Subscriber Connector): push-on, pull-to-unlock, very common in data centers. LC (Lucent Connector): smaller and more compact than SC, locks with a clip, press-to-release.'), (66, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.2 Peripheral Cables', 'What are the USB versions and their maximum speeds?', 'USB 1.1: 1.5/12 Mbps | USB 2.0: 480 Mbps | USB 3.2 Gen 1: 5 Gbps | USB 3.2 Gen 2: 10 Gbps | USB 3.2 Gen 2×2: 20 Gbps | USB4 Gen 2×2: 20 Gbps | USB4 Gen 3×2: 40 Gbps', 'USB 1.1: Low/Full speed (1.5/12 Mbps). USB 2.0: 480 Mbps. USB 3.2 Gen 1 (formerly USB 3.0): 5 Gbps. USB 3.2 Gen 2 (formerly USB 3.1): 10 Gbps. USB 3.2 Gen 2×2: 20 Gbps (USB-C only). USB4 Gen 2×2: 20 Gbps (USB-C, requires TB3/4 controller). USB4 Gen 3×2: 40 Gbps — same speed as Thunderbolt 3/4, requires USB-C. USB-C is a physical connector shape only; check device specs for actual USB version.'), (67, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.2 Peripheral Cables', 'What is Thunderbolt and how has it evolved through versions 1–5?', 'High-speed serial connector. TB1/2: Mini DP, 20Gbps | TB3: 40Gbps, USB-C | TB4: 40Gbps, USB-C, stricter requirements | TB5: 120Gbps (80Gbps base), USB-C, PCIe 5.0', 'Thunderbolt 1: 20 Gbps, Mini DisplayPort. TB2: 20 Gbps aggregated, Mini DP. TB3: 40 Gbps, USB-C connector, up to 6 daisy-chained devices. TB4: 40 Gbps, USB-C, dual 4K or single 8K display, mandatory PCIe 4.0 tunneling — stricter certification than TB3. TB5 (2024+): 80 Gbps base / 120 Gbps burst, USB-C, PCIe 5.0 tunneling, supports up to 240W power delivery, required for latest eGPU and high-bandwidth displays.'), (68, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.2 Video Cables', 'What are HDMI, DisplayPort, DVI, and VGA?', 'HDMI: 19-pin digital audio+video, ~20m | DisplayPort: packetized digital A+V, locking | DVI: digital/analog video, no audio | VGA: DB-15 analog only, degrades 5-10m', 'HDMI: 19-pin Type A, carries digital audio and video, ~20m signal range. DisplayPort: packetized A/V, compatible with HDMI/DVI via passive adapter, may have locking mechanism. DVI: single link (3.7 Gbps)/dual link (7.4 Gbps), no audio. VGA: DB-15 blue analog connector, video only, degrades after 5-10m.'), (69, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.2 Storage Cables', 'What are the SATA revision speeds?', 'SATA 1.0: 1.5 Gbps | SATA 2.0: 3.0 Gbps | SATA 3.0: 6.0 Gbps | SATA 3.2: 16 Gbps | eSATA: matches version, 2m, different connector', 'SATA revisions: 1.0 = 1.5 Gbps, 2.0 = 3.0 Gbps, 3.0 = 6.0 Gbps (most common), 3.2 = 16 Gbps, all with 1-meter cable limit. eSATA (external) matches SATA version speed, uses 2-meter cables, physically different connectors. Each SATA device uses one power and one data cable.'), (70, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.2 Copper Connectors', 'What are RJ11, RJ45, and F-connectors used for?', 'RJ11: 6P2C telephone/DSL | RJ45: 8P8C Ethernet | F-connector: RG-6 coax for cable TV/DOCSIS', 'RJ11 is a 6-position, 2-conductor modular connector for telephone and DSL. RJ45 is 8-position, 8-conductor for Ethernet. F-connector is threaded coaxial for cable television, cable modems, and DOCSIS.'), (71, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.2 Copper Connectors', 'What is a Molex connector used for?', '4-pin peripheral power connector providing +12V and +5V — powers storage devices, optical drives, fans, and other peripherals inside the PC case', 'The Molex connector (from Molex Connector Company, also called AMP MATE-N-LOK) is a 4-pin power connector inside the computer case. It provides +12V and +5V to storage devices, optical drives, fans, and other peripherals.'), (72, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.2 Adapters and Converters', 'What is the difference between an adapter and a converter?', 'Adapter: electrically compatible connector change (passive) — e.g., DVI-D to HDMI. Converter: changes signal format (active) — e.g., VGA analog to DVI digital', 'An adapter simply changes the physical connector — DVI-D and HDMI are electrically compatible so a passive adapter works. A converter changes the actual signal format, requiring active electronics (e.g., VGA analog to DVI digital conversion).'), (73, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.3 Memory Overview', 'What is DRAM and why does it need constant refreshing?', 'Dynamic Random Access Memory — stores data as charges in capacitors that leak; must be constantly refreshed or data is lost', 'DRAM stores data in capacitors that slowly leak charge. The memory controller must constantly refresh every cell or the data disappears. ''Random access'' means any storage location can be accessed directly.'), (74, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.3 Memory Technologies', 'What are the key differences between DDR3, DDR4, and DDR5 RAM?', 'DDR3: max 16GB/DIMM | DDR4: faster, max 64GB/DIMM | DDR5: fastest, max 64GB/DIMM, on-die ECC, new key position — none are interchangeable', 'DDR3 max 16GB/DIMM. DDR4 increases speed and max capacity to 64GB/DIMM. DDR5 provides faster data transfers with 64GB/DIMM max, on-die ECC, and a moved key (notch). Each generation has no backwards compatibility — none are interchangeable.'), (75, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.3 Memory Technologies', 'What is ECC memory and when is it used?', 'Error Correcting Code — detects and corrects single-bit errors on-the-fly; used in servers, VMs, and database systems requiring data integrity', 'ECC memory adds extra bits to detect and automatically correct single-bit errors. Parity memory only detects errors but cannot correct them. ECC requires motherboard/CPU support and looks identical to non-ECC physically. Used in critical systems where data integrity is paramount.'), (76, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.3 Memory Technologies', 'What is multi-channel memory and how does it improve performance?', 'Two or more independent memory buses operating simultaneously — dual-channel doubles bandwidth; modules should be identical pairs in color-coded slots', 'Multi-channel memory runs multiple modules in parallel, widening the effective memory bus. Dual-channel uses two 64-bit buses simultaneously (128-bit total), doubling throughput. Modules should be identical (exact matches are best) and installed in color-coded paired slots.'), (77, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.4 Storage Devices', 'What is NVMe and why is it faster than SATA for SSDs?', 'Non-Volatile Memory Express — designed for SSDs using PCIe bus; lower latency and higher throughput than SATA''s AHCI limit of 600 MB/s', 'SATA was designed for HDDs using AHCI, limited to ~600 MB/s. NVMe was designed specifically for SSDs using the PCIe Express bus, supporting much lower latency and higher throughput. Often connects via M.2 interface.'), (78, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.4 Storage Devices', 'What is the M.2 interface and what are B-key and M-key?', 'Compact SSD form factor with no separate cables — B-key and M-key are connector notch types; M.2 doesn''t guarantee NVMe (may still use AHCI)', 'M.2 connects directly to the motherboard with no power or data cables. Can use PCIe (NVMe, 4+ GB/s) or SATA signals. Key type (B-key, M-key, or both) describes the physical connector notch. Important: M.2 does NOT guarantee NVMe — verify with documentation.'), (79, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.4 RAID', 'What are RAID 0, RAID 1, RAID 5, and RAID 6?', 'RAID 0: striping (fast, zero redundancy) | RAID 1: mirroring (full redundancy, 2x space) | RAID 5: striping+parity (3+ disks, 1 failure ok) | RAID 6: 2 parity (4+ disks, 2 failures ok)', 'RAID 0: high performance, no redundancy — one failure destroys the array. RAID 1: every file duplicated — high redundancy, doubles required disk space. RAID 5: blocks striped with distributed parity across 3+ disks — efficient, survives one failure. RAID 6: adds second parity block, needs 4+ disks, survives two simultaneous failures.'), (80, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.4 RAID', 'What is RAID 1+0 (RAID 10) and what does it require?', 'A stripe of mirrors — combines RAID 0 speed with RAID 1 redundancy; requires minimum 4 drives. RAID is NOT backup.', 'RAID 10 first creates RAID 1 mirror pairs, then stripes across them (RAID 0), giving both speed and redundancy. Requires 4+ drives. Critical reminder: RAID protects against drive failure only — it does NOT protect against accidental deletion, fire, or ransomware.'), (81, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.5 Motherboard Form Factors', 'What are ATX, microATX, and ITX motherboard form factors?', 'ATX: full-size (Intel 1995), 24-pin power | microATX: smaller, fewer slots, backward-compatible | Mini-ITX: low-power, small, fits any ATX case', 'ATX (Advanced Technology Extended) is the full-size Intel standard from 1995, 24-pin power. microATX (uATX/M-ATX) is smaller with fewer expansion slots but compatible mounting/power — very popular. Mini-ITX is a low-power small form factor, screw-compatible with ATX, used in media centers and compact systems.'), (82, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.5 Motherboard Expansion Slots', 'What is PCIe and how do its versions differ?', 'Peripheral Component Interconnect Express — serial x1/x4/x8/x16 lanes. PCIe 3.0: ~1 GB/s/lane | PCIe 4.0: ~2 GB/s/lane | PCIe 5.0: ~4 GB/s/lane | PCIe 6.0: ~8 GB/s/lane', 'PCIe uses independent serial lanes (x1, x4, x8, x16). Version bandwidth per lane: PCIe 3.0 ≈ 1 GB/s (x16 = 16 GB/s), PCIe 4.0 ≈ 2 GB/s (x16 = 32 GB/s), PCIe 5.0 ≈ 4 GB/s (x16 = 64 GB/s), PCIe 6.0 ≈ 8 GB/s. Cards are backward/forward compatible — a PCIe 5.0 NVMe SSD in a PCIe 3.0 slot runs at PCIe 3.0 speed. PCIe 5.0 slots are on current Intel/AMD platforms and used by the latest NVMe SSDs and GPUs.'), (83, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.5 The BIOS', 'What is the difference between Legacy BIOS and UEFI BIOS?', 'Legacy BIOS: 25+ years old, 16-bit, limited hardware support. UEFI: modern, graphical+text, Secure Boot, large drive support (GPT), faster boot', 'Legacy BIOS initializes hardware, runs POST, finds boot loader — limited modern drivers. UEFI (Unified Extensible Firmware Interface) replaces legacy BIOS, supports graphical interfaces, Secure Boot, GPT drives over 2TB, and faster boot times.'), (84, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.5 BIOS Settings', 'What is Secure Boot and how does it protect a system?', 'UEFI feature that digitally signs known-good software — prevents unsigned/malicious bootloaders from running; verifies OS bootloader signature', 'Secure Boot is part of UEFI. The BIOS includes the manufacturer''s public key, checks digital signatures during updates, and prevents unauthorized flash writes. At boot, it verifies the OS bootloader''s digital signature — must be signed with a trusted certificate or manually approved signature.'), (85, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.5 BIOS Settings', 'What is the CMOS battery and what happens when it fails?', 'Small ''button'' battery maintaining BIOS settings — when it fails, date/time and BIOS config resets every boot', 'CMOS memory stores BIOS configuration and is backed by a small battery. When the battery fails, settings are lost on every shutdown — date/time resets, custom BIOS configurations are gone. Replace the battery to fix. Settings can also be reset with a jumper.'), (86, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.5 HSM and TPM', 'What is a TPM and what security features does it provide?', 'Trusted Platform Module — cryptographic processor with unique device key, random number generator, enables per-device encryption (BitLocker) and Secure Boot', 'TPM is a cryptographic processor on the motherboard. It includes random number generators, key generators, a unique secret key not available outside the device, and persistent/versatile memory. It links encryption to a specific computer — you can''t move an encrypted drive to another machine without the TPM key.'), (87, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.5 HSM and TPM', 'What is an HSM and how does it differ from a TPM?', 'Hardware Security Module — enterprise-grade crypto hardware for many systems (vs TPM which is per-device); protects CA keys in data centers', 'While TPM is used on a single system for device encryption, HSM is used in large environments to secure data across many systems. HSMs are often deployed as plug-in cards or separate hardware in data centers. They perform cryptographic functions for other devices and protect the Certificate Authority key.'), (88, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.5 CPU Features', 'What is the difference between 32-bit and 64-bit processors?', '32-bit: max 4GB RAM (2^32 values). 64-bit: up to 17 billion GB RAM (2^64 values). 64-bit OS runs both 32-bit and 64-bit apps.', '32-bit processors can address only 4GB max RAM. 64-bit processors support 2^64 values — vastly more addressable memory. A 64-bit OS can run both 32-bit (installed to Program Files (x86)) and 64-bit applications. A 32-bit OS cannot run 64-bit apps.'), (89, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.5 CPU Features', 'What is ARM architecture and where is it used in modern computing?', 'Advanced RISC Machine — simplified instruction set, low power, low heat; used in mobile, IoT, and now mainstream laptops (Apple M-series, Qualcomm Snapdragon X)', 'ARM uses Reduced Instruction Set Computing (RISC): simplified instructions, highly efficient per watt. ARM Ltd. licenses designs to manufacturers. Used in: all smartphones/tablets, IoT devices, Apple Silicon (M1–M4), Qualcomm Snapdragon X Elite for Windows laptops, AWS Graviton servers. ARM64 (AArch64) is the 64-bit instruction set. Key exam point: ARM-based Windows laptops run x64 apps via emulation and native ARM64 apps natively.'), (90, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.5 Cooling', 'What is thermal paste and how should it be applied?', 'Thermally conductive adhesive between CPU and heat sink — fills microscopic gaps to improve heat transfer; apply pea-sized amount', 'Thermal paste fills microscopic surface imperfections between the CPU heat spreader and heat sink, eliminating insulating air gaps. Apply a pea-sized amount in the center — it spreads when the heat sink is pressed down. Too much can be as problematic as too little.'), (91, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.6 Computer Power', 'What voltages does a computer power supply output and what uses each?', '+12V: PCIe/drives/fans | +5V: motherboard components | +3.3V: M.2/RAM/logic | -12V: legacy LAN/serial | +5VSB: standby power', '+12V: PCIe adapters, drive motors, cooling fans, most modern components. +5V: some motherboard components. +3.3V: M.2 slots, RAM slots, logic circuits. -12V: integrated LAN, older serial ports. +5VSB (standby): maintains power when system is ''off'' so the power button works.'), (92, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.6 Computer Power', 'What is the US vs Europe electrical standard and why does it matter for PSUs?', 'US/Canada: 120V AC, 60Hz | Europe: 220-240V AC, 50Hz — plugging 120V PSU into 230V will destroy it', 'US/Canada uses 110-120 VAC at 60 Hz. Europe uses 220-240 VAC at 50 Hz. Power supplies must match the local voltage. Dual-voltage PSUs switch automatically or manually. NEVER plug a 120V PSU into a 230V outlet.'), (93, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.6 Computer Power', 'What is a modular power supply?', 'PSU where cables are added only as needed — fewer unused wires, better airflow, easier cable management; more expensive than fixed PSUs', 'Fixed PSUs have all cables permanently attached — may have too many unused cables. Modular PSUs let you connect only needed cables (24-pin, PCIe, SATA, etc.), reducing clutter, improving airflow, and making installation easier. The trade-off is higher cost.'), (94, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.6 Computer Power', 'What is a redundant power supply and what does hot-swappable mean?', 'Two+ PSUs each capable of 100% load (normally at 50%) — hot-swappable means replacing a failed PSU without powering down', 'Redundant PSUs are used in servers where downtime is unacceptable. Each PSU can handle full load; normally they share (running ~50% each for efficiency). If one fails, the other takes full load. Hot-swappable means pulling and replacing the failed PSU while the server keeps running.'), (95, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.7 Multifunction Devices', 'What is the difference between PCL and PostScript printer languages?', 'PCL (Printer Command Language): HP-created, widely used. PostScript: Adobe-created, high-end printers — driver must match printer language', 'PCL (Printer Command Language) was created by Hewlett-Packard and is used across the industry. PostScript was created by Adobe and is popular with high-end printers. The driver must match the printer language — mismatched drivers produce garbage output.'), (96, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.7 Multifunction Devices', 'What printer security features are available on modern MFDs?', 'User authentication, badging (badge-to-print), audit logs (event viewer), secured prints (passcode held at printer)', 'Modern MFD security: Authentication ensures only authorized users manage the printer. Badging holds print jobs until the employee taps a badge — prevents sensitive documents sitting in the tray. Audit logs track usage (cost management, security). Secured prints hold the job until a passcode is entered at the printer.'), (97, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.8 Laser Printer Maintenance', 'What are the six steps of the laser printing process?', '1-Charging (drum negatively charged) → 2-Exposing (laser neutralizes charge) → 3-Developing (toner sticks) → 4-Transferring (toner to paper) → 5-Fusing (heat+pressure) → 6-Cleaning (drum cleaned)', 'Laser process: (1) Charging: corona wire/roller gives drum uniform negative charge. (2) Exposing: laser neutralizes charge in image pattern. (3) Developing: negatively charged toner sticks to neutralized areas. (4) Transferring: toner transferred from drum to paper. (5) Fusing: heat and pressure permanently bond toner to paper. (6) Cleaning: drum cleaned for next cycle.'), (98, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.8 Laser Printer Maintenance', 'What is included in a laser printer maintenance kit and when should it be performed?', 'Replacement feed rollers, new fuser unit, etc. — based on page counter; power down first (fuser units are HOT); reset page counter after', 'Standard maintenance kits replace feed rollers, fuser unit, and other wear items. Check the printer''s page counter to know when maintenance is due. Power down before replacing the fuser — it operates at very high temperatures. Reset the page counter after maintenance is complete.'), (99, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.8 Inkjet Printers', 'What are the advantages and disadvantages of inkjet printers?', 'Pros: inexpensive, quiet, high-resolution. Cons: expensive proprietary ink, output eventually fades, clogs easily', 'Inkjet printers are relatively inexpensive and quiet with high-resolution output. Disadvantages: proprietary ink cartridges are expensive, printed output eventually fades, and tiny nozzles clog easily if not used regularly. Uses CMYK (Cyan, Magenta, Yellow, Key/Black) cartridges.'), (100, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.8 Thermal Printers', 'How does a thermal printer work and where is it commonly used?', 'Heat-sensitive thermal paper turns black when heated — no ink needed; used in cash registers and credit card terminals; paper sensitive to light/heat', 'Thermal printers use heat to activate specially coated thermal paper — no ink, toner, or ribbons. A full-length heating element (no moving print head) creates the image. Very quiet. Common in cash registers and credit card terminals. Disadvantage: paper is sensitive to light and heat, and output fades over time.'), (101, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.8 Impact Printers', 'What is a dot-matrix (impact) printer best suited for and what are its characteristics?', 'Best for carbon/multi-part forms — pins hit ribbon to mark paper; low cost/page, NOISY, poor graphics; uses tractor feed for continuous paper', 'Dot-matrix printers use pins pressing against a ribbon to impact multiple sheets — ideal for carbon copies/multipart forms. Advantages: good for carbon copies, low cost per page. Disadvantages: very noisy, poor graphics quality. Uses tractor feed (holes on paper sides) for continuous forms.'), (102, 'core1', '4.0 Virtualization & Cloud', '4.1 Virtualization Concepts', 'What is a sandbox in virtualization?', 'Isolated virtual environment with no connection to production — safe space for development, testing, and running untrusted code with rollback capability', 'A sandbox is an isolated testing environment with no connection to production. Developers can try/break code and roll back to snapshots without consequences. Used for software development, security research, testing application compatibility, and running legacy software.'), (103, 'core1', '4.0 Virtualization & Cloud', '4.1 Virtualization Services', 'What is the difference between a Type 1 and Type 2 hypervisor?', 'Type 1 (Bare Metal): runs directly on hardware — VMware ESXi, Hyper-V, Xen. Type 2 (Hosted): runs on top of existing OS — VMware Workstation, VirtualBox, Parallels', 'Type 1 (Bare Metal): hypervisor installs directly on hardware, best performance, used in enterprise data centers. Type 2 (Hosted): runs as an application on an existing OS (Windows/macOS/Linux), easier for personal/testing use. Examples: VirtualBox, VMware Workstation, Parallels Desktop.'), (104, 'core1', '4.0 Virtualization & Cloud', '4.1 Virtualization Services', 'What CPU technologies support virtualization?', 'Intel Virtualization Technology (VT) or AMD Virtualization (AMD-V) — must be enabled in BIOS/UEFI', 'Hardware virtualization support is required for efficient VM performance. Intel calls it Intel VT; AMD calls it AMD-V. Must be enabled in BIOS/UEFI. Resource requirements: CPU with virtualization support, memory beyond host OS needs, disk space per guest OS, and configurable virtual networking.'), (105, 'core1', '4.0 Virtualization & Cloud', '4.1 Virtualization Services', 'What is VM escaping and why is it a security concern?', 'Malware in a VM detects virtualization, compromises the hypervisor, and jumps to another guest OS or host — can expose all VMs on the same host', 'VM escaping is when malware exploits a hypervisor vulnerability to move from one VM to another or to the host. This is a critical concern in multi-tenant cloud environments where multiple customers share the same physical hardware — malware on one VM could potentially access another customer''s data.'), (106, 'core1', '4.0 Virtualization & Cloud', '4.1 Virtualization Services', 'What is VDI (Virtual Desktop Infrastructure)?', 'Applications run on a remote server (Desktop as a Service) — minimal client hardware; requires strong network connectivity since everything runs across the wire', 'VDI runs applications on a remote server. The client only needs to display output (DaaS). Benefits: minimal client hardware requirements, centralized management, easy updates. Drawback: requires reliable network — everything happens across the connection.'), (107, 'core1', '4.0 Virtualization & Cloud', '4.2 Cloud Models', 'What are the four cloud deployment models?', 'Private: own virtualized data center | Public: over internet (AWS/Azure) | Hybrid: mix of public+private | Community: shared by organizations', 'Private: your own virtualized data center — full control, pay everything upfront. Public: available to everyone (AWS, Azure, GCP) — third-party infrastructure, metered or upfront cost. Hybrid: combination of public and private. Community: multiple organizations with common interests share resources.'), (108, 'core1', '4.0 Virtualization & Cloud', '4.2 Cloud Models', 'What are IaaS, PaaS, and SaaS?', 'IaaS: you manage VMs/OS/apps (AWS EC2) | PaaS: provider manages platform, you develop (SalesForce) | SaaS: fully managed apps (Gmail, Microsoft 365)', 'IaaS (Infrastructure as a Service): you outsource hardware but manage OS, apps, and security. PaaS (Platform as a Service): provider manages infrastructure and platform — you handle development only. SaaS (Software as a Service): fully on-demand software, no installation needed (Google Mail, Microsoft 365).'), (109, 'core1', '4.0 Virtualization & Cloud', '4.2 Cloud Characteristics', 'What are the key characteristics of cloud computing?', 'Elasticity (scale instantly), Availability (always-on/redundant), File synchronization (multi-location data), Multitenancy (shared infrastructure), Metered or non-metered billing', 'Cloud characteristics: Elasticity — scale resources up/down instantly. Availability — redundancy keeps systems always available. File synchronization — data duplicated across cloud locations. Multitenancy — many clients share the same underlying infrastructure. Billing can be metered (pay per use) or non-metered (flat block rate).'), (110, 'core1', '5.0 Troubleshooting', '5.1 Troubleshooting Hardware', 'What is POST and what does it test?', 'Power-On Self Test — BIOS tests CPU, CMOS, video, and memory before booting OS; failures signaled by beep codes or LED indicators', 'POST runs when the computer is powered on. BIOS tests major system components: CPU, CMOS, video, and memory. Failures noted with beep codes and/or status codes (vary by BIOS manufacturer). A successful POST passes control to the boot loader to start the OS.'), (111, 'core1', '5.0 Troubleshooting', '5.1 Troubleshooting Hardware', 'What does a BSOD indicate and how do you troubleshoot it?', 'Windows Stop Error — bad hardware/drivers/application; info in event log; try Last Known Good, System Restore, Safe Mode, rollback driver, or run hardware diagnostics', 'A BSOD (Blue Screen of Death) indicates a critical system failure. Diagnostic info is also written to the event log. Troubleshooting: Last Known Good Configuration, System Restore, Rollback Driver, Safe Mode. If hardware-related, reseat or remove the hardware. Run manufacturer/BIOS hardware diagnostics.'), (112, 'core1', '5.0 Troubleshooting', '5.1 Troubleshooting Hardware', 'What causes unusual computer noises and what does each indicate?', 'Rattling: loose components | Scraping: hard drive issues (backup immediately!) | Clicking: fan problems | Popping: blown capacitor', 'Computers should hum — any other sound warrants investigation. Rattling: loose components inside. Scraping: hard drive head/platter issues — back up immediately. Clicking: failing fan bearing. Popping: blown capacitor on motherboard or component.'), (113, 'core1', '5.0 Troubleshooting', '5.1 Troubleshooting Hardware', 'What does smoke or a burning smell from a computer indicate?', 'Electrical problem — disconnect power immediately, locate and replace all damaged components; there should NEVER be a burned odor', 'Smoke or burning smell is a serious electrical problem. Immediately disconnect power. Even after cooling, locate and replace all damaged components. Do not attempt to run a system that has emitted smoke.'), (114, 'core1', '5.0 Troubleshooting', '5.1 Troubleshooting Hardware', 'What are the common causes of sluggish computer performance?', 'High CPU/I/O (check Task Manager), pending Windows updates, low disk space, CPU throttling from power-saving mode, or malware', 'Troubleshoot sluggish performance: (1) Task Manager — check CPU/I/O utilization. (2) Install Windows Updates — often include driver fixes. (3) Check disk space. (4) On laptops, check power-saving mode throttling. (5) Run anti-virus/anti-malware scan.'), (115, 'core1', '5.0 Troubleshooting', '5.1 Troubleshooting Hardware', 'What does an inaccurate system date/time at every boot indicate?', 'Failing CMOS battery on the motherboard — replace the small button-style battery', 'If the system date/time resets on every boot, the CMOS battery that maintains BIOS settings is failing. Replace the button-style battery on the motherboard. On older systems this also resets all BIOS configuration; newer computers use a jumper to reset settings.'), (116, 'core1', '5.0 Troubleshooting', '5.2 Troubleshooting Storage Devices', 'What are common symptoms of a failing hard drive?', 'Clicking/scraping sounds, read errors/data corruption, slow performance (retrying bad sectors), OS can''t find drive, S.M.A.R.T. errors', 'HDD failure symptoms: clicking or scraping sounds (mechanical failure), read/write errors and data corruption, slow performance as drive retries bad sectors, inability to boot or BIOS can''t find the drive, and S.M.A.R.T. (Self-Monitoring Analysis and Reporting Technology) error warnings. Back up immediately at first signs.'), (117, 'core1', '5.0 Troubleshooting', '5.3 Troubleshooting Display Issues', 'What are common display troubleshooting steps for a blank screen?', 'Check power and signal cable → verify input source → check brightness → swap monitor → test on another computer → try VGA mode (F8) if no video after Windows loads', 'Blank screen steps: (1) Check both power and signal cables. (2) Verify correct input source (HDMI, DVI, VGA). (3) Check brightness — may be too dim. (4) Swap with a known-good monitor. (5) Test monitor on another computer. (6) If video works during POST but not Windows, try VGA mode (F8).'), (118, 'core1', '5.0 Troubleshooting', '5.5 Troubleshooting Networks', 'What does an APIPA address (169.254.x.x) indicate during troubleshooting?', 'Device could not reach a DHCP server — check network connection, verify DHCP server is running, check VLAN/firewall configuration', 'A 169.254.x.x address means Windows assigned APIPA because no DHCP server responded. Troubleshoot: verify cable is connected, check switch port activity, verify DHCP server is running, confirm device can reach DHCP server (check firewall/VLAN config).'), (119, 'core1', '5.0 Troubleshooting', '5.5 Troubleshooting Networks', 'What are the common network troubleshooting steps when a device has no connectivity?', 'Physical layer → IP config (ipconfig) → ping 127.0.0.1 → ping gateway → ping external IP → test DNS → check firewall', 'Network troubleshooting order: (1) Check physical — cable, port lights, switch. (2) Verify IP config — correct IP, subnet, gateway, DNS. (3) Ping loopback 127.0.0.1 — tests TCP/IP stack. (4) Ping default gateway — tests local network. (5) Ping external IP — tests routing. (6) Test DNS name resolution. (7) Check firewall rules.'), (120, 'core1', '5.0 Troubleshooting', '5.6 Troubleshooting Printers', 'What are common laser printer print quality issues and their causes?', 'Faded: low toner or calibration. Smearing: fuser issue. Ghost images: drum not cleaning. Vertical streaks: dirty/damaged drum or OPC', 'Laser quality issues: Faded output — low toner (not empty) or density calibration needed. Smearing/smudging — fuser unit not applying enough heat/pressure, needs replacement. Ghost images (previous page repeating) — drum not cleaning properly. Vertical streaks — dirty drum, damaged toner cartridge, or scratched OPC drum.'), (121, 'core1', '5.0 Troubleshooting', '5.6 Troubleshooting Printers', 'What is the first step when a printer shows ''no connectivity'' on a network?', 'Print test page to get IP → ping the IP → verify IP is static or DHCP-reserved → check firewall (ports 515/LPD, 631/IPP, 9100/RAW)', 'Printer network troubleshooting: (1) Print a test page from front panel to find its IP. (2) Ping the printer''s IP. (3) Ensure IP hasn''t changed — use DHCP reservation or static IP for printers. (4) Check firewall — allow printing ports (515/LPD, 631/IPP, 9100 RAW).'), (122, 'core1', '5.0 Troubleshooting', '5.4 Troubleshooting Mobile Devices', 'What are common mobile device troubleshooting techniques?', 'Soft reset → check OS/app updates → clear app cache → factory reset (last resort — backup first)', 'Mobile troubleshooting: soft reset (power cycle) resolves many transient issues. Check OS and app updates — bugs are often patched. Clear app cache for specific app problems. Factory reset is the last resort — it erases all data and returns device to factory state (always back up first).'), (123, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.5 Network Devices', 'What is a patch panel and why is it used?', 'Combination of punch-down blocks and RJ-45 connectors — permanently punches desk cable runs; patch cables to switch can be easily changed', 'A patch panel centralizes cable management. Permanent cable runs from workstations are punched to the back once. The front RJ-45 ports connect to the switch via short patch cables. Changes to workstation-to-switch connections require only replacing a patch cable — no re-running cable through walls.'), (124, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.2 Network Cables', 'What is coaxial cable (RG-6) and what are its main uses?', 'Cable with inner conductor, dielectric insulator, metal shielding, and plastic jacket — RG-6 for cable TV, DOCSIS modems, and cable internet up to 1 Gbps+', 'Coaxial cable has two conductors sharing a common axis: inner conductor, dielectric insulator, metal shielding, and outer plastic jacket. RG-6 is used for television/digital cable, DOCSIS cable modems, and cable internet. Provides broadband across multiple frequencies.'), (125, 'core1', '1.0 Mobile Devices', '1.2 Connecting Mobile Devices', 'What is mobile hotspot/tethering?', 'Turns a smartphone into a personal Wi-Fi router — extends cellular data to other devices; may require additional carrier charges', 'A mobile hotspot turns your phone into a personal wireless router, extending cellular data to nearby Wi-Fi devices. Also possible via USB or Bluetooth tethering. Dependent on carrier — may require additional charges or limit hotspot data speeds. Uses your cellular data plan.'), (126, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.5 BIOS Settings', 'What is virtualization support in BIOS and why might you need to enable it?', 'Intel VT or AMD-V hardware virtualization — must be enabled in BIOS/UEFI for hypervisors to run VMs efficiently (required by Hyper-V, VMware, VirtualBox 64-bit)', 'Hardware virtualization allows the hypervisor to run multiple OS instances efficiently. Often disabled by default in BIOS. To enable: enter BIOS/UEFI, find Virtualization/VT-x/AMD-V setting. Required by: Windows Hyper-V, VMware, VirtualBox (64-bit guests), and WSL2.'), (127, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.8 Inkjet Printer Maintenance', 'What are the key maintenance tasks for an inkjet printer?', 'Clean print heads (auto or manual), replace CMYK cartridges, calibrate/align nozzles, clear paper jams carefully', 'Inkjet maintenance: many printers auto-clean heads daily — streaks indicate clogged heads, run manual cleaning. Replace individual CMYK cartridges. Calibrate nozzles for crisp, non-overlapping colors. For paper jams: remove all loose paper without ripping, check for remaining scraps.'), (128, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.8 Thermal Printer Maintenance', 'What are the key maintenance tasks for a thermal printer?', 'Replace thermal paper (cannot substitute other paper), clean heating element with IPA, avoid hot areas that could pre-darken paper', 'Thermal maintenance: replace thermal paper when empty (cannot substitute regular paper — keep a list of sizes). Clean heating element with liquid cleaner/IPA, use a cleaning card for head and paper pathways. Thermal paper is sensitive to heat — keep printers away from car dashboards, radiators, and hair dryers.'), (129, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.4 Storage Devices', 'What are optical drives and what formats do they support?', 'Laser reads microscopic bumps — formats: CD-ROM (~700MB), DVD-ROM (~4.7GB/8.5GB dual), Blu-ray (~25GB); relatively slow, used for archival/installation', 'Optical drives use a laser to read microscopic bumps (binary data) on rotating discs. CD-ROM (~700MB), DVD-ROM (4.7GB single, 8.5GB dual layer), Blu-ray (~25GB). Relatively slow, used as archival media or application installation. Less common today as software distribution shifted to downloads.'), (130, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.4 Storage Devices', 'What is flash memory and what are its limitations?', 'EEPROM non-volatile memory — no power to retain data, limited write cycles, not designed for archival storage; always have a backup', 'Flash memory (EEPROM — Electrically Erasable Programmable Read-Only Memory) is non-volatile — no power required to retain data. Limited number of write cycles (can still read after writes are exhausted). Not designed for long-term archival storage — easy to lose or damage. Always maintain a backup.'), (131, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.2 Peripheral Cables', 'What is USB4 and how does it differ from USB 3.2?', 'USB4 uses Thunderbolt 3 protocol over USB-C; Gen 2×2: 20 Gbps, Gen 3×2: 40 Gbps — requires USB-C, doubles bandwidth of USB 3.2', 'USB4 is based on the Thunderbolt 3 protocol and requires a USB-C connector. USB4 Gen 2×2 reaches 20 Gbps; USB4 Gen 3×2 reaches 40 Gbps — matching Thunderbolt 3/4 speeds. USB4 also supports video output (DisplayPort, HDMI via alt mode) and PCIe tunneling. Always check the device''s spec sheet — a USB-C port does NOT guarantee USB4 speed.'), (132, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.3 Memory Technologies', 'What is LPDDR5 memory and where is it used?', 'Low Power DDR5 — soldered laptop/mobile RAM running at lower voltage (1.1V vs 1.1V DDR5); faster and more power-efficient than LPDDR4X; used in ultrabooks and ARM laptops', 'LPDDR (Low Power Double Data Rate) memory is soldered directly to the motherboard in laptops, tablets, and smartphones to save space and power. LPDDR5 offers speeds up to 6400 MT/s with better power efficiency than LPDDR4X. It is common in Qualcomm Snapdragon X, Apple M-series, and thin-and-light Intel/AMD laptops. Because it is soldered, it cannot be upgraded — capacity is fixed at purchase.'), (133, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.4 Storage Devices', 'What is NVMe 2.0 and what new features does it add over NVMe 1.x?', 'NVMe 2.0 (2021+) adds: Zoned Namespace (ZNS) for SSDs, Key Value storage, new command sets for hard drives and optical media, and improved PCIe 5.0 support', 'NVMe 2.0 is the updated NVMe specification released in 2021. Key additions: Zoned Namespace (ZNS) command set allows drives to be managed in zones for better SSD longevity and throughput. Key Value (KV) command set optimizes NoSQL-style storage. Command sets for HDDs and Fabrics (NVMe-oF). NVMe 2.0 also officially supports PCIe 5.0, enabling consumer SSDs exceeding 12 GB/s read speeds. Most modern high-end M.2 SSDs are NVMe 2.0 compatible.'), (134, 'core1', '3.0 Hardware', '3.5 CPU Features', 'What is an NPU and why is it included in modern processors?', 'Neural Processing Unit — dedicated AI/ML inference accelerator built into the CPU/SoC; offloads AI workloads from CPU/GPU for efficiency (Copilot+ PC requirement)', 'An NPU (Neural Processing Unit) is a specialized processor core designed to accelerate machine learning inference operations (matrix math, tensor operations). Modern SoCs include NPUs: Apple M-series, Qualcomm Snapdragon X Elite, AMD Ryzen AI, Intel Core Ultra (Meteor Lake+). Microsoft''s Copilot+ PC requirement mandates 40+ TOPS (Tera Operations Per Second) NPU performance. NPUs enable local AI features like Windows Studio Effects, real-time translation, and AI image generation without internet connectivity.'), (135, 'core1', '2.0 Networking', '2.2 Wireless Network Technologies', 'What are the key new features of Wi-Fi 7 (802.11be) compared to Wi-Fi 6E?', 'Multi-Link Operation (MLO): simultaneous use of multiple bands; 320 MHz channels; 4096-QAM; up to 46 Gbps theoretical — major improvement in latency and throughput', 'Wi-Fi 7 (802.11be) improvements over Wi-Fi 6/6E: Multi-Link Operation (MLO) allows a device to transmit and receive simultaneously across 2.4, 5, and 6 GHz bands — reducing latency and increasing throughput. 320 MHz channel width (vs 160 MHz in Wi-Fi 6E) doubles bandwidth. 4096-QAM modulation (vs 1024-QAM) increases data density. Up to 16 spatial streams. Theoretical max ~46 Gbps. Key exam point: MLO is the signature feature of Wi-Fi 7.'), (136, 'core1', '1.0 Mobile Devices', '1.1 Laptop Hardware', 'What are the key hardware considerations for ARM-based Windows laptops?', 'ARM64 apps run natively; x64 apps run via emulation (slower); x86-32 apps supported; no legacy x64 drivers — check hardware compatibility before deployment', 'ARM-based Windows laptops (Qualcomm Snapdragon X, Microsoft Surface Pro X) run ARM64 apps natively at full speed. x64 (Intel/AMD) apps run through Rosetta-like emulation — functional but with performance overhead. 32-bit x86 apps also supported via emulation. Critical limitation: x64 kernel drivers (antivirus, hardware tools) may not work — organizations must verify software compatibility. Apple Silicon (M-series) runs macOS natively and Windows via virtualization.'), (137, 'core1', '4.0 Virtualization & Cloud', '4.2 Cloud Models', 'What is Infrastructure as Code (IaC) and why is it important in cloud environments?', 'Managing infrastructure through code/scripts rather than manual configuration — enables repeatable, version-controlled, automated deployments (Terraform, Ansible, ARM templates)', 'Infrastructure as Code (IaC) treats infrastructure configuration as software: written in files, stored in version control (Git), reviewed, and automatically applied. Tools include: Terraform (multi-cloud), Ansible (agentless configuration), AWS CloudFormation, Azure Resource Manager (ARM) templates. IaC ensures environments are consistent (no manual configuration drift), deployments are repeatable, and changes are auditable. Key exam concept: IaC is a foundational practice in DevOps and cloud operations.'), (138, 'core1', '5.0 Troubleshooting', '5.1 Troubleshooting Hardware', 'A system with a modern PCIe 5.0 NVMe SSD installed runs much slower than expected. What are likely causes?', 'BIOS slot not configured for PCIe 5.0, insufficient cooling (PCIe 5.0 SSDs run very hot), M.2 slot on PCIe 3.0/4.0 lanes, or PCIe bifurcation settings', 'PCIe 5.0 NVMe SSDs reach 12+ GB/s but have specific requirements: the M.2 slot must be wired to PCIe 5.0 lanes from the CPU (not chipset lanes which are typically PCIe 4.0 or 3.0). Check BIOS for PCIe bifurcation and generation settings. PCIe 5.0 SSDs generate significant heat — a heatsink or active cooler is often required to sustain peak speeds. Verify the SSD is recognized at its correct PCIe generation in BIOS before OS troubleshooting.'), (201, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.1 Windows Editions', 'What are the four main Windows 10/11 editions and their primary use cases?', 'Home (consumers), Pro (business/power users), Enterprise (large organizations), Education (schools/universities)', 'Windows Home targets everyday consumers with basic features. Pro adds BitLocker, domain join, Remote Desktop, and Hyper-V. Enterprise includes all Pro features plus advanced security tools (AppLocker, DirectAccess). Education mirrors Enterprise but is licensed for academic institutions. Only Pro and above support joining a domain.'), (202, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.1 Windows Editions', 'What are the minimum hardware requirements for Windows 11, and what is Copilot+ PC?', 'Windows 11: TPM 2.0, UEFI Secure Boot, 2-core 64-bit CPU at 1 GHz+, 4 GB RAM, 64 GB storage, DirectX 12. Copilot+ PC adds: 40+ TOPS NPU, 16 GB RAM, 256 GB SSD', 'Windows 11 base requirements: TPM 2.0, UEFI with Secure Boot, 64-bit CPU (2+ cores, ≥1 GHz), 4 GB RAM, 64 GB storage, DirectX 12 compatible GPU. Copilot+ PC is a new hardware tier (2024+) enabling AI-powered features: requires a neural processing unit (NPU) delivering 40+ TOPS, 16 GB RAM minimum, and 256 GB SSD. Copilot+ features include Recall (AI-searchable activity history), Live Captions with real-time translation, and Windows Studio Effects — all processed locally without cloud dependency.'), (203, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.1 Windows Editions', 'Which Windows editions support BitLocker full-disk encryption?', 'Windows Pro, Enterprise, and Education — NOT Windows Home', 'BitLocker is a full-disk encryption feature built into Windows that requires a TPM chip. It is available on Windows Pro, Enterprise, and Education editions. Windows Home users can use Device Encryption (a simplified version) if their hardware supports it, but the full BitLocker management interface is only in Pro and above.'), (204, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.2 Windows Command Line', 'What does the ''sfc /scannow'' command do?', 'System File Checker — scans and repairs corrupted or missing Windows system files', 'SFC (System File Checker) scans all protected Windows system files and replaces corrupted or missing files with cached versions. Run from an elevated command prompt. If SFC cannot repair files, run ''DISM /Online /Cleanup-Image /RestoreHealth'' first to repair the Windows image, then re-run sfc /scannow.'), (205, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.2 Windows Command Line', 'What is the purpose of DISM and when should you use it?', 'Deployment Image Servicing and Management — repairs the Windows image itself; use before SFC when the system image is corrupted', 'DISM (Deployment Image Servicing and Management) can repair the Windows component store (WinSxS). The key command is: DISM /Online /Cleanup-Image /RestoreHealth. Use it when SFC /scannow reports errors it cannot fix — DISM downloads correct files from Windows Update to repair the local image. Always run DISM first, then SFC.'), (206, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.2 Windows Command Line', 'What does ''chkdsk /f /r'' do and when should you run it?', '/f fixes file system errors; /r locates bad sectors and recovers data — run when a drive has errors or before decommissioning', 'CHKDSK (Check Disk) scans the file system for errors. /f fixes detected file system errors. /r locates bad sectors and attempts to recover readable data. On a system drive, it schedules the scan for next reboot since the drive is in use. Run it when seeing disk errors in Event Viewer, after improper shutdowns, or when a drive reports errors.'), (207, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.2 Windows Command Line', 'What does ''ipconfig /all'' display compared to just ''ipconfig''?', 'ipconfig shows IP, subnet, gateway; /all adds MAC address, DHCP server, DNS servers, lease times, and adapter description', 'ipconfig displays basic IP configuration (IP address, subnet mask, default gateway). The /all switch adds: physical (MAC) address, DHCP enabled/disabled, DHCP server IP, DNS servers, lease obtained/expires dates, and adapter description. Other useful variants: ipconfig /release (release DHCP lease), /renew (get new IP), /flushdns (clear DNS cache), /displaydns (show cached DNS).'), (208, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.2 Windows Command Line', 'What command shows active network connections, listening ports, and associated processes?', 'netstat -ano — shows all connections, port numbers, and process IDs', 'netstat (network statistics) displays network connections. Key flags: -a (all connections and listening ports), -n (numeric addresses instead of names, faster), -o (owning process ID). Combine as ''netstat -ano''. You can then cross-reference PIDs with Task Manager or ''tasklist'' to identify which process is using a specific port — useful for detecting malware using network connections.'), (209, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.2 Windows Command Line', 'What is the difference between ''tasklist'' and ''taskkill''?', 'tasklist displays running processes; taskkill terminates them — taskkill /PID [id] or /IM [name] /F forces termination', 'tasklist shows all running processes with their PID, memory usage, and image name — similar to Task Manager''s Processes tab. taskkill ends processes: ''taskkill /PID 1234'' kills by process ID, ''taskkill /IM notepad.exe'' kills by name, adding /F forces termination of unresponsive processes. Useful for scripting automated process management.'), (210, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.3 Windows Settings & Tools', 'What is msconfig used for?', 'System Configuration — manages startup programs, boot options, services, and can enable Safe Mode for next boot', 'msconfig (System Configuration) provides access to: General (normal/diagnostic/selective startup), Boot (Safe Mode options, boot timeout, OS selection), Services (enable/disable non-Microsoft services), Startup (link to Task Manager), Tools (shortcuts to common admin tools). It is commonly used for troubleshooting — disabling startup items and services to isolate issues. Setting Safe Mode here requires a reboot to clear it afterward.'), (211, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.3 Windows Settings & Tools', 'What information can you find in Windows Event Viewer?', 'Application, security, system event logs with errors, warnings, and informational events — useful for diagnosing crashes, login failures, service errors', 'Event Viewer (eventvwr.msc) organizes logs by: Windows Logs (Application, Security, System, Setup, Forwarded Events) and Applications and Services Logs. Security log records logon events, account management, and policy changes. System log records hardware/driver events and service failures. Application log records program crashes. Critical/Error/Warning/Information/Verbose are the severity levels.'), (212, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.3 Windows Settings & Tools', 'What are the NTFS permissions and their access levels, and how do they interact with share permissions?', 'NTFS: Full Control, Modify, Read & Execute, List Folder Contents, Read, Write — local access. Share: Full Control, Change, Read — network access. When both apply, the MORE RESTRICTIVE permission wins.', 'NTFS permissions control access whether local or network. Full Control allows all actions including changing permissions. Modify allows read/write/delete but not permission changes. Read & Execute allows running files and reading. Write allows creating/modifying. Share permissions only apply when accessing over the network via SMB. When both NTFS and share permissions are set, the effective permission is the most restrictive combination. Best practice: set share permission to Full Control for authenticated users; use NTFS permissions for granular control.'), (213, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.3 Windows Settings & Tools', 'What is the Windows Registry and what are its five root keys?', 'HKLM (Local Machine), HKCU (Current User), HKCR (Classes Root), HKU (Users), HKCC (Current Config)', 'The Windows Registry is a hierarchical database storing OS and application configuration. HKLM contains system-wide settings. HKCU stores per-user preferences. HKCR has file associations and COM object registrations. HKU contains all user profiles. HKCC is a link to the current hardware profile. Edit with regedit.exe — always back up before changes. Malware often runs from HKCU\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run.'), (214, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.4 Linux & macOS', 'What are the essential Linux command-line tools a technician should know?', 'ls (list), cd (change dir), pwd (print working dir), cp/mv/rm (copy/move/delete), chmod (permissions), grep (search), ps/top (processes), sudo (elevated), apt/yum (package manager)', 'Key Linux commands: ls -la (detailed list with hidden files), cd /path (navigate), pwd (current directory), cp src dst (copy), mv src dst (move/rename), rm -rf dir (force delete), chmod 755 file (set permissions), grep -r ''text'' /path (recursive search), ps aux (all processes), top (live process monitor), sudo command (run as root), apt install/remove (Debian/Ubuntu), yum install (RHEL/CentOS).'), (215, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.4 Linux & macOS', 'What is virtualization and what are the two types of hypervisors?', 'Type 1 (bare-metal) runs directly on hardware — VMware ESXi, Hyper-V; Type 2 (hosted) runs on top of an OS — VirtualBox, VMware Workstation', 'Virtualization allows multiple virtual machines to share physical hardware resources. Type 1 hypervisors install directly on hardware and are used in enterprise/server environments (VMware ESXi, Microsoft Hyper-V, Citrix XenServer). Type 2 hypervisors run within a host OS on a desktop/laptop (Oracle VirtualBox, VMware Workstation, Parallels on Mac). Type 1 offers better performance; Type 2 is easier to set up for testing.'), (216, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.1 Malware Types', 'What is the difference between a virus, a worm, and a trojan?', 'Virus: attaches to files, requires user action to spread; Worm: self-replicates across networks without user action; Trojan: masquerades as legitimate software', 'A virus requires a host file and user interaction (opening a file) to spread and execute. A worm self-replicates and spreads automatically across networks by exploiting vulnerabilities — no user action needed (e.g., WannaCry). A Trojan disguises itself as useful software but performs malicious actions when run. Unlike viruses/worms, Trojans typically do not self-replicate. Trojans often install backdoors or RATs (Remote Access Trojans).'), (217, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.1 Malware Types', 'What is ransomware and what is the recommended response?', 'Malware that encrypts files and demands payment for decryption key — response: isolate, report, restore from clean backup (do NOT pay ransom)', 'Ransomware encrypts user/system files and demands a ransom (usually cryptocurrency) for the decryption key. Famous examples: WannaCry, CryptoLocker, Ryuk. Response steps: 1) Immediately disconnect from the network to prevent spread, 2) Document/photograph the ransom screen, 3) Report to management and potentially law enforcement, 4) Wipe and restore from a known-good backup. Paying the ransom is discouraged — no guarantee of key delivery and funds criminal activity.'), (218, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.1 Malware Types', 'What is a rootkit and why is it particularly dangerous?', 'Malware that hides itself and other malware at the OS/kernel level — evades standard antivirus detection; requires bootable scanner to remove', 'A rootkit modifies the operating system at a deep level (kernel, boot sector, firmware) to hide its presence and the presence of other malware. Because it runs below the OS, standard antivirus running within Windows cannot reliably detect it. Removal typically requires booting from external media (Windows PE, Linux live USB) and scanning the drive offline. In severe cases, a full OS reinstall is required. Rootkits can persist across OS reinstalls if in the firmware (UEFI rootkit).'), (219, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.1 Malware Types', 'What are spyware, adware, and keyloggers?', 'Spyware: monitors user activity and transmits data; Adware: displays unwanted ads; Keylogger: records keystrokes to capture passwords', 'Spyware silently monitors browsing habits, collects personal information, and transmits it to a remote attacker. Adware displays unwanted advertisements, often injecting ads into browsers, and may be bundled with free software. A keylogger records every keystroke — capturing usernames, passwords, credit card numbers, and messages — and sends them to an attacker. Keyloggers can be software (runs on OS) or hardware (physical device plugged between keyboard and computer).'), (220, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.1 Malware Types', 'What is a botnet and how is it used by attackers?', 'A network of infected computers (bots/zombies) controlled by a command-and-control (C2) server — used for DDoS attacks, spam, credential stuffing, cryptomining', 'A botnet is a collection of internet-connected devices infected with malware and controlled remotely by an attacker (bot herder) through a Command-and-Control (C2) server. Botnets are used for: DDoS attacks (flooding targets with traffic), sending spam emails, credential stuffing attacks, cryptocurrency mining, and spreading more malware. Individual infected machines are called ''bots'' or ''zombies.'' The owner typically doesn''t know their device is part of a botnet.'), (221, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.2 Social Engineering', 'What is phishing and how does it differ from spear phishing and whaling?', 'Phishing: mass email attacks targeting anyone; Spear phishing: targeted at specific individuals/org; Whaling: targets high-level executives (CEO, CFO)', 'Phishing sends fraudulent emails en masse impersonating trusted organizations (banks, Microsoft) to steal credentials. Spear phishing is tailored to a specific individual or organization, including personal details to appear legitimate — much harder to detect. Whaling specifically targets high-value executives whose credentials or authorization can yield large financial or data gains. Vishing is voice/phone phishing. Smishing is SMS text message phishing.'), (222, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.2 Social Engineering', 'What are tailgating and piggybacking in physical security?', 'Tailgating: following an authorized person through a secure door without their knowledge; Piggybacking: entering with the person''s consent but without proper authorization', 'Tailgating (also called tailgating) occurs when an unauthorized person follows an authorized employee through a secured door without the employee noticing. Piggybacking is similar but the authorized person is aware and holds the door — often out of politeness. Both bypass physical access controls like badge readers. Countermeasures: security awareness training, mantraps (double-door airlocks), security cameras, and policies against holding doors for others.'), (223, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.2 Social Engineering', 'What is shoulder surfing and dumpster diving?', 'Shoulder surfing: visually stealing information by watching someone type; Dumpster diving: retrieving sensitive information from discarded documents/hardware', 'Shoulder surfing involves looking over someone''s shoulder to observe passwords, PINs, or sensitive data being entered or displayed. Countermeasure: privacy screens, positioning awareness. Dumpster diving involves searching through trash for discarded documents, old drives, or equipment containing sensitive information. Countermeasures: cross-cut shredders for documents, proper drive destruction/degaussing before disposal, clear desk policies. Both are low-tech but effective attack vectors.'), (224, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.3 Security Controls', 'What is multi-factor authentication (MFA) and what are the three factors?', 'Something you know (password/PIN), something you have (smart card/token/phone), something you are (biometric — fingerprint, face, iris)', 'MFA requires two or more different authentication factors. Combining factors from different categories significantly increases security — even if an attacker obtains your password, they still need the physical token or biometric. Common MFA implementations: password + SMS code, password + authenticator app TOTP, smart card + PIN. Two-factor authentication (2FA) is a subset of MFA using exactly two factors. Location and behavior can also serve as factors in advanced systems.'), (225, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.3 Security Controls', 'What is the principle of least privilege?', 'Users and processes should have only the minimum permissions needed to perform their job — nothing more', 'Least privilege limits damage from accidents, errors, and malicious attacks. Examples: a receptionist should not have admin rights; a web server process shouldn''t run as SYSTEM/root; a developer''s test account shouldn''t access production databases. Implementation: use standard user accounts for daily tasks, only elevate when necessary (UAC in Windows), use role-based access control (RBAC), and regularly audit permissions. This limits the blast radius of a compromised account.'), (226, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.3 Security Controls', 'What is BitLocker and what does it protect against?', 'Windows full-disk encryption that protects data if a device is lost or stolen — requires TPM chip; protected partition cannot be read without authentication', 'BitLocker encrypts entire drive volumes using AES encryption. It uses the TPM chip to store encryption keys and verify system integrity at boot. BitLocker protects against: physical theft of a drive (data unreadable without key), offline attacks (booting from external media to access files). BitLocker can require a PIN at boot for additional security. Recovery keys should be stored in Active Directory or Microsoft account. BitLocker To Go encrypts removable drives.'), (227, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.3 Security Controls', 'What are the steps to remove malware from a Windows system?', '1) Identify symptoms, 2) Quarantine/isolate, 3) Disable System Restore, 4) Boot to safe mode/offline scanner, 5) Run malware scans, 6) Remove/quarantine malware, 7) Re-enable protections, 8) Patch system, 9) Document', 'CompTIA''s malware removal process: 1) Investigate and identify malware type. 2) Quarantine infected system from the network. 3) Disable System Restore to prevent restoring malware from restore points. 4) Boot into Safe Mode or use an offline bootable scanner (outside the OS). 5-6) Run multiple anti-malware tools, remove threats. 7) Re-enable System Restore, update definitions, schedule scans. 8) Apply OS/application patches that were exploited. 9) Document findings for future reference.'), (228, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.3 Security Controls', 'What is a firewall and what is the difference between hardware and software firewalls?', 'Hardware firewall: network-level device protecting entire network; Software firewall: host-based, runs on individual computer (Windows Defender Firewall)', 'A firewall controls network traffic based on rules. Hardware firewalls (routers, UTM appliances) sit at the network perimeter and protect all devices on the network — filtering inbound/outbound traffic. Software firewalls run on individual hosts and control traffic to/from that specific device. Windows Defender Firewall is a software firewall built into Windows. Best practice is to use both: hardware firewall at the perimeter and host-based firewall on each device for defense in depth.'), (229, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.4 Data Destruction', 'What are the approved methods for securely destroying data on storage devices?', 'Degaussing (magnetic fields destroy magnetic drives), Secure erase/overwrite (software wiping), Shredding/destruction (physical), Encryption then deletion', 'Standard deletion or formatting only removes file system pointers — data recovery is possible. Secure methods: Degaussing uses strong magnetic fields to scramble data on magnetic HDDs and tapes (does not work on SSDs). Overwriting replaces data with zeros/random patterns (DoD 5220.22-M standard uses multiple passes). Physical destruction: shredding, drilling holes, incineration. For SSDs, manufacturer secure erase commands or physical destruction are recommended since degaussing is ineffective. Encryption before disposal is an additional layer.'), (230, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.4 Data Destruction', 'What is the difference between data wiping, low-level formatting, and standard formatting?', 'Data wiping: overwrites all sectors with zeros/random data; Low-level formatting: initializes physical sectors on drive; Standard (high-level) format: only clears file system index, data remains recoverable', 'A standard quick format only erases the master file table or FAT — the actual data blocks remain and are easily recovered with forensic tools. A full format in Windows does overwrite data in Windows Vista and later. Low-level formatting (from BIOS/drive utility) initializes physical track and sector markings — rarely needed on modern drives. Data wiping tools (DBAN, Eraser) overwrite all sectors with patterns. For maximum security: wipe + physical destruction.'), (231, 'core2', '3.0 Software Troubleshooting', '3.1 Windows Troubleshooting', 'What causes a Blue Screen of Death (BSOD) and how do you begin troubleshooting?', 'Hardware failure, driver issues, or OS corruption — check Event Viewer, minidump files in C:\Windows\Minidump, use WinDbg to analyze crash dump', 'BSOD (Stop Error) indicates a fatal system error forcing Windows to halt to prevent data corruption. Common causes: bad RAM, faulty drivers (especially graphics/storage), failing hardware, overheating, or rootkits. Troubleshooting: 1) Note the STOP error code and offending file. 2) Check Event Viewer > Windows Logs > System for errors before the crash. 3) Analyze minidump files with WinDbg or WhoCrashed. 4) Boot Safe Mode to test with minimal drivers. 5) Run memory diagnostics (Windows Memory Diagnostic / MemTest86).'), (232, 'core2', '3.0 Software Troubleshooting', '3.1 Windows Troubleshooting', 'What is the Windows Recovery Environment (WinRE) and what tools does it provide?', 'Pre-boot repair environment — Startup Repair, System Restore, System Image Recovery, Command Prompt, and Reset this PC', 'WinRE (Windows Recovery Environment) is accessible by pressing F8 at boot, holding Shift while clicking Restart, or booting from Windows installation media. It provides: Startup Repair (automatically fixes boot issues), System Restore (rolls back to restore point), System Image Recovery (restores full backup image), Command Prompt (advanced manual repairs with bcdedit, diskpart, sfc), Reset this PC (reinstall Windows keeping/removing files), and Go back to previous version.'), (233, 'core2', '3.0 Software Troubleshooting', '3.1 Windows Troubleshooting', 'What is Safe Mode and when do you use it?', 'Minimal startup mode loading only essential drivers — use to diagnose driver/software issues, remove malware, or run repairs when normal boot fails', 'Safe Mode starts Windows with a minimal set of drivers and services. Safe Mode types: Safe Mode (basic VGA, no network), Safe Mode with Networking (adds network drivers for internet access), Safe Mode with Command Prompt (for advanced users). Boot into Safe Mode via msconfig, WinRE, or Shift+Restart. Use it to: uninstall problematic software/drivers, run malware scans away from startup items, diagnose if a clean boot resolves issues, access an otherwise unbootable system.'), (234, 'core2', '3.0 Software Troubleshooting', '3.1 Windows Troubleshooting', 'What does System Restore do and what does it NOT protect?', 'Rolls back OS registry and system files to a restore point — does NOT protect personal files (documents, photos) or user data', 'System Restore creates snapshots of Windows system files, installed programs, and registry settings. It can undo driver installs, Windows updates, or software changes that caused instability. Important: System Restore does NOT affect personal documents, pictures, or email — these will not be restored. It also does not remove viruses if they infected system files before the restore point was created. Disable System Restore when removing malware to prevent restoring infected files from restore points.'), (235, 'core2', '3.0 Software Troubleshooting', '3.2 Application Troubleshooting', 'A user reports applications are crashing randomly. What is your diagnostic approach?', 'Check Event Viewer application logs, verify system resources (RAM/disk), check for OS/application updates, test in Clean Boot, run SFC, check for malware', 'Systematic troubleshooting: 1) Event Viewer > Application log for crash details and error codes. 2) Check RAM with Windows Memory Diagnostic (mdsched.exe). 3) Check disk health with chkdsk. 4) Verify adequate free disk space (low space causes crashes). 5) Update application and Windows — patches fix known crash bugs. 6) Clean Boot (msconfig) isolates third-party software conflicts. 7) SFC /scannow for corrupted system files. 8) Scan for malware. 9) Reinstall application as last resort.'), (236, 'core2', '4.0 Operational Procedures', '4.1 Documentation', 'What are the key types of documentation a technician should maintain?', 'Network diagrams, asset inventory, knowledge base articles, incident reports, change documentation, standard operating procedures (SOPs)', 'Documentation types: Network diagrams (logical and physical maps of network topology). Asset inventory (hardware/software inventory with serial numbers, licenses). Knowledge base (solutions to known issues for future reference). Incident reports (document security incidents: what happened, impact, response). Change documentation (records of changes made to systems). SOPs (step-by-step procedures for common tasks). Good documentation reduces mean time to repair (MTTR) and supports compliance requirements.'), (237, 'core2', '4.0 Operational Procedures', '4.1 Documentation', 'What is change management and why is it important?', 'A formal process for requesting, reviewing, approving, testing, and documenting changes to IT systems — prevents uncontrolled changes that cause outages', 'Change management ensures that changes are: Requested (change request submitted with details), Reviewed (assessed for risk and impact), Approved by change advisory board (CAB), Tested in non-production first, Implemented during a maintenance window, Verified after implementation, and Documented. A rollback plan must exist before any change. Prevents ''change-related incidents'' — the most common cause of outages in IT environments. CompTIA emphasizes: document everything before, during, and after changes.'), (238, 'core2', '4.0 Operational Procedures', '4.2 Scripting Basics', 'What are the common scripting languages a CompTIA A+ technician should know?', 'Batch (.bat/.cmd) for basic Windows automation, PowerShell (.ps1) for advanced Windows administration, Python (.py) for cross-platform automation, Shell/Bash for Linux/macOS', 'Batch scripts use CMD commands for simple Windows automation (net user, robocopy, scheduled tasks). PowerShell is the modern Windows scripting environment with full .NET access — can manage Active Directory, registry, services. Python is versatile for cross-platform scripts, file processing, and API interactions. Bash is standard for Linux/macOS automation. File extensions: .bat/.cmd (batch), .ps1 (PowerShell), .py (Python), .sh (shell). PowerShell execution policy may need to be set to allow scripts: Set-ExecutionPolicy RemoteSigned.'), (239, 'core2', '4.0 Operational Procedures', '4.2 Scripting Basics', 'What does a PowerShell execution policy control and how do you change it?', 'Controls which scripts can run: Restricted (no scripts), RemoteSigned (local scripts ok, downloaded must be signed), Unrestricted (all scripts) — change with Set-ExecutionPolicy', 'PowerShell execution policies prevent accidental execution of malicious scripts. Policies: Restricted (default, no scripts allowed), AllSigned (all scripts must be digitally signed), RemoteSigned (local scripts run freely, downloaded scripts require a digital signature), Unrestricted (all scripts run, downloaded scripts warn). Change with: Set-ExecutionPolicy RemoteSigned -Scope CurrentUser. Check current policy: Get-ExecutionPolicy. This is a common item on the A+ exam and real-world administration.'), (240, 'core2', '4.0 Operational Procedures', '4.3 Environmental & Safety', 'What is the proper procedure for handling electrostatic discharge (ESD) when working with computer components?', 'Wear an anti-static wrist strap connected to ground, work on anti-static mat, handle components by edges, avoid carpet areas, keep components in anti-static bags', 'ESD can damage or destroy electronic components with discharge invisible to humans (as little as 30V can damage ICs, while humans feel static at ~3000V). Preventions: Anti-static wrist strap (grounds you to the case). Anti-static mat (safe work surface). Touch bare metal on the case before touching components. Handle PCBs by edges, never touching ICs or traces. Store components in anti-static bags (silvery/pink). Avoid working in carpeted areas. Humidity above 50% reduces static buildup.'), (241, 'core2', '4.0 Operational Procedures', '4.3 Environmental & Safety', 'What is a Material Safety Data Sheet (MSDS/SDS) and when is it required?', 'Document describing chemical hazards, safe handling, storage, disposal, and emergency response for a hazardous material — required for toner, cleaning solvents, batteries', 'MSDS (now called SDS - Safety Data Sheet per GHS standard) documents: chemical composition, physical and chemical properties, health hazards, safe handling and storage, PPE requirements, first aid measures, fire and explosion data, spill cleanup, and disposal procedures. Required by OSHA for all hazardous materials in the workplace. Technicians encounter SDS for laser toner cartridges (fine powder is a respiratory hazard), cleaning solvents, thermal paste, and battery acid. Always review SDS before handling unfamiliar chemicals.'), (242, 'core2', '4.0 Operational Procedures', '4.4 Incident Response', 'What are the steps in a basic incident response process?', '1) Identify/detect, 2) Contain/isolate, 3) Eradicate (remove threat), 4) Recover (restore systems), 5) Lessons learned/report', 'Incident response (based on NIST SP 800-61): Preparation (policies, tools, training before an incident). Identification (detect and confirm an incident occurred). Containment (limit damage — isolate affected systems from network). Eradication (remove malware, close vulnerabilities). Recovery (restore from backup, verify system integrity, monitor for recurrence). Lessons learned (document incident timeline, impact, response, and improvements). Chain of custody must be maintained for forensic evidence — document everything.'), (243, 'core2', '4.0 Operational Procedures', '4.4 Incident Response', 'What is chain of custody in IT security and why does it matter?', 'Documentation tracking evidence handling from collection to court — records who collected it, when, where, and who had access — ensures evidence is admissible in legal proceedings', 'Chain of custody is a legal concept ensuring digital evidence integrity. Proper procedure: 1) Document the system state before touching it (photos, hashes). 2) Use write blockers when making forensic copies. 3) Create a cryptographic hash (MD5/SHA-256) of evidence. 4) Seal evidence with tamper-evident measures. 5) Log every person who accesses the evidence with timestamps. 6) Verify hash matches when re-examining. Broken chain of custody can make evidence inadmissible in court. Always preserve original evidence — work from copies.'), (244, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.5 Wireless Security', 'What are WEP, WPA, WPA2, and WPA3 and which should be used?', 'WEP: deprecated/broken (never use); WPA: deprecated; WPA2-AES (CCMP): current standard; WPA3: latest with SAE and enhanced protections', 'WEP (Wired Equivalent Privacy) uses RC4 and can be cracked in minutes — never use. WPA (Wi-Fi Protected Access) improved over WEP but also deprecated. WPA2-Personal uses Pre-Shared Key (PSK) with AES-CCMP encryption — still widely used. WPA2-Enterprise uses 802.1X/RADIUS for per-user authentication. WPA3 replaces PSK with SAE (Simultaneous Authentication of Equals), provides forward secrecy, protects against offline dictionary attacks, and is required on new Wi-Fi 6 devices. Always use WPA2 or WPA3 minimum.'), (245, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.5 Wireless Security', 'What security measures should be configured on a SOHO wireless router?', 'Change default admin password, use WPA2/WPA3, disable WPS, change SSID, enable firewall, disable remote management, update firmware, use guest network', 'SOHO router hardening: 1) Change default admin credentials (admin/admin is exploitable). 2) Use WPA2-AES or WPA3 with a strong passphrase. 3) Disable WPS (Wi-Fi Protected Setup) — vulnerable to brute-force PIN attacks. 4) Change default SSID (reveals router model). 5) Enable built-in firewall. 6) Disable remote management from WAN unless needed. 7) Update firmware to patch vulnerabilities. 8) Use guest network for visitors to isolate from main network. 9) Disable UPnP if not needed.'), (246, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.5 Cloud Computing', 'What are the three main cloud service models and what does each provide?', 'IaaS (VMs/networking), PaaS (development platform), SaaS (complete applications) — responsibility shifts from provider to customer as you move from SaaS to IaaS', 'IaaS (Infrastructure as a Service): Provider manages physical hardware, hypervisor. Customer manages OS, middleware, apps. Examples: AWS EC2, Azure VMs. PaaS (Platform as a Service): Provider manages OS and runtime. Customer manages only the application and data. Examples: Azure App Service, Heroku, Google App Engine. SaaS (Software as a Service): Provider manages everything. Customer only uses the software. Examples: Microsoft 365, Salesforce, Google Workspace. The shared responsibility model defines security obligations for each party.'), (247, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.3 Security Controls', 'What is a VPN and what protocols are commonly used?', 'Virtual Private Network — encrypts traffic between client and corporate network over public internet; protocols: OpenVPN, IPSec/IKEv2, L2TP/IPSec, PPTP (deprecated), SSL/TLS VPN', 'A VPN creates an encrypted tunnel over a public network (internet) to securely connect remote users or sites to a private network. Split tunneling sends only corporate traffic through VPN while other traffic goes directly to internet. Always-on VPN automatically connects. Common protocols: IPSec/IKEv2 (fast, mobile-friendly), OpenVPN (open-source, flexible), L2TP/IPSec (common, uses double encapsulation), WireGuard (modern, fast). PPTP is insecure — never use. SSL VPNs use port 443 and work through most firewalls.'), (248, 'core2', '3.0 Software Troubleshooting', '3.3 Mobile OS Troubleshooting', 'What are common troubleshooting steps for a slow or unresponsive mobile device?', 'Soft reset/restart, close background apps, clear app cache, check storage space, update OS/apps, factory reset as last resort — also check for malware', 'Mobile device troubleshooting: 1) Soft reset (restart) clears RAM and resolves most temporary issues. 2) Close background apps consuming CPU/RAM. 3) Clear app cache: Settings > Apps > [App] > Clear Cache. 4) Free up storage (devices slow at >90% full). 5) Update OS and apps — fixes bugs and security issues. 6) Check battery health (degraded batteries throttle CPU). 7) Scan for malware/unauthorized apps. 8) Factory reset removes all data but resolves software issues — back up first. 9) For iOS: check iCloud Backup, use iTunes/Finder for restoration.'), (249, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.6 Mobile Device Security', 'What is mobile device management (MDM) and what can it control?', 'Software platform to remotely manage mobile devices — can enforce encryption, passcodes, app control, remote wipe, and compliance policies', 'MDM solutions (Microsoft Intune, Jamf, VMware Workspace ONE) allow IT administrators to: enforce screen lock and PIN/password complexity, enable full-device encryption, control which apps can be installed, push certificates and Wi-Fi/VPN profiles, monitor compliance status, remotely lock a lost device, and remotely wipe all data from a lost/stolen device. BYOD (Bring Your Own Device) environments often use MAM (Mobile Application Management) to control only corporate apps without full device control.'), (250, 'core2', '4.0 Operational Procedures', '4.5 Professionalism', 'What should a technician do when they encounter sensitive personal data during repairs?', 'Maintain confidentiality — do not read/copy/share personal data; inform management if discovering illegal content; follow organizational privacy policies; document actions', 'Technicians often access customer files during repairs. Professional obligations: Do not read personal emails, documents, or photos unless absolutely necessary for the repair. Do not copy, share, or discuss customer data. If you discover what appears to be illegal content (CSAM, etc.): do not delete it (preserve evidence), do not access further, immediately report to management and follow their guidance for law enforcement reporting. Privacy laws (GDPR, HIPAA, CCPA) impose legal obligations on organizations handling personal data. Maintaining customer trust is paramount.'), (251, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.1 Windows Features', 'What is Windows Subsystem for Linux (WSL2) and how does it differ from WSL1?', 'WSL2 runs a real Linux kernel in a lightweight Hyper-V VM — full syscall compatibility, better file I/O performance, supports Docker natively. WSL1 used translation layer.', 'WSL (Windows Subsystem for Linux) allows running Linux distributions natively on Windows. WSL1 translated Linux syscalls to Windows equivalents — fast but not fully compatible. WSL2 runs an actual Linux kernel inside a lightweight Hyper-V virtual machine, providing full Linux binary compatibility, Docker support, and significantly better I/O performance with Linux file systems. Install with: ''wsl --install''. WSL2 is testable on 220-1202 as a key Windows OS feature for developers and power users.'), (252, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.3 Security Controls', 'What is Zero Trust security and how does it differ from traditional perimeter security?', 'Never trust, always verify — every user, device, and network request is authenticated and authorized regardless of location; replaces the ''trusted internal network'' model', 'Traditional perimeter security assumes everything inside the network is trusted (castle-and-moat model). Zero Trust assumes breach and requires: continuous verification of identity (MFA), device health checks (MDM compliance), least-privilege access, micro-segmentation of networks, and encrypted communication even internally. Key principles: verify explicitly, use least privilege access, assume breach. Technologies: Azure AD Conditional Access, Microsoft Intune, identity-based access policies. Driven by remote work, cloud adoption, and the realization that insider threats and lateral movement are major risks.'), (253, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.2 Social Engineering', 'What are AI-enhanced social engineering threats and how should organizations defend against them?', 'AI-generated phishing emails (no typos, personalized), deepfake voice/video impersonation, AI-powered credential stuffing — defend with MFA, verification procedures, and security awareness training', 'AI is enabling more sophisticated attacks: AI-written phishing emails are grammatically perfect and highly personalized using OSINT. Voice cloning can impersonate executives (CEO fraud/vishing). Deepfake video can be used in video calls for impersonation. AI-powered tools automate credential stuffing and password spraying at massive scale. Defenses: MFA (renders stolen passwords useless), out-of-band verification for unusual requests (call back on a known number), security awareness training that includes AI threat scenarios, and behavioral analytics to detect anomalies.'), (254, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.3 Security Controls', 'What is Windows Hello for Business and how does it replace passwords?', 'Enterprise passwordless authentication using biometrics (face/fingerprint) or PIN — backed by TPM-protected cryptographic keys, not transmitted over network', 'Windows Hello for Business replaces passwords with asymmetric key-based authentication. When set up: a private key is stored in the device''s TPM chip, a public key is registered with Azure AD or Active Directory. At login, the user proves possession of the private key via biometric (face, fingerprint) or PIN — the PIN is local and never transmitted. Because the private key never leaves the TPM, there is nothing to steal from a server breach. Requires: TPM 2.0, Windows 11 Pro/Enterprise, Azure AD or hybrid AD join. Recommended for 220-1202 as it relates to MFA and passwordless identity.'), (255, 'core2', '4.0 Operational Procedures', '4.2 Scripting Basics', 'What are key improvements in PowerShell 7 compared to Windows PowerShell 5.1?', 'Cross-platform (Windows/Linux/macOS), open-source (.NET Core), parallel execution (ForEach-Object -Parallel), updated operators, better error handling, side-by-side installation', 'PowerShell 7 (based on .NET Core/5+) is cross-platform and open-source, unlike Windows PowerShell 5.1 (Windows-only, closed-source .NET Framework). Key additions: ForEach-Object -Parallel for concurrent execution, null conditional operators (?. and ??=), ternary operator (condition ? true : false), improved error handling with Get-Error, Pipeline Chain Operators (&& and ||). PowerShell 7 installs side-by-side with Windows PowerShell 5.1 — they coexist. The pwsh command launches PowerShell 7; powershell launches 5.1.'), (256, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.3 Windows Settings & Tools', 'What are Windows 11''s new security features compared to Windows 10?', 'Mandatory TPM 2.0, Secure Boot required, Virtualization-Based Security (VBS) on by default, Memory Integrity (HVCI), Smart App Control, Credential Guard enhanced', 'Windows 11 security improvements: TPM 2.0 is mandatory (not optional). Secure Boot required. VBS (Virtualization-Based Security) is enabled by default — uses Hyper-V to isolate critical OS components. HVCI (Hypervisor-Protected Code Integrity / Memory Integrity) prevents injection of malicious code into kernel. Smart App Control uses AI/ML to block untrusted apps. Credential Guard protects NTLM hashes and Kerberos tickets in a VBS-isolated environment. These are testable 220-1202 objectives added to reflect Windows 11''s security-by-default design.'), (257, 'core2', '3.0 Software Troubleshooting', '3.1 Windows Troubleshooting', 'What is the Windows Reliability Monitor and how does it differ from Event Viewer?', 'Reliability Monitor (perfmon /rel) shows a visual timeline of stability and crash events — easier to correlate events vs Event Viewer''s raw log format', 'Reliability Monitor (perfmon /rel or search ''reliability'') shows a graphical 1–10 stability index over time, plotting hardware failures, software crashes, Windows failures, and miscellaneous failures. Easy to spot: ''it started crashing after this date'' by correlating with software installs. Event Viewer provides raw, detailed event logs with thousands of entries — more powerful but harder to navigate. For 220-1202, Reliability Monitor is often the first tool to check when investigating intermittent crashes or system instability over time.'), (258, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.4 Data Destruction', 'What is BitLocker XTS-AES and how does it improve over the older CBC mode?', 'XTS-AES (XEX-based Tweaked CodeBook with ciphertext Stealing) — sector-level encryption with better diffusion, prevents pattern attacks on fixed-length disk sectors; default on Windows 11', 'BitLocker uses AES encryption. In older Windows versions, CBC (Cipher Block Chaining) mode was used — vulnerable to pattern attacks on fixed-size disk sectors. XTS-AES (default in Windows 10 1511+ for new drives, standard in Windows 11) uses sector-based tweaking that prevents identical plaintext sectors from producing identical ciphertext — defeating attacks that exploit sector-level patterns. BitLocker supports 128-bit or 256-bit AES. For 220-1202, know that XTS-AES is the current BitLocker encryption mode and why it is preferred over CBC for disk encryption.'), (259, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.1 File Systems', 'Compare NTFS, FAT32, exFAT, and ReFS — what are the key differences for the A+ exam?', 'NTFS: max 16 TB file, journaling, permissions, encryption (Windows default). FAT32: max 4 GB file, universal compatibility. exFAT: large files on flash/USB, no journaling. ReFS: max 35 PB, self-healing, no BitLocker encryption drive support', 'NTFS (New Technology File System) is the default for Windows drives — supports file/folder permissions, EFS encryption, quotas, journaling (crash recovery), and files up to 16 TB. FAT32 is limited to 4 GB per file and 8 TB partition; used for older flash drives and compatibility. exFAT (Extended FAT) removes the 4 GB file limit — ideal for large video files on USB drives and SD cards; no journaling. ReFS (Resilient File System) is used in Windows Server/Storage Spaces for very large volumes with self-healing checksums — not all Windows features (like BitLocker) are supported on ReFS. For 220-1202 know which file system to choose based on file size, OS, and use case.'), (260, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.1 File Systems', 'What are ext4, APFS, and HFS+ and on which operating systems are they used?', 'ext4 = Linux default (journaling, large files). APFS (Apple File System) = macOS 10.13+/iOS default (snapshots, cloning, encryption). HFS+ = older Macs (macOS 10.12 and earlier)', 'ext4 (Fourth Extended Filesystem) is the standard Linux file system — supports journaling, files up to 16 TB, volumes up to 1 EB; backwards compatible with ext2/ext3. APFS (Apple File System) replaced HFS+ starting with macOS High Sierra (10.13) — designed for SSDs with native encryption, snapshots (used by Time Machine), space sharing, and fast cloning without copying data. HFS+ (Mac OS Extended) was the Apple standard before APFS; still used on spinning HDDs and compatible with older macOS. For 220-1202 know: Linux uses ext4, modern Macs use APFS, older Macs used HFS+.'), (261, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.1 Disk Partitioning', 'What is the difference between MBR and GPT partition styles?', 'MBR: max 2 TB disk, 4 primary partitions, legacy BIOS. GPT: max 9.4 ZB, 128 partitions, requires UEFI, includes redundant partition table backup', 'MBR (Master Boot Record) stores the partition table in the first 512-byte sector — limited to 2 TB per disk and 4 primary partitions (or 3 primary + 1 extended with logical partitions inside). It works with legacy BIOS systems. GPT (GUID Partition Table) is part of the UEFI specification — supports disks over 2 TB, up to 128 partitions on Windows, and stores a backup copy of the partition table at the end of the disk for redundancy. Modern Windows installations on drives over 2 TB require GPT. For 220-1202: UEFI = GPT, legacy BIOS = MBR.'), (262, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.2 OS Installation', 'What are the Windows OS upgrade vs. clean install vs. in-place upgrade differences?', 'Upgrade: keeps files/settings/apps. Clean install: wipes drive, fresh OS. In-place upgrade/repair install: reinstalls Windows over itself to fix OS corruption while keeping files and apps', 'Windows installation types: (1) Upgrade — migrates existing files, settings, and applications to the new OS version; requires compatible existing OS. (2) Clean install — formats the target partition and installs fresh; removes all existing data. (3) In-place upgrade (repair install) — reinstalls the same or newer version of Windows over itself to fix system file corruption without removing user data or applications; useful when SFC/DISM can''t fix corruption. (4) Image deployment — applies a pre-configured disk image (Sysprep + WIM/ISO) for multiple identical installations. For 220-1202 know when each method is appropriate.'), (263, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.3 Windows Tools', 'What do the following .msc commands open: compmgmt.msc, diskmgmt.msc, devmgmt.msc, eventvwr.msc, gpedit.msc, lusrmgr.msc?', 'compmgmt.msc = Computer Management. diskmgmt.msc = Disk Management. devmgmt.msc = Device Manager. eventvwr.msc = Event Viewer. gpedit.msc = Local Group Policy Editor. lusrmgr.msc = Local Users and Groups', 'MMC (Microsoft Management Console) snap-ins accessed via Run dialog: compmgmt.msc opens Computer Management (hub for Device Manager, Disk Management, Services, etc.). diskmgmt.msc opens Disk Management for partition/volume tasks. devmgmt.msc opens Device Manager to manage hardware and drivers. eventvwr.msc opens Event Viewer for system/application/security logs. gpedit.msc opens Local Group Policy Editor (not available on Home editions). lusrmgr.msc opens Local Users and Groups to manage accounts and group membership. For 220-1202 memorize these shortcuts — they appear frequently in troubleshooting scenarios.'), (264, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.3 Windows Tools', 'What are the purposes of msinfo32, resmon, cleanmgr, and defrag in Windows?', 'msinfo32 = System Information (hardware summary). resmon = Resource Monitor (real-time CPU/RAM/disk/network per process). cleanmgr = Disk Cleanup (free space by removing temp files). defrag = Disk Defragmenter/Optimizer (reorganize HDD; TRIM for SSD)', 'msinfo32 (System Information) provides a comprehensive summary: OS version, hardware resources, components, and software environment — useful for quick hardware inventory. resmon (Resource Monitor) extends Task Manager with per-process detail on CPU, memory, disk I/O, and network activity in real time. cleanmgr (Disk Cleanup) removes temporary files, Recycle Bin contents, Windows Update leftovers, and more — can recover gigabytes on older systems. defrag (Disk Defragmenter/Optimizer) reorganizes fragmented files on HDDs for faster access; on SSDs it runs TRIM (mark deleted blocks) instead of defragmenting. For 220-1202, know which tool to use for which diagnostic or maintenance task.'), (265, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.3 Windows CLI', 'What does diskpart do and what are its key subcommands?', 'diskpart is a CLI disk partitioning tool; key subcommands: list disk, select disk #, list partition, create partition primary, format fs=ntfs quick, assign letter=X, clean (wipes all data)', 'diskpart is a powerful command-line disk management utility (must run as Administrator). Workflow: open diskpart → ''list disk'' to see all disks → ''select disk 0'' → ''list partition'' → ''select partition 1'' → then perform actions. ''create partition primary'' creates a new primary partition. ''format fs=ntfs quick'' does a quick format. ''assign letter=D'' assigns a drive letter. ''clean'' removes all partition and volume information from the disk (destructive — used for secure wiping). ''extend'' and ''shrink'' resize volumes. For 220-1202, diskpart is the CLI equivalent of Disk Management and is heavily tested for drive configuration tasks.'), (266, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.3 Windows CLI', 'What are robocopy and xcopy, and when is robocopy preferred?', 'robocopy (Robust File Copy): advanced file/folder copy with resume on interruption, mirror mode (/MIR), multi-threading, preserves timestamps/ACLs. xcopy: older copy tool, no resume; robocopy is preferred for large or networked transfers', 'xcopy copies files and directory trees but lacks reliability features — it doesn''t resume interrupted transfers. robocopy (Robust File Copy, built into Windows Vista+) is a much more powerful copy tool: supports /MIR (mirror source to destination, deleting extras), /MT (multi-threaded), /Z (restartable mode), /COPYALL (copies all file attributes including ACLs and timestamps), and /LOG (writes output to a log file). robocopy is the standard for backing up data, migrating profiles, or syncing directories. For 220-1202, know that robocopy is preferred over xcopy for any large-scale or mission-critical file copy operation.'), (267, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.3 Windows CLI', 'What do gpupdate and gpresult do?', 'gpupdate /force = immediately re-applies Group Policy settings. gpresult /r = displays the Resultant Set of Policy (RSoP) — which GPOs are applied to the current user/computer', 'Group Policy is applied at logon and at periodic intervals (default ~90 minutes). gpupdate /force forces an immediate refresh of both computer and user policies without waiting for the next cycle. gpresult generates a Group Policy results report: gpresult /r shows a text summary of applied GPOs; gpresult /H report.html creates a detailed HTML report showing all applied and denied policies and the reason. These tools are critical for troubleshooting Group Policy issues — e.g., confirming that a password policy or software restriction policy is actually applied to a machine. For 220-1202 know both commands and their common switches.'), (268, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.3 Windows CLI', 'What do tracert, pathping, and nslookup do?', 'tracert: traces route (hops) to a destination showing latency per hop. pathping: combines ping + tracert with packet loss stats per hop. nslookup: queries DNS to resolve hostnames to IP addresses (and reverse)', 'tracert (trace route) sends ICMP packets with increasing TTL values to map each router hop to a destination — shows IP/hostname and round-trip latency per hop. Useful for identifying where in the network path delays or failures occur. pathping runs like tracert but then sends 100 packets to each hop and reports packet loss percentage — better for identifying unreliable links. nslookup queries DNS servers interactively: ''nslookup google.com'' returns the IP; ''nslookup'' then ''server 8.8.8.8'' lets you query a specific DNS server. For 220-1202 know when to use each tool in network troubleshooting.'), (269, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.4 Windows Network', 'What is the difference between a workgroup and a domain in Windows?', 'Workgroup: peer-to-peer, local accounts only, no central management, max ~10-20 PCs practical. Domain: centrally managed by Active Directory Domain Controller, domain accounts, Group Policy, single sign-on across resources', 'Workgroups are decentralized — each PC manages its own user accounts. There is no central authentication: if you want to access a shared folder on another PC, you need a matching local account on that machine. Suitable for small home/office networks. Domains use Active Directory on a Windows Server Domain Controller — user accounts are stored centrally, Group Policy enforces settings across all machines, and users can log in to any domain-joined PC with a single domain account (SSO). IT administrators can manage software deployment, password policies, and access controls from one place. For 220-1202: domains are the enterprise standard; workgroups are for small/home environments.'), (270, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.5 macOS Features', 'What are FileVault, Time Machine, Keychain, and Spotlight in macOS?', 'FileVault: full-disk encryption (XTS-AES-128). Time Machine: automatic incremental backup to external/network drive. Keychain: password/certificate manager. Spotlight: system-wide search (Cmd+Space)', 'FileVault 2 encrypts the entire macOS startup disk using XTS-AES-128 encryption — similar to BitLocker on Windows. Time Machine automatically backs up the entire Mac to an external drive or Time Capsule/NAS, keeping hourly backups for 24 hours, daily for a month, and weekly for all previous months. Keychain Access stores Wi-Fi passwords, website logins, certificates, and secure notes — the macOS equivalent of Windows Credential Manager. Spotlight (Cmd+Space) is a universal search tool that indexes and searches files, emails, contacts, apps, and can do calculations and conversions. For 220-1202 know each macOS feature and its Windows equivalent.'), (271, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.5 macOS Features', 'What is the macOS Terminal and what common commands does it share with Linux?', 'macOS Terminal provides a bash/zsh shell with Unix commands: ls, cd, pwd, cp, mv, rm, chmod, sudo, grep, man, top, ps, kill, brew (Homebrew package manager)', 'macOS is built on Darwin (BSD Unix), so the Terminal gives access to Unix/POSIX command-line tools. Common commands: ls (list files), cd (change directory), pwd (print working directory), cp/mv/rm (copy/move/delete), chmod (change permissions), sudo (run as root), grep (search text), man (manual pages), top/ps (process monitoring), kill (terminate process). Homebrew (brew) is the popular package manager for macOS — similar to apt on Debian/Ubuntu. For 220-1202 know that macOS and Linux share many CLI commands and that the Terminal is the gateway to macOS system administration.'), (272, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.6 Linux Basics', 'What are /etc/passwd, /etc/shadow, /etc/fstab, and /var/log in Linux?', '/etc/passwd: user account info (username, UID, shell). /etc/shadow: hashed passwords (root-only). /etc/fstab: file systems to auto-mount at boot. /var/log: system log directory (syslog, auth.log, kern.log)', 'Key Linux configuration files: /etc/passwd stores user account metadata — one line per user with fields: username:password-placeholder:UID:GID:comment:home:shell (passwords moved to /etc/shadow). /etc/shadow stores hashed passwords readable only by root — separates credential storage from account info for security. /etc/fstab (file systems table) defines which partitions/network shares mount automatically at boot, with options like read-only or noexec. /var/log contains system log files: /var/log/syslog or /var/log/messages for general logs, /var/log/auth.log for authentication events, /var/log/kern.log for kernel messages. For 220-1202 know the purpose of each file.'), (273, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.6 Linux Basics', 'How does Linux file permission (chmod) work in octal notation?', 'Permissions: rwx = 4+2+1. Octal 755 = rwxr-xr-x (owner: all; group/others: read+execute). 644 = rw-r--r-- (owner: read+write; others: read only). chmod 755 file.sh', 'Linux file permissions use a 3×3 grid: owner, group, others — each with read (r=4), write (w=2), execute (x=1). Octal values: 7=rwx, 6=rw-, 5=r-x, 4=r--, 0=---. chmod 755 file.sh sets owner=rwx(7), group=r-x(5), others=r-x(5) — typical for executable scripts. chmod 644 file.txt sets owner=rw-(6), group=r--(4), others=r--(4) — typical for config files. chmod 600 id_rsa sets owner=rw-, group/others=--- — required for SSH private keys. chown changes ownership: ''chown user:group file''. For 220-1202 know how to read and set octal permissions.'), (274, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.6 Linux Basics', 'What is the difference between apt and dnf/yum package managers in Linux?', 'apt (Advanced Package Tool): Debian/Ubuntu-based distros. dnf (Dandified YUM) / yum: Red Hat/Fedora/CentOS-based distros. Both install, remove, and update packages from repositories', 'Linux package managers handle software installation and updates: apt (apt-get/apt) is used on Debian, Ubuntu, Linux Mint, and derivatives — commands: ''apt update'' (refresh repo index), ''apt upgrade'' (update installed packages), ''apt install <pkg>'', ''apt remove <pkg>''. yum (Yellowdog Updater Modified) was used on older RHEL/CentOS systems; dnf replaced yum starting with Fedora 18 and RHEL 8 — commands are similar: ''dnf install <pkg>'', ''dnf update''. Both use package repositories. pacman is used on Arch Linux. For 220-1202 know which distro family uses which package manager.'), (275, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.1 Physical Security', 'What is a mantrap (access control vestibule) and what physical security controls complement it?', 'Mantrap/vestibule: two-door entry where the first door must close before the second opens — prevents tailgating. Complemented by: badge readers, biometrics, CCTV, bollards, cable locks, key fobs, smart cards', 'A mantrap (also called an access control vestibule) uses two interlocked doors to create an airlock-style entry — only one door can be open at a time, preventing unauthorized tailgating. Physical security layers: badge readers (proximity cards/RFID) grant access to authorized personnel; key fobs are small RFID tokens; smart cards embed a microchip (CAC/PIV — used by US government/military); biometrics use fingerprint/retinal/facial recognition. CCTV (Closed-Circuit TV) provides surveillance and forensic evidence. Bollards (short metal posts) prevent vehicle ramming attacks. Cable locks physically secure laptops to desks. For 220-1202 know all physical security controls and the threats they mitigate.'), (276, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.1 Authentication', 'How does TOTP (Time-based One-Time Password) work and what are its use cases?', 'TOTP generates a 6-digit code every 30 seconds using a shared secret + current time (RFC 6238); used in authenticator apps (Google Authenticator, Authy) as an MFA second factor', 'TOTP is an algorithm (RFC 6238) that combines a shared secret key (provisioned via QR code during enrollment) with the current Unix timestamp divided into 30-second intervals — HMAC-SHA1 produces a 6-digit code. Both the server and the authenticator app calculate the same code independently — no network connection needed during code generation. TOTP is the standard behind most authenticator apps. It''s a ''something you have'' factor for MFA. HOTP (HMAC-based OTP) is similar but counter-based instead of time-based. For 220-1202 know TOTP as the mechanism behind authenticator app MFA and how it differs from SMS-based OTP (SMS is less secure due to SIM swapping).'), (277, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.1 Authentication', 'What is SAML and how does it enable Single Sign-On (SSO)?', 'SAML (Security Assertion Markup Language): XML-based standard for exchanging authentication/authorization data between an Identity Provider (IdP) and Service Provider (SP) — allows one login to access multiple apps', 'SAML enables SSO in enterprise environments: the Identity Provider (IdP, e.g., Okta, Azure AD, ADFS) authenticates the user once; when the user accesses a Service Provider (SP, e.g., Salesforce, Office 365), the SP redirects to the IdP, which issues a SAML assertion (XML token) confirming the user''s identity. The SP trusts this assertion and grants access — no second login needed. SAML is the backbone of enterprise SSO and federated identity. OAuth 2.0 and OpenID Connect (OIDC) are modern alternatives more suited to mobile/API scenarios. For 220-1202 know SAML as the SSO standard and the IdP/SP roles.'), (278, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.1 Authentication', 'What is the difference between RADIUS, TACACS+, and Kerberos for network authentication?', 'RADIUS: UDP, encrypts only password, used for network access (Wi-Fi/VPN). TACACS+: TCP, encrypts entire payload, granular authorization per command (Cisco devices). Kerberos: ticket-based, Windows AD authentication, mutual authentication', 'RADIUS (Remote Authentication Dial-In User Service): uses UDP ports 1812/1813, primarily for network access authentication (802.1X Wi-Fi, VPN). Only the password is encrypted in the packet — rest of the attributes are in cleartext. Common with ISP/enterprise Wi-Fi. TACACS+ (Terminal Access Controller Access-Control System Plus): TCP port 49, Cisco proprietary, encrypts the entire packet body, separates authentication/authorization/accounting (AAA), allows per-command authorization — preferred for managing network devices. Kerberos: Windows Active Directory''s native authentication protocol — uses tickets (TGT from KDC) for mutual authentication without sending passwords over the network. For 220-1202 know use cases for each.'), (279, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.2 Attacks', 'What is an on-path (man-in-the-middle) attack and how does ARP poisoning enable it?', 'On-path attack: attacker inserts themselves between two communicating hosts to intercept/modify traffic. ARP poisoning: attacker sends fake ARP replies mapping their MAC to another host''s IP — redirecting traffic through the attacker', 'An on-path (formerly ''man-in-the-middle'') attack intercepts communication between two parties. ARP (Address Resolution Protocol) maps IP addresses to MAC addresses on a local network — it is stateless and has no authentication, so attackers can send unsolicited ARP replies (''ARP poisoning'' or ''ARP spoofing'') that tell other hosts: ''the default gateway IP is at my MAC address.'' Traffic destined for the gateway is then sent to the attacker, who forwards it (becoming transparent). Defenses: Dynamic ARP Inspection (DAI) on managed switches, static ARP entries, encrypted protocols (TLS/HTTPS). For 220-1202 know ARP poisoning as the enabling mechanism for on-path attacks on local networks.'), (280, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.2 Attacks', 'What are brute force vs. dictionary vs. rainbow table attacks on passwords?', 'Brute force: try every possible combination. Dictionary: try words from a wordlist. Rainbow table: precomputed hash-to-password lookup table (defeated by salting)', 'Brute force attacks try every possible character combination — guaranteed to find the password eventually but impractical for long passwords. Dictionary attacks use a wordlist of common passwords and words — much faster than brute force but fails on truly random passwords. Rainbow table attacks use precomputed tables of hash values to instantly reverse hash-to-password lookups — extremely fast but require huge storage. Defense against rainbow tables: salting — adding a random value (salt) to each password before hashing means the same password produces different hashes, making precomputed tables useless. For 220-1202: salt + bcrypt/Argon2 defeats rainbow tables; account lockout + CAPTCHA defeats brute force.'), (281, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.2 Attacks', 'What are Business Email Compromise (BEC) and supply chain attacks?', 'BEC: attacker spoofs/hijacks executive email to trick employees into wire transfers or credential disclosure. Supply chain attack: compromising software/hardware before it reaches the end user (e.g., malicious update, tainted hardware component)', 'Business Email Compromise (BEC) is a targeted social engineering attack — the attacker either spoofs a CEO/CFO email address or gains access to their actual account, then sends urgent wire transfer requests or credential phishing to finance/HR employees. BEC causes billions in losses annually (FBI IC3 top cybercrime by dollar value). Supply chain attacks compromise a trusted software update or hardware component to deliver malware to end users at scale — examples: SolarWinds (malicious update), compromised USB drives in manufacturing. Defenses: email authentication (DMARC/DKIM/SPF), out-of-band verification for wire transfers, vendor security assessments. For 220-1202 recognize these attack types and their defenses.'), (282, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.2 Attacks', 'What are zero-day vulnerabilities and how do they differ from unpatched vulnerabilities?', 'Zero-day: vulnerability unknown to the vendor — no patch exists. Unpatched: vulnerability is known with an available patch that hasn''t been applied. Zero-days are more dangerous because there is no defense other than mitigating controls', 'A zero-day (0-day) vulnerability is one that is unknown to the software vendor — it has been ''zero days'' since the vendor became aware of it, so no patch exists. Attackers who discover zero-days can exploit them with no official fix available. Detection relies on behavioral analysis (EDR/XDR), network anomaly detection, and exploit prevention features. Once disclosed (responsibly or publicly), the vendor races to issue a patch. An unpatched vulnerability has a known CVE and an available patch — applying Patch Tuesday updates (Windows), keeping software current, and vulnerability scanning addresses these. For 220-1202 know the difference and why zero-days require layered defenses beyond patch management.'), (283, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.3 Security Controls', 'What is Active Directory and what are its core components: domains, OUs, and Group Policy?', 'Active Directory (AD): Microsoft''s LDAP/Kerberos-based directory service. Domain: administrative boundary. OU (Organizational Unit): container for organizing objects (users/computers/groups). GPO (Group Policy Object): settings applied to OUs/domains', 'Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) is the central identity management service in Windows enterprise environments. A domain is an administrative and security boundary — all computers and users share a common database on the Domain Controller (DC). OUs (Organizational Units) are like folders within the domain — you can organize users and computers into OUs (by department, location, role) and apply different GPOs to each OU. GPOs define security settings, software installation, desktop restrictions, and hundreds of other policies — they are linked to sites, domains, or OUs and applied via Group Policy. For 220-1202 know the AD hierarchy: Forest → Domain → OU → Objects, and how GPOs flow downward.'), (284, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.3 Security Controls', 'What is DLP (Data Loss Prevention) and how does it work?', 'DLP: monitors and blocks unauthorized transfer of sensitive data (PII, PHI, credit card numbers) via email, USB, web upload, or printing — uses content inspection and policy rules', 'Data Loss Prevention (DLP) solutions prevent sensitive data from leaving the organization through unauthorized channels. DLP agents inspect content in motion (network traffic — emails, web uploads), in use (endpoint activity — copy to USB, printing), and at rest (stored data scanning). DLP policies define what counts as sensitive: credit card patterns (PCI), SSNs (PII), health records (PHI/HIPAA), source code, etc. When a policy match is detected, DLP can block, quarantine, encrypt, or alert. Examples: blocking emailing a document with 10+ credit card numbers, preventing USB copy of files tagged ''Confidential''. For 220-1202 know DLP as a control for data exfiltration prevention.'), (285, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.3 Security Controls', 'What is Privileged Access Management (PAM) and just-in-time access?', 'PAM: secures, monitors, and controls access to privileged accounts (admin/root). Just-in-time (JIT) access: grants elevated permissions only for the duration needed, then auto-revokes — reduces standing privilege exposure', 'Privileged Access Management (PAM) solutions vault privileged credentials (local admin, service accounts, root), enforce MFA for privilege use, record privileged sessions, and provide audit trails. Just-in-time (JIT) access (also called zero standing privileges) means users have no persistent admin rights — they request elevated access for a task, receive it for a limited time window, and it''s automatically revoked. This minimizes the attack surface: even if credentials are compromised, there are no persistent admin accounts to abuse. Examples: Microsoft PIM (Privileged Identity Management) in Azure AD, CyberArk, BeyondTrust. For 220-1202 know PAM as the solution for controlling privileged account risk.'), (286, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.3 Security Controls', 'What are the key elements of a Windows password policy and account lockout policy?', 'Password policy: minimum length (12+ chars), complexity (upper/lower/number/symbol), max age (90 days), history (24 passwords). Account lockout: threshold (5 attempts), duration (30 min), reset counter (30 min)', 'Windows password policy (via Group Policy → Computer Configuration → Windows Settings → Security Settings → Account Policies): Minimum password length: 8+ characters (NIST recommends 12+). Password complexity: enforces mix of character types. Maximum password age: how long before forced change (NIST now discourages routine expiration without compromise indication). Password history: prevents reusing recent passwords. Account lockout policy: Lockout threshold: number of failed attempts before lockout (e.g., 5). Lockout duration: how long the account stays locked. Reset counter: time window for counting failed attempts. For 220-1202 know these settings and where they are configured.'), (287, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.3 Security Controls', 'What is a screened subnet (DMZ) and how does it differ from a standard network segmentation?', 'Screened subnet (DMZ): semi-trusted network zone between the internet and the internal LAN — hosts public-facing servers (web, email, DNS). Traffic flows: Internet → DMZ → (filtered) → Internal LAN. Prevents direct internet access to internal resources', 'A screened subnet (traditionally called a DMZ — Demilitarized Zone) is created using two firewalls or a three-interface firewall: the outer firewall allows internet traffic to the DMZ; the inner firewall restricts what DMZ servers can access on the internal LAN. Public-facing services (web servers, email gateways, DNS) live in the DMZ — if compromised, attackers can''t directly reach internal systems. SOHO routers implement a simpler version: port forwarding exposes specific services without a full DMZ. For 220-1202 know the screened subnet architecture and why separating public-facing servers from the internal network reduces attack surface.'), (288, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.3 SOHO Security', 'What SOHO router security settings should always be configured?', 'Change default admin credentials, disable WPS, use WPA3/WPA2-AES, disable remote management, enable firewall, disable UPnP, set up guest network for IoT/visitors, update firmware', 'SOHO (Small Office/Home Office) router hardening checklist: (1) Change default username/password — default credentials are publicly known. (2) Disable WPS (Wi-Fi Protected Setup) — vulnerable to PIN brute force attacks. (3) Use WPA3 (or WPA2-AES at minimum) — avoid WEP and TKIP. (4) Disable remote management — prevents internet-accessible admin panel. (5) Enable the built-in SPI firewall. (6) Disable UPnP (Universal Plug and Play) — automatically opens ports, creating security holes. (7) Create a separate guest network for IoT devices and visitors — isolates them from the main LAN. (8) Keep firmware updated. For 220-1202 know all of these hardening steps.'), (289, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.3 Browser Security', 'What browser security features should technicians configure for end-user protection?', 'Enable: automatic updates, pop-up blocker, HTTPS-only mode, DNS-over-HTTPS (DoH). Audit: extensions (remove untrusted ones). Use: private/incognito mode for sensitive browsing. Set: browser proxy settings for corporate environments', 'Browser security configuration for end users: Keep browsers updated — most exploits target unpatched browsers. Pop-up blocker prevents malvertising. HTTPS-only mode forces encrypted connections — warns on HTTP sites. DNS-over-HTTPS (DoH) encrypts DNS queries so ISPs and eavesdroppers can''t see which domains you''re resolving. Extensions are a major attack vector — malicious browser extensions can steal credentials and inject ads; audit and remove unnecessary ones. Private/incognito mode doesn''t save history, cookies, or form data locally (but doesn''t hide traffic from ISP/employer). Corporate proxy settings route traffic through a filtering proxy for content inspection. For 220-1202 know these settings in context of user support.'), (290, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.3 Mobile Security', 'What is MDM (Mobile Device Management) and what can it enforce on managed devices?', 'MDM: centrally manages mobile devices. Can enforce: screen lock/PIN, full-device encryption, remote wipe, app allowlist/blocklist, VPN profiles, certificate deployment, container separation (BYOD), jailbreak/root detection', 'MDM (Mobile Device Management) solutions (e.g., Microsoft Intune, Jamf, VMware Workspace ONE) enroll devices and push configuration profiles. Key MDM capabilities: screen lock enforcement (PIN/biometric required), minimum passcode complexity, full device encryption, remote wipe (full or selective), push app installs/removals, VPN/Wi-Fi/email profile configuration, certificate distribution, containerization (separates work data from personal on BYOD devices), jailbreak/root detection and compliance policy (can quarantine non-compliant devices). MAM (Mobile Application Management) manages only apps without full device control. For 220-1202 know MDM as the enterprise solution for mobile device security.'), (291, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.4 Malware Removal', 'What are the 10 steps of the CompTIA malware removal process?', '1. Investigate/identify symptoms. 2. Quarantine infected system. 3. Disable System Restore. 4. Remediate (remove malware in safe mode). 5. Schedule scans/update AV. 6. Enable System Restore + create restore point. 7. Re-enable network. 8. Educate end user. 9. Document findings. 10. Verify system functionality', 'CompTIA''s official malware removal procedure: (1) Identify symptoms and research malware type. (2) Quarantine — disconnect from network to prevent spread/C2 communication. (3) Disable System Restore — prevents malware from hiding in restore points. (4) Remediate — boot to safe mode or WinPE, run updated AV/anti-malware scanners, manually remove if needed. (5) Schedule follow-up scans; ensure AV definitions are current. (6) Re-enable System Restore; create a clean restore point. (7) Reconnect to network. (8) Educate the user on how the infection occurred. (9) Document all findings, actions, and tools used. (10) Verify all applications and network resources function normally. For 220-1202 know this sequence in order.'), (292, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.3 Security Controls', 'What is AutoRun vs. AutoPlay and why should AutoRun be disabled?', 'AutoRun: automatically executes a program from removable media when connected (security risk — can auto-run malware). AutoPlay: prompts the user to choose an action. AutoRun should be disabled via Group Policy; AutoPlay is acceptable with user control', 'AutoRun reads autorun.inf from removable media (USB, CD) and automatically launches the specified executable — historically a major malware vector (Conficker worm spread via AutoRun). Microsoft disabled AutoRun for USB drives by default starting in Windows 7 SP1 and released patches for earlier versions. AutoPlay still prompts the user with action choices (open files, play media) but does not auto-execute programs — it''s safer but should still be configured appropriately. Group Policy: ''Turn off AutoPlay'' / ''Prevent AutoRun'' under Computer Configuration → Administrative Templates → Windows Components. For 220-1202 know the security distinction and that AutoRun should be disabled.'), (293, 'core2', '3.0 Software Troubleshooting', '3.1 Windows Boot Errors', 'What causes ''NTLDR is missing'' and ''Bootmgr is missing'' errors and how are they fixed?', 'NTLDR missing = Windows XP boot loader error (wrong partition active or corrupt boot files). Bootmgr missing = Windows Vista/7/8/10/11 error. Fix: boot from Windows media → Startup Repair or bootrec /fixmbr, /fixboot, /rebuildbcd', 'NTLDR (NT Loader) is the Windows XP boot loader — ''NTLDR is missing'' appears when the active partition is wrong, the drive boot order has changed, or NTLDR/boot.ini are missing/corrupt. Fix: set correct active partition in Recovery Console, copy NTLDR from install media. Bootmgr is Windows Vista+ boot manager — ''Bootmgr is missing'' has similar causes. Fix using bootrec from Windows Recovery Environment (WinRE): ''bootrec /fixmbr'' (rewrites MBR), ''bootrec /fixboot'' (rewrites boot sector), ''bootrec /rebuildbcd'' (rebuilds Boot Configuration Data store). Also ''bootrec /scanos'' scans for Windows installations to add to BCD. For 220-1202 know these commands and their order.'), (294, 'core2', '3.0 Software Troubleshooting', '3.1 Windows Troubleshooting', 'What causes a ''slow roaming profile'' or ''temporary profile'' issue and how is it resolved?', 'Slow roaming profile: large profile size (too many files in Documents/Desktop syncing over slow WAN). Temporary profile: corrupted or locked profile causes Windows to create a temp profile at logon. Fix: clean up profile size, check profile path, delete/rename corrupt profile key in registry (HKLM\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows NT\CurrentVersion\ProfileList)', 'Roaming profiles store user data on a network share and sync at logon/logoff — slow performance usually means the profile is too large (videos, large Outlook PST files) or the network connection is slow. Solutions: redirect Documents/Desktop to a separate share (Folder Redirection), set profile size limits via Group Policy. Temporary profile at logon: Windows creates a temp profile (TEMP) when it cannot load the actual profile — caused by locked/in-use profile files, permission issues, or corruption. Check: Event Viewer for profile service errors, Registry: HKLM\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows NT\CurrentVersion\ProfileList — look for a .bak entry or SID with wrong path. Delete or rename the corrupt entry and re-log. For 220-1202 know both issues and their fixes.'), (295, 'core2', '3.0 Software Troubleshooting', '3.2 Mobile Troubleshooting', 'What troubleshooting steps address mobile app crashes and failed app installs?', 'App crash: force stop → clear cache → clear app data → uninstall/reinstall → check OS version compatibility. Failed install: check storage space, check app permissions, re-download, check for sideloading restrictions, verify app store account', 'Mobile app troubleshooting approach: For crashes — Force Stop the app (Settings → Apps), then clear cache (removes temporary files, often fixes crashes without data loss), clear app data (resets app to fresh state — loses settings/login), uninstall and reinstall, check if the app requires a newer OS version. For failed installs — verify sufficient storage (apps often need 2× their size for installation), check that downloads can proceed (network/Wi-Fi), ensure the app store account is signed in, check for enterprise restrictions (MDM may block certain apps), verify the device is not in low-storage mode. Sideloading (installing APKs outside the Play Store on Android) requires enabling ''Install unknown apps'' — a security risk. For 220-1202 know this systematic approach.'), (296, 'core2', '3.0 Software Troubleshooting', '3.2 Mobile Troubleshooting', 'What are jailbreaking (iOS) and rooting (Android), and what security risks do they introduce?', 'Jailbreaking: removes iOS sandbox restrictions to install unsigned apps and system tweaks. Rooting: grants root/superuser access on Android. Both bypass OS security model — risks: malware, loss of warranty, no OTA updates, MDM non-compliance', 'Jailbreaking exploits iOS vulnerabilities to remove Apple''s code signing enforcement — allows installing apps from unofficial stores (Cydia), system-level tweaks, and custom themes. Rooting Android gives superuser (root) access — allows full control over the OS, custom ROMs, and unrestricted app permissions. Security risks of both: (1) Malware can be installed without OS-level sandboxing restrictions. (2) Official updates may break the jailbreak/root or be blocked by the user. (3) Device warranty is voided. (4) MDM policies detect jailbreak/root status and can block corporate access or wipe the device. (5) Banking and payment apps often refuse to run on jailbroken/rooted devices. For 220-1202 recognize these as security risks in mobile device management.'), (297, 'core2', '3.0 Software Troubleshooting', '3.3 Malware Symptoms', 'What are browser hijacking symptoms and how is it removed?', 'Symptoms: changed homepage/search engine, unwanted toolbars, pop-up ads, redirects to unknown sites. Removal: uninstall suspicious browser extensions, reset browser settings, run anti-malware scan, check startup entries (msconfig/Task Scheduler), remove suspicious programs from Add/Remove Programs', 'Browser hijacking is a type of malware/PUP (Potentially Unwanted Program) that modifies browser settings without permission. Symptoms: home page changed to unknown site, search results redirected through a different search engine injecting ads, unwanted toolbars, constant pop-ups, or browser opening tabs to ad sites. Removal steps: (1) Remove suspicious extensions in browser settings. (2) Reset browser to default settings. (3) Run anti-malware (Malwarebytes is effective for PUPs). (4) Check msconfig/Task Scheduler for persistent startup entries. (5) Uninstall suspicious programs via Control Panel. (6) Check browser shortcut target — malware sometimes adds a URL to the desktop shortcut''s target field. For 220-1202 know these symptoms and removal steps.'), (298, 'core2', '3.0 Software Troubleshooting', '3.3 Malware Symptoms', 'What is a false positive in antivirus software and why is it a problem?', 'False positive: AV software flags a legitimate file as malware. Problem: can quarantine/delete critical system files, block legitimate applications, disrupt operations — IT must whitelist/exclude the file and report to AV vendor', 'Antivirus false positives occur when legitimate software triggers a malware signature — usually due to code patterns that resemble known malware, or overly aggressive heuristic detection. Famous examples: AV products quarantining their own update files, or flagging custom in-house software. Impact: quarantined system files can cause application crashes or even prevent Windows from booting; business applications blocked can halt operations. Response: add the file/path to the AV exclusion list (whitelist) in the AV management console, restore the quarantined file if safe, report the false positive to the AV vendor. For 220-1202 know false positives as a legitimate AV problem requiring exclusion management — distinct from actual malware.'), (299, 'core2', '3.0 Software Troubleshooting', '3.1 Windows Troubleshooting', 'What tools and steps fix a failed Windows Update?', 'Steps: run Windows Update Troubleshooter, clear SoftwareDistribution folder, run ''net stop wuauserv'', DISM /Online /Cleanup-Image /RestoreHealth, SFC /scannow, check Windows Update logs (%windir%\Logs\WindowsUpdate)', 'Windows Update failures are often caused by corrupted update cache or damaged system files. Fix steps: (1) Run the built-in Windows Update Troubleshooter (Settings → Troubleshoot). (2) Stop Windows Update service: ''net stop wuauserv'', then delete the contents of C:\Windows\SoftwareDistribution\Download (the update cache), then restart: ''net start wuauserv''. (3) Run ''DISM /Online /Cleanup-Image /RestoreHealth'' to repair the Windows image from Windows Update servers. (4) Run ''SFC /scannow'' to fix protected system files. (5) Check %windir%\Logs\WindowsUpdate for specific error codes. Common error codes: 0x80070057 (invalid parameter), 0x800F0922 (cannot connect), 0x80073712 (missing file). For 220-1202 know this troubleshooting sequence.'), (300, 'core2', '4.0 Operational Procedures', '4.1 Documentation', 'What is a ticketing system and what information should every support ticket contain?', 'Ticketing system (e.g., ServiceNow, Jira, Zendesk): tracks IT incidents/requests. Every ticket should include: user/device info, problem description, date/time, priority/severity, assigned technician, steps taken, resolution, closure date', 'A ticketing (ITSM) system is central to IT service management — it creates a documented, trackable record of every incident, service request, and change. Key ticket fields: User name and contact info, Device/asset ID, Detailed problem description, Date and time reported, Priority/severity level (P1 critical to P4 informational), Assigned technician, All troubleshooting steps performed, Resolution description, Root cause (if identified), Time to resolution, Closure confirmation from user. Good documentation enables: trend analysis (recurring issues), SLA compliance tracking, knowledge base building, audit trails, and handoff between technicians. For 220-1202 know ticketing as a required operational procedure.'), (301, 'core2', '4.0 Operational Procedures', '4.1 Asset Management', 'What is an asset management system / CMDB and why is it important for IT operations?', 'Asset management tracks all IT assets (hardware/software/licenses). CMDB (Configuration Management Database): maps CIs (Configuration Items) and their relationships — supports change management, incident response, and compliance auditing', 'Asset management maintains an inventory of all IT assets: hardware (computers, servers, printers, network devices), software licenses, and cloud subscriptions. Key data: asset tag/serial number, purchase date, warranty expiry, assigned user/location, software versions, and license counts. A CMDB (Configuration Management Database) extends this to map the relationships between Configuration Items (CIs) — e.g., which applications run on which servers, which servers support which business services. CMDBs are critical for: change impact analysis (what breaks if I update this server?), incident resolution (what changed recently?), compliance (are all assets licensed?), and disaster recovery planning. For 220-1202 know asset management and CMDB as core ITSM components.'), (302, 'core2', '4.0 Operational Procedures', '4.2 Change Management', 'What is the IT change management process and what are the key document types involved?', 'Process: request change → document RFC → risk assessment → CAB approval → sandbox testing → implement → verify → document. Key docs: RFC (Request for Change), change log, rollback plan. Change types: standard (pre-approved), normal (CAB review), emergency (expedited CAB)', 'Change management ensures changes to IT systems are planned, tested, and documented to minimize risk. Process flow: (1) Submit RFC (Request for Change) detailing what, why, when, and risk. (2) Risk assessment — what could go wrong? Impact on users/business? (3) CAB (Change Advisory Board) reviews and approves/denies normal changes. (4) Test in sandbox/staging environment. (5) Schedule maintenance window. (6) Implement change. (7) Verify functionality. (8) Document outcomes and update CMDB. Rollback plan: every change must have a documented plan to reverse it if things go wrong. Standard changes are pre-approved (e.g., routine patch application). Emergency changes skip full CAB but require retrospective documentation. For 220-1202 know this process.'), (303, 'core2', '4.0 Operational Procedures', '4.2 Backup Types', 'What are full, incremental, differential, and synthetic full backups?', 'Full: copies all data, clears archive bit. Incremental: copies only changed data since last backup (any type), clears archive bit — fast backup, slow restore. Differential: copies all changes since last full, does NOT clear archive bit — slower backup, faster restore. Synthetic full: combines last full + all incrementals into a new full without re-reading source data', 'Backup strategies use the archive bit (a file attribute set when a file changes): Full backup: copies everything, clears archive bit for all files. Incremental: copies only files changed since last full OR incremental, clears archive bit — minimum daily backup size, but restore requires the last full + every incremental since. Differential: copies all files changed since the last full backup (doesn''t clear archive bit) — grows over time but restore needs only the last full + the latest differential. Synthetic full: backup software assembles a new full backup from existing full + incrementals on the backup server — no load on the production system. For 220-1202 know restore time vs backup time tradeoffs for each type.'), (304, 'core2', '4.0 Operational Procedures', '4.2 Backup Strategy', 'What is the 3-2-1 backup rule and the GFS (Grandfather-Father-Son) rotation scheme?', '3-2-1 rule: 3 copies of data, on 2 different media types, with 1 copy offsite. GFS rotation: daily (Son) backups, weekly (Father) full backups, monthly (Grandfather) full backups — provides tiered retention', 'The 3-2-1 backup rule is the gold standard for backup strategy: 3 total copies of data (1 original + 2 backups), stored on 2 different media types (e.g., local NAS + tape/cloud), with 1 copy offsite (protects against site-level disasters like fire/flood). GFS (Grandfather-Father-Son) tape rotation maximizes media reuse while providing tiered retention: Son = daily incremental/differential backups (kept 1 week). Father = weekly full backups (kept 1 month). Grandfather = monthly full backups (kept 1 year or longer). A newer extension is 3-2-1-1-0: adds 1 offline/immutable copy and 0 errors verified by restore testing. For 220-1202 know both the 3-2-1 rule and GFS rotation.'), (305, 'core2', '4.0 Operational Procedures', '4.2 Power Management', 'What are the different types of UPS (Uninterruptible Power Supply) and a surge suppressor?', 'Standby UPS: switches to battery on power loss (small gap). Line-interactive UPS: regulates voltage sags/surges + battery backup. Online/double-conversion UPS: always runs on battery (best protection, no transfer gap). Surge suppressor: protects against voltage spikes only — no battery', 'UPS types for 220-1202: Standby (offline) UPS: monitors power and switches to battery in ~10ms on failure — basic protection for small office devices. Line-interactive UPS: adds an AVR (Automatic Voltage Regulator) that handles brownouts/surges without switching to battery — better for areas with fluctuating power. Online (double-conversion) UPS: AC input is always converted to DC to charge the battery, then back to clean AC for the load — zero transfer time, completely isolated from power issues — required for servers and sensitive equipment. Surge suppressor: MOV (Metal Oxide Varistor) components absorb voltage spikes but provide NO battery backup — only protects against surges, not outages. For 220-1202 match each type to its use case.'), (306, 'core2', '4.0 Operational Procedures', '4.3 Incident Response', 'What is the order of volatility in digital forensics and why does it matter?', 'Most volatile → least volatile: CPU registers/cache → RAM → network state/connections → running processes → disk (HDD/SSD) → optical/removable media → backups/logs/archives. Collect most volatile data first before it''s lost', 'Order of volatility guides first responders in digital forensics — collect evidence from most volatile (lost quickly) to least volatile (persists longest): (1) CPU registers, cache, and RAM — lost when powered off; contains encryption keys, passwords, running processes. (2) Network connections — ARP tables, routing tables, open sockets — change rapidly. (3) Running processes — process list, open handles. (4) Hard disk contents — non-volatile but can be modified. (5) Optical/removable media — CDs, USB drives. (6) Backups, logs, archives — most persistent. For 220-1202 know this order. Also: before touching a potentially compromised system, document its current state, preserve RAM (live forensics if possible), and never run tools that modify the disk.'), (307, 'core2', '4.0 Operational Procedures', '4.3 Incident Response', 'What are the key steps in the CompTIA incident response process?', '1. Identify (detect incident). 2. Contain (limit damage — quarantine). 3. Eradicate (remove threat). 4. Recover (restore systems). 5. Lessons learned (post-mortem, documentation). Chain of custody: document evidence handling throughout', 'CompTIA''s incident response process aligns with NIST SP 800-61: (1) Identification — detect the incident through alerts, user reports, or monitoring tools. (2) Containment — short-term: isolate affected systems; long-term: patch/fix root cause without destroying evidence. (3) Eradication — remove malware, close vulnerabilities, reset compromised credentials. (4) Recovery — restore systems from clean backups, verify functionality, monitor closely. (5) Post-incident activity (Lessons Learned) — document timeline, impact, what worked, what didn''t, process improvements. Chain of custody: every piece of evidence must be documented — who collected it, when, how it was stored, who had access — to maintain legal admissibility. For 220-1202 know this sequence.'), (308, 'core2', '4.0 Operational Procedures', '4.3 Regulatory Compliance', 'What are HIPAA, PCI DSS, GDPR, and SOX — and what data do they protect?', 'HIPAA: US law protecting PHI (patient health info) — healthcare providers/insurers. PCI DSS: payment card data security standard — any entity processing credit cards. GDPR: EU regulation protecting EU residents'' personal data. SOX: US law requiring financial record integrity — public companies', 'Key compliance frameworks for 220-1202: HIPAA (Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act): US federal law — protects PHI (Protected Health Information), requires safeguards for medical records, breach notification within 60 days. PCI DSS (Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard): industry standard (Visa/Mastercard) — 12 requirements for securing cardholder data, mandatory for merchants/processors. GDPR (General Data Protection Regulation): EU law — right to access, right to erasure (''right to be forgotten''), data breach notification within 72 hours, privacy by design; applies to any organization handling EU residents'' data regardless of location. SOX (Sarbanes-Oxley): US law for public companies — financial reporting integrity, IT controls for financial systems. Know which data type each regulation covers.'), (309, 'core2', '4.0 Operational Procedures', '4.3 Regulatory Compliance', 'What are NDA, AUP, and data retention policies in IT operations?', 'NDA (Non-Disclosure Agreement): legal contract preventing disclosure of confidential information. AUP (Acceptable Use Policy): defines permitted use of company IT resources. Data retention policy: specifies how long data must be kept before disposal (driven by legal/regulatory requirements)', 'NDA (Non-Disclosure Agreement): employees and contractors sign NDAs to protect trade secrets, client data, and proprietary information — violations can result in legal liability. AUP (Acceptable Use Policy): defines what employees may and may not do with company computers, networks, and internet access — covers personal use, prohibited content, social media, etc.; must be signed during onboarding. Data retention policy: legal and regulatory requirements dictate minimum retention periods: HIPAA medical records: 6 years. GDPR: only as long as necessary for stated purpose. Financial records (SOX): 7 years. After the retention period, data must be securely destroyed per the data destruction policy. For 220-1202 know these policies and their purposes.'), (310, 'core2', '4.0 Operational Procedures', '4.4 Scripting', 'What are common use cases for scripting in IT operations (CompTIA A+ 220-1202)?', 'Scripting use cases: automated user onboarding/offboarding, batch file operations, automated backups, log parsing, system health checks, software deployment, network configuration, scheduled maintenance tasks', 'The 220-1202 exam tests understanding of when and why to use scripts, not deep coding skills. Common scripting use cases: (1) Automated user onboarding/offboarding — create/disable AD accounts, set permissions, send welcome emails. (2) Batch file operations — rename/move/copy files in bulk, process reports. (3) Automated backups — schedule robocopy or rsync to run nightly. (4) Log parsing — filter event logs for security events, extract error codes. (5) System health checks — check disk space, CPU usage, service status across multiple machines. (6) Software deployment — push MSI packages silently. (7) Network configuration — configure IP settings on multiple devices. PowerShell is the preferred tool for Windows automation; bash/Python for Linux/macOS. Know use cases over syntax.'), (311, 'core2', '4.0 Operational Procedures', '4.4 Remote Access', 'What remote access technologies does the 220-1202 exam cover?', 'RDP (Remote Desktop Protocol, port 3389): Windows graphical remote desktop. SSH (port 22): secure CLI remote access (Linux/network devices). VNC: graphical remote access (cross-platform). VPN: encrypted tunnel to private network. Screen sharing/remote support tools: RMM (Remote Monitoring & Management), TeamViewer, Remote Assistance', 'Remote access technologies for 220-1202: RDP (Remote Desktop Protocol): Microsoft''s protocol for full graphical remote desktop sessions to Windows machines — port 3389 TCP, requires Network Level Authentication (NLA) for security. SSH (Secure Shell): encrypted CLI access to Linux/Unix systems and network equipment — port 22; use SSH keys instead of passwords for better security. VNC (Virtual Network Computing): cross-platform graphical remote access; less secure than RDP, should be tunneled through SSH or VPN. VPN creates an encrypted tunnel between the client and corporate network — allows remote workers to access internal resources as if on-site. RMM (Remote Monitoring and Management) tools: allow IT teams to remotely manage, monitor, and support multiple endpoints simultaneously. Windows Remote Assistance (Quick Assist): invite-based support session.'), (312, 'core2', '4.0 Operational Procedures', '4.1 Onboarding/Offboarding', 'What are the key IT tasks in employee onboarding and offboarding?', 'Onboarding: create AD account, assign equipment, set up email/MFA/VPN, provide AUP/NDA to sign, install needed software, grant least-privilege access. Offboarding: disable account immediately, revoke tokens/MFA, retrieve equipment, preserve/transfer data, document access removed', 'Onboarding IT checklist: (1) Create user account (AD/Azure AD) with appropriate group memberships. (2) Provision and configure device (image, join domain, encrypt). (3) Set up email, MFA, and VPN. (4) Have user sign AUP, NDA, and security policy. (5) Install role-specific software. (6) Apply least-privilege principle — grant only needed access. Offboarding IT checklist (security-critical — must happen on last day or before): (1) Disable the AD account immediately — do not delete right away (preserve audit trail). (2) Revoke MFA tokens and session tokens. (3) Remove from all security groups. (4) Retrieve corporate devices. (5) Preserve/transfer critical data per legal hold requirements. (6) Revoke VPN certificates, remote access, and cloud app access. For 220-1202 know both processes.'), (313, 'core2', '4.0 Operational Procedures', '4.4 AI Management', 'What considerations apply to managing AI tools in enterprise IT environments (220-1202)?', 'Key concerns: data privacy (don''t input PII/PHI/trade secrets into public AI), output accuracy (verify AI-generated content), bias/fairness, regulatory compliance, acceptable use policy for AI tools, Shadow AI (employees using unapproved AI services)', 'The 220-1202 exam includes AI management as a new topic area. Enterprise IT considerations for AI: (1) Data privacy — employees must not enter PII, PHI, financial data, or trade secrets into public AI services (ChatGPT, Copilot) that may retain or train on that data; update the AUP to explicitly address AI tool use. (2) Output accuracy — AI can hallucinate (generate plausible but wrong information); all AI outputs must be verified before use in decisions. (3) Shadow AI — employees using unapproved AI tools bypass corporate data controls; IT should inventory and govern AI tool use. (4) Compliance — GDPR, HIPAA, and other regulations may restrict how data is processed by third-party AI. (5) Acceptable use — define approved AI tools and use cases in policy. For 220-1202 recognize these as real-world IT governance concerns.'), (314, 'core2', '4.0 Operational Procedures', '4.2 Backup Strategy', 'What is cloud backup vs. local backup vs. hybrid backup, and when is each used?', 'Local backup: fast backup/restore, no internet needed, vulnerable to site disasters. Cloud backup: offsite protection, accessible anywhere, slower restore, ongoing cost. Hybrid: local for speed + cloud for offsite — best of both (implements 3-2-1 rule)', 'Local backup (NAS, external drives, tape): fastest backup and restore speeds, no bandwidth dependency, low ongoing cost — but vulnerable to fire, flood, theft, or ransomware that spreads to attached backup drives. Cloud backup (AWS S3, Azure Backup, Backblaze): automatically offsite, scalable, accessible from anywhere — but restore speed depends on internet bandwidth, and large restores can take hours or days. Also ongoing subscription cost. Hybrid backup: combines a local backup target (fast daily restore) with cloud replication (offsite for DR scenarios) — this naturally implements the 3-2-1 rule. For 220-1202 know that hybrid backup is generally recommended for businesses as it balances RTO (Recovery Time Objective) and RPO (Recovery Point Objective) with offsite protection.'), (315, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.3 EOL/EOSL', 'What is the difference between EOL (End of Life) and EOSL (End of Service Life) for software/hardware, and why do they matter for security?', 'EOL: vendor stops selling/developing. EOSL (End of Service Life): vendor stops ALL support including security patches. Running EOSL software is a major security risk — no patches for newly discovered vulnerabilities. Example: Windows 7 EOSL January 2020', 'EOL (End of Life) means the vendor has stopped active development and new feature releases for the product — it may still receive critical security patches. EOSL (End of Service Life, also called End of Support) means ALL vendor support has ended, including security patches — any new vulnerabilities discovered will never be fixed. Running EOSL systems: security risk (unpatched CVEs accumulate), compliance violation (PCI DSS, HIPAA require current/supported software), and vendor will not provide assistance. Mitigation if EOSL systems can''t be immediately replaced: network isolation, additional firewall controls, and accelerated upgrade planning. Microsoft''s update lifecycle: Mainstream Support (new features + security) → Extended Support (security only) → End of Support. For 220-1202 know the risk and policy implications of running EOSL software.'), (316, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.3 BYOD', 'What is BYOD (Bring Your Own Device) and what security challenges does it present?', 'BYOD: employees use personal devices for work. Challenges: device not managed by IT, mixing personal/corporate data, MDM enrollment friction, patching compliance, remote wipe conflicts (wiping personal data), legal/privacy issues', 'BYOD policies allow employees to use their personal smartphones, laptops, and tablets for work — reduces hardware costs but creates security challenges: (1) IT doesn''t control the device baseline — personal devices may run outdated OS or have malware. (2) Corporate data mixes with personal data — sensitive emails/files on unmanaged devices. (3) Remote wipe: MDM full-device wipe removes ALL data including personal photos/apps — creates employee pushback; selective wipe (remove only corporate container) is preferred. (4) Legal/privacy: IT monitoring personal devices raises privacy concerns. (5) Patch compliance: IT cannot mandate updates on personal devices. Solutions: MDM containerization, MAM-only (manage apps, not device), clear BYOD policy in AUP, VPN for corporate access. For 220-1202 know BYOD risks and mitigation strategies.'), (317, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.3 Task Manager', 'What are the key tabs in Windows Task Manager and what does each show?', 'Processes: running apps and background processes with CPU/RAM/disk/network usage. Performance: real-time graphs for CPU/RAM/disk/network/GPU. App history: resource usage over time. Startup: programs that launch at boot. Users: per-user resource usage. Details: advanced process info (PID, threads). Services: running Windows services', 'Windows Task Manager (Ctrl+Shift+Esc or Ctrl+Alt+Del) tabs: Processes tab: all running processes grouped as Apps, Background processes, and Windows processes — shows CPU, memory, disk, and network consumption per process; right-click to End Task or Go to Details. Performance tab: live graphs for all system resources; ''Open Resource Monitor'' link for deeper detail. App history: resource consumption by Store apps over time. Startup tab: lists programs configured to start with Windows and their startup impact (High/Medium/Low/None) — disable unnecessary items here. Users tab: shows all logged-on users and their resource usage. Details tab: advanced view with PID, thread count, handles — used for troubleshooting. Services tab: view and start/stop Windows services. For 220-1202 know which tab to use for which diagnostic task.'), (318, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.6 Linux Basics', 'What is systemd and what are the systemctl commands for managing services?', 'systemd: init system and service manager used by most modern Linux distros (replaces SysVinit). Key commands: systemctl start/stop/restart/status <service>, systemctl enable/disable <service> (persist across reboots), systemctl list-units --type=service', 'systemd is the standard initialization system for modern Linux distributions (Ubuntu 15+, CentOS 7+, Fedora, Debian 8+). It replaces SysVinit and manages system startup, services, and dependencies. Key systemctl commands: ''systemctl start nginx'' — start a service. ''systemctl stop nginx'' — stop a service. ''systemctl restart nginx'' — stop then start. ''systemctl status nginx'' — show running status, recent logs, and PID. ''systemctl enable nginx'' — configure to start automatically at boot (creates symlink). ''systemctl disable nginx'' — remove from autostart. ''systemctl list-units --type=service'' — list all service units. ''journalctl -u nginx'' — view service logs. For 220-1202 know systemctl as the Linux service management tool.'), (319, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.4 Cloud Concepts', 'What is cloud identity synchronization and how does Azure AD Connect work?', 'Cloud identity sync: replicates on-premises AD accounts to cloud identity providers (Azure AD/Entra ID). Azure AD Connect: Microsoft tool that syncs on-prem AD users, groups, and passwords to Azure AD — enables hybrid identity (same credentials for on-prem and cloud resources)', 'In hybrid environments, organizations maintain on-premises Active Directory while also using cloud services (Microsoft 365, Azure). Azure AD Connect (now called Microsoft Entra Connect) runs on a Windows Server and synchronizes: user accounts, group memberships, and (optionally) password hashes or authentication tokens to Azure AD/Entra ID. Users then have the same username and password for both on-prem resources (file shares, printers) and cloud services (SharePoint Online, Teams). Password Hash Synchronization (PHS) copies hashed passwords to the cloud. Pass-through Authentication (PTA) validates passwords against on-prem AD in real time. Federated Identity (ADFS) redirects authentication to on-prem infrastructure. For 220-1202 understand that cloud identity sync enables seamless hybrid authentication.'), (320, 'core2', '2.0 Security', '2.2 Social Engineering', 'What are the key social engineering techniques tested on CompTIA A+ 220-1202?', 'Phishing (email), vishing (voice/phone), smishing (SMS), whaling (targeting executives), spear phishing (targeted), impersonation, tailgating, shoulder surfing, dumpster diving, pretexting (fabricated scenario to extract info)', 'Social engineering manipulates humans rather than exploiting technical vulnerabilities. Key types: Phishing: bulk deceptive emails impersonating trusted entities to steal credentials. Spear phishing: targeted phishing using personal details about the victim. Whaling: spear phishing targeting high-value executives (CEO, CFO). Vishing: phone-based social engineering (''your IT department calling — need your password to fix an issue''). Smishing: SMS-based phishing with malicious links. Impersonation: posing as IT support, a vendor, or an authority figure in person. Tailgating: following an authorized person through a secure door without authenticating. Shoulder surfing: observing someone''s screen or keyboard to steal credentials. Dumpster diving: searching discarded documents for sensitive information. Pretexting: fabricating an elaborate scenario to gain trust and extract information. For 220-1202 recognize all these attack types.'), (321, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.8 iOS and Android Features', 'A user wants to install an app that is not available in the official app store on their Android device. What is this process called, and what must be enabled?', 'Sideloading; enable ''Install unknown apps'' (or ''Unknown sources'') in Settings.', 'Sideloading installs APK files directly, bypassing the Google Play Store. On Android 8+, you enable per-app permission under Settings > Apps > Special App Access. It increases malware risk since apps aren''t Play Protect-vetted. iOS does not allow sideloading on non-jailbroken devices without Enterprise or TestFlight provisioning. For 220-1202 know that sideloading is Android-specific and is a security concern requiring policy control via MDM.'), (322, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.8 iOS and Android Features', 'What is ADB and what is it primarily used for?', 'Android Debug Bridge — a command-line tool for communicating with an Android device from a PC.', 'ADB allows technicians to install/uninstall apps, access a shell, transfer files, and capture logs on an Android device. USB debugging must be enabled in Developer Options. ADB is commonly used for troubleshooting, sideloading apps, and unlocking bootloaders. It is part of the Android SDK Platform Tools. For 220-1202 know that ADB requires USB Debugging enabled and is the primary CLI tool for Android device management.'), (323, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.9 Chrome OS Features', 'A user''s Chromebook is having persistent software issues. What is the Chrome OS equivalent of a factory reset, and what does it do?', 'Powerwash — erases all local data and returns the Chromebook to factory state.', 'Powerwash is accessed via Settings > Advanced > Reset Settings. It removes all local accounts, files, and settings but does not affect cloud-stored Google data. Because Chrome OS is cloud-centric, most data is safe in Google Drive. Powerwash is recommended before selling a device or after a serious software issue. For 220-1202 know that Powerwash is the Chrome OS factory reset and that Chromebooks are designed to store data in the cloud.'), (324, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.9 Chrome OS Features', 'What feature allows Chromebook users to run full Linux applications, and what is it called internally?', 'Linux (Beta) / Crostini — runs a Debian Linux container allowing native Linux app installation.', 'Crostini uses a virtual machine (Termina) running a Linux container, providing an isolated environment for Linux apps. Users can install .deb packages and use apt. It is enabled under Settings > Advanced > Developers > Linux development environment. This is separate from Android app support (via Google Play on compatible Chromebooks). For 220-1202 know that Chrome OS supports Linux apps via Crostini containers and is cloud-focused by design.'), (325, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.3 Application Compatibility', 'On a 64-bit Windows system, where are 32-bit applications installed by default?', 'C:\Program Files (x86)', '64-bit applications install to C:\Program Files, while 32-bit apps go to C:\Program Files (x86). This separation prevents DLL conflicts between 32-bit and 64-bit libraries. The WOW64 subsystem (Windows 32-bit on Windows 64-bit) allows 32-bit apps to run on 64-bit Windows. A 32-bit app cannot directly call a 64-bit DLL and vice versa. For 220-1202 know the directory distinction and that WOW64 enables 32-bit app compatibility on 64-bit Windows.'), (326, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.3 Application Compatibility', 'A legacy application only runs on Windows XP. How can you attempt to run it on Windows 10 without a virtual machine?', 'Right-click the executable > Properties > Compatibility tab > Run this program in compatibility mode.', 'Compatibility mode makes Windows present itself to the application as an older OS version. You can also adjust DPI settings, run as administrator, and disable visual themes from the same tab. It works for many older applications but not all — some require actual legacy OS environments. For 220-1202 know that compatibility mode is found in the exe properties and supports modes back to Windows XP SP3.'), (327, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.4 Windows Printer Setup', 'A user cannot print after connecting a new USB printer. What is the correct sequence to install the printer driver in Windows?', 'Connect printer, Windows installs driver automatically or use Add Printer wizard; install manufacturer driver if needed.', 'Windows first attempts to find the driver via Windows Update or driver store. If not found, use Settings > Bluetooth & devices > Printers & scanners > Add a printer/scanner. For network printers, provide the IP or hostname. If automatic detection fails, choose ''The printer I want isn''t listed'' for manual options. Always install the manufacturer driver for full feature support. For 220-1202 know the Add Printer wizard path and that the Print Spooler service (spoolsv.exe) must be running.'), (328, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.4 Windows Printer Setup', 'Print jobs are stuck in the queue and no documents are printing. What service should you restart, and how?', 'Print Spooler service (spoolsv.exe) — restart via services.msc or ''net stop/start spooler''.', 'The Print Spooler queues print jobs and communicates with the printer driver. Stuck jobs can be cleared by stopping the spooler, deleting files from C:\Windows\System32\spool\PRINTERS, then restarting the service. You can also manage it from services.msc or Task Manager. A corrupted spool file is a common cause of printer queues freezing. For 220-1202 know that clearing the spool folder requires stopping the Print Spooler service first.'), (329, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.5 Device Manager', 'In Device Manager, what does a yellow exclamation mark on a device indicate?', 'The device has a problem — usually a missing, corrupted, or incompatible driver.', 'A yellow exclamation mark means the device is recognized but not functioning properly. A yellow question mark means the device is unknown (no driver installed). A down arrow means the device is disabled. Right-clicking and selecting Properties shows the error code (e.g., Code 43 = device failure). For 220-1202 know the difference between the exclamation mark (driver problem) and question mark (unknown/no driver) symbols in Device Manager.'), (330, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.5 Device Manager', 'After a Windows Update, a sound card stops working. What Device Manager action should you try first?', 'Roll back the driver — Device Manager > device Properties > Driver tab > Roll Back Driver.', 'Driver rollback reverts to the previously installed driver version, which is useful when a new driver causes instability. The Roll Back Driver button is only available if a previous driver exists. If rollback is not available, uninstall the driver and reinstall the older version manually. Windows Update can sometimes push bad driver updates for third-party hardware. For 220-1202 know that driver rollback is under the Driver tab in Device Manager properties and requires a previous driver to exist.'), (331, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.6 Windows Activation', 'A Windows 10 installation shows error 0xC004F213 after a hardware change. What does this mean?', 'The digital license cannot be matched to the hardware — hardware change broke the digital activation link.', 'Windows 10/11 digital licenses are tied to the motherboard''s hardware hash. A major hardware change (e.g., motherboard replacement) can invalidate a digital license, especially OEM licenses. Retail licenses can be reactivated via phone or the activation troubleshooter. OEM licenses are non-transferable. Error 0xC004F213 specifically means hardware mismatch. For 220-1202 know that OEM licenses are tied to the original hardware and cannot be transferred, while Retail licenses can be moved.'), (332, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.6 Windows Activation', 'What is the difference between an OEM Windows license and a Retail Windows license?', 'OEM is tied to original hardware (non-transferable); Retail can be moved to a new computer.', 'OEM licenses are sold with PCs by manufacturers and cannot be transferred if the PC is replaced. They are cheaper but bound to the motherboard. Retail (Full Packaged Product) licenses are purchased independently and can be deactivated on one machine and activated on another. Volume licenses are used by organizations and managed through KMS or MAK. For 220-1202 know that OEM = non-transferable/hardware-bound, Retail = transferable, Volume = enterprise/KMS-managed.'), (333, 'core2', '2.0 Networking', '2.6 APIPA', 'A workstation has the IP address 169.254.45.12. What does this indicate, and what is the likely cause?', 'APIPA address — the device could not reach a DHCP server and self-assigned a link-local address.', 'APIPA (Automatic Private IP Addressing) assigns addresses in the 169.254.0.0/16 range when DHCP fails. The device can communicate with other APIPA hosts on the same subnet but cannot reach the internet or other subnets. To fix: check the DHCP server, network connectivity, and IP configuration. Run ''ipconfig /release'' then ''ipconfig /renew'' to retry DHCP. For 220-1202 know that 169.254.x.x always means DHCP failure and the device has an APIPA address.'), (334, 'core2', '2.0 Networking', '2.7 Network Adapter Troubleshooting', 'A user cannot access the network. ipconfig shows the correct IP. What should you check next?', 'Check default gateway, DNS settings, physical connection, and whether the adapter is enabled.', 'Correct IP but no connectivity suggests gateway or DNS misconfiguration. Run ''ping'' to the gateway to test Layer 3 connectivity, then ''ping 8.8.8.8'' to test internet routing, then ''nslookup google.com'' to test DNS resolution. Also check for a disabled adapter in Network Connections. ''ipconfig /flushdns'' clears the DNS cache. For 220-1202 know the structured troubleshooting: IP > Gateway ping > External IP ping > DNS test.'), (335, 'core2', '2.0 Networking', '2.7 Network Adapter Troubleshooting', 'What commands release and renew a DHCP lease in Windows?', '''ipconfig /release'' releases the current lease; ''ipconfig /renew'' requests a new IP from DHCP.', 'These commands are essential for DHCP troubleshooting. /release sends a DHCP Release message to the server; /renew sends a Discover/Request to obtain a new lease. If /renew returns an APIPA address, the DHCP server is unreachable. ''ipconfig /flushdns'' clears the local DNS resolver cache. ''ipconfig /registerdns'' re-registers the host with DNS. For 220-1202 know all four ipconfig switches: /release, /renew, /flushdns, /registerdns.'), (336, 'core2', '2.0 Networking', '2.8 Windows Remote Desktop', 'A technician tries to RDP to a Windows 10 Home machine but cannot connect. Why?', 'Remote Desktop (RDP) is only available on Windows 10/11 Pro, Enterprise, and Education — not Home.', 'Windows Home editions cannot act as an RDP host (server). They can use RDP as a client to connect to other machines. The workaround is to upgrade to Pro or use a third-party tool like VNC or TeamViewer. RDP uses TCP port 3389 and requires the Remote Desktop service to be running. NLA (Network Level Authentication) authenticates users before the full desktop loads, providing extra security. For 220-1202 know that RDP hosting requires Pro/Enterprise and runs on TCP 3389.'), (337, 'core2', '2.0 Networking', '2.8 Windows Remote Desktop', 'What is the difference between Remote Desktop and Remote Assistance in Windows?', 'Remote Desktop gives full control of an unattended session; Remote Assistance requires the user to invite a helper and can be view-only.', 'Remote Desktop (RDP) creates a separate session and locks the local screen — used for remote administration. Remote Assistance (or Quick Assist) requires the local user to send an invitation and can be configured for view-only or full control. Remote Assistance is typically used for help desk support. Both use TCP port 3389 but serve different use cases. For 220-1202 know that Remote Desktop = unattended admin access; Remote Assistance = user-initiated help desk tool.'), (338, 'core2', '4.0 Security', '4.6 Windows Defender Firewall', 'A newly installed application cannot communicate over the network. What should you check in Windows Defender Firewall?', 'Check inbound/outbound rules — add an Allow rule for the application or its port in Windows Defender Firewall.', 'Windows Defender Firewall has three profiles: Domain (on corporate network), Private (trusted home/work), and Public (untrusted networks). Applications can be allowed through the firewall via ''Allow an app or feature.'' For granular control, use Advanced Settings to create inbound/outbound rules by port, program, or protocol. Block rules take precedence over allow rules. For 220-1202 know the three firewall profiles and that Advanced Settings allows port/program-based rules.'), (339, 'core2', '4.0 Security', '4.3 Certificate Types', 'A browser shows ''Your connection is not private'' with a certificate error. What are two common causes?', 'Expired certificate, or certificate CN/SAN does not match the website domain (hostname mismatch).', 'Certificate errors indicate the site''s TLS certificate cannot be validated. Common causes: expired certificate, self-signed certificate not trusted by the browser''s CA store, hostname mismatch, or the CA is not trusted. Self-signed certificates are created without a CA and must be manually trusted. Browsers show ERR_CERT_DATE_INVALID for expired certs and ERR_CERT_COMMON_NAME_INVALID for hostname mismatches. For 220-1202 know the difference between self-signed (no CA trust) and CA-signed (trusted chain) certificates.'), (340, 'core2', '4.0 Security', '4.4 Email Security (SPF, DKIM, DMARC)', 'What does SPF protect against, and where is it configured?', 'SPF prevents email spoofing by specifying authorized mail servers in a DNS TXT record for the domain.', 'Sender Policy Framework (SPF) is a DNS TXT record listing IP addresses/servers permitted to send email for a domain. Receiving mail servers check SPF to verify the sending server is authorized. DKIM adds a cryptographic signature to email headers for integrity verification. DMARC uses SPF and DKIM results to define a policy (none/quarantine/reject) for failing messages. For 220-1202 know: SPF = authorized senders (DNS), DKIM = digital signature (integrity), DMARC = policy enforcement combining both.'), (341, 'core2', '4.0 Security', '4.4 Email Security (SPF, DKIM, DMARC)', 'An organization wants to ensure that emails failing SPF or DKIM checks are quarantined. Which email security standard handles this enforcement?', 'DMARC (Domain-based Message Authentication, Reporting & Conformance).', 'DMARC builds on SPF and DKIM by specifying a policy for what to do when checks fail: p=none (monitor only), p=quarantine (send to spam), or p=reject (block delivery). DMARC also provides aggregate reports to the domain owner. It requires at least SPF or DKIM alignment to pass. Without DMARC, SPF/DKIM failures are handled inconsistently by receivers. For 220-1202 know that DMARC = policy layer that uses SPF+DKIM results to quarantine or reject spoofed email.'), (342, 'core2', '4.0 Security', '4.2 Honeypots and Honeynets', 'What is the purpose of a honeypot in a network security strategy?', 'A honeypot is a decoy system designed to attract and detect attackers, diverting them from real assets.', 'Honeypots appear to be legitimate, valuable targets (e.g., a fake database server) but are closely monitored. Any interaction with a honeypot is inherently suspicious since legitimate users have no reason to access it. A honeynet is a network of multiple honeypots simulating a full environment. They help gather threat intelligence about attacker methods and tools without risking real systems. For 220-1202 know that honeypot = single decoy system; honeynet = network of honeypots; both are deception-based detection tools.'), (343, 'core2', '4.0 Security', '4.7 AppLocker and Software Restriction Policies', 'A company wants to prevent users from running any executable not on an approved list. Which Windows feature should be used?', 'AppLocker — a Windows feature that allows or blocks applications based on rules (path, publisher, hash).', 'AppLocker is available on Windows Enterprise and Education editions and is configured via Group Policy. It supports four rule collections: Executable, Windows Installer, Script, and Packaged Apps. Rules can use publisher (digital signature), path, or file hash conditions. Software Restriction Policies (SRP) is the older predecessor, available on all editions. AppLocker provides better logging and enforcement granularity. For 220-1202 know that AppLocker = application whitelisting via GPO, requires Enterprise, and uses publisher/path/hash rules.'), (344, 'core2', '4.0 Security', '4.5 Windows Defender Antivirus', 'Windows Defender real-time protection keeps turning off automatically. What is a likely cause?', 'A third-party antivirus is installed, which disables Defender''s real-time protection to avoid conflicts.', 'Windows Defender AV automatically disables real-time protection when another registered AV product is detected via Windows Security Center. If no other AV is present and Defender keeps disabling, check Group Policy (gpedit.msc) or registry settings. Definition updates are delivered via Windows Update and can also be updated manually. Exclusions should be used sparingly (e.g., for known false positives). For 220-1202 know that Defender and third-party AV coexist in limited passive mode, and Defender manages definitions through Windows Update.'), (345, 'core2', '5.0 Operational Procedures', '5.5 Slow System Performance Troubleshooting', 'A user reports their PC is running slowly. What are the first tools and checks you should use?', 'Task Manager (CPU/RAM/disk usage), Resource Monitor, check for malware, check startup programs.', 'Open Task Manager (Ctrl+Shift+Esc) to identify high CPU, RAM, or disk usage. Resource Monitor (resmon.exe) provides more detail. High disk usage (often 100%) may indicate an HDD bottleneck, Windows Search indexing, or malware. Use Autoruns or Task Manager''s Startup tab to disable unnecessary startup items. Check for malware with Defender or another scanner. For 220-1202 know Task Manager columns (CPU/Memory/Disk/Network), Resource Monitor for granular detail, and Event Viewer for application errors causing slowdowns.'), (346, 'core2', '5.0 Operational Procedures', '5.5 Application Not Responding', 'An application becomes unresponsive. After force-closing it, the issue recurs daily at the same time. Where would you look for the root cause?', 'Event Viewer > Windows Logs > Application log — look for errors/warnings near the time of the crash.', 'Event Viewer records application errors, crashes, and warnings with timestamps. The Application log shows events from user-mode programs; the System log shows OS and driver events. Look for Error level events with the application name as the source. A recurring crash may indicate a memory leak, corrupt file, or conflicting scheduled task. For 220-1202 know that application crashes are logged in Event Viewer > Windows Logs > Application, and a memory leak causes gradual performance degradation over time.'), (347, 'core2', '5.0 Operational Procedures', '5.5 Cannot Access Network Share', 'A user cannot access a network share that others can reach. What are the first three things to verify?', 'Verify the user has share/NTFS permissions, check firewall (port 445/SMB), and confirm correct credentials.', 'Network share access requires both Share permissions AND NTFS permissions — the more restrictive applies. SMB uses TCP port 445; verify Windows Firewall or network firewall is not blocking it. Credential prompts may indicate the user''s cached credentials are wrong — use Credential Manager to clear them. Also verify Network Discovery and File and Printer Sharing are enabled. For 220-1202 know that SMB = port 445, both share and NTFS permissions must allow access, and the more restrictive permission wins.'), (348, 'core2', '5.0 Operational Procedures', '5.5 Missing DLL Errors', 'A user gets a ''missing .dll file'' error when launching an application. What are the steps to resolve it?', 'Reinstall the application, run SFC /scannow, or register the DLL with ''regsvr32 filename.dll''.', 'DLL (Dynamic Link Library) errors occur when a required library is deleted, corrupted, or misregistered. Reinstalling the application usually restores the DLL. SFC (System File Checker) repairs missing or corrupted Windows system DLLs. ''regsvr32 filename.dll'' registers a COM DLL with the Windows Registry. Never download DLLs from random websites — malware is commonly distributed this way. For 220-1202 know: reinstall app first, then SFC /scannow for system DLLs, and regsvr32 for registering COM components.'), (349, 'core2', '5.0 Operational Procedures', '5.7 Environmental Controls', 'What are the ideal temperature and humidity ranges for a data center or server room?', 'Temperature: 68–77°F (20–25°C); Relative humidity: 45–55%.', 'Too much heat causes component failure and throttling; too little humidity causes ESD (electrostatic discharge); too much humidity causes condensation and corrosion. Hot/cold aisle containment alternates server rack orientations so cold air intakes face the cold aisle and hot exhausts face the hot aisle. ASHRAE provides data center temperature guidelines. ESD is a risk below ~35% humidity. For 220-1202 know the optimal ranges, that low humidity increases ESD risk, and that hot/cold aisle design improves cooling efficiency.'), (350, 'core2', '5.0 Operational Procedures', '5.8 E-Waste Disposal', 'A company needs to dispose of old computers, monitors, and batteries. What is the correct disposal method?', 'Use certified e-waste recycling centers, manufacturer take-back programs, or certified recyclers — never landfill.', 'Electronics contain hazardous materials (lead, mercury, cadmium) that contaminate soil and water if landfilled. The EU WEEE Directive requires manufacturers to provide take-back programs. In the US, many states have e-waste laws. Batteries must be recycled separately — lithium batteries are a fire hazard in regular waste streams. Hard drives should be wiped or shredded before recycling. For 220-1202 know that e-waste must go to certified recyclers, WEEE is the EU regulation, and data destruction must precede hardware disposal.'), (351, 'core2', '5.0 Operational Procedures', '5.6 Software Licensing', 'A company purchases software where one license covers all employees. What type of license is this?', 'Volume license (also called enterprise license) — covers multiple users/devices under one agreement.', 'Volume licensing allows organizations to deploy software to many machines without individual product keys. Microsoft uses Volume License Service Center (VLSC) and KMS/MAK activation. OEM licenses are pre-installed and tied to hardware. Retail licenses are transferable. Subscription/SaaS licenses (e.g., Microsoft 365) require ongoing payments and are cloud-delivered. Open-source software is freely distributed with source code under licenses like GPL or MIT. For 220-1202 know all license types: OEM, Retail, Volume, Subscription (SaaS), Freeware, Open-source.'), (352, 'core2', '5.0 Operational Procedures', '5.3 IT Professionalism', 'A user calls frustrated because their issue has not been resolved after two days. How should a professional technician handle this?', 'Acknowledge frustration empathetically, provide a realistic status update, set a clear timeline, and follow up proactively.', 'IT professionalism includes active listening, avoiding technical jargon with non-technical users, setting realistic expectations, and following through on commitments. Never promise what you cannot deliver. If an issue is delayed, proactive communication prevents escalations. Maintain confidentiality about other users'' information. For 220-1202 know that professionalism includes: empathy, avoiding jargon, setting expectations, follow-up, confidentiality, and never discussing other users'' personal information.'), (353, 'core2', '5.0 Operational Procedures', '5.4 Prohibited Content Discovery', 'While servicing a user''s PC, a technician discovers what appears to be illegal content. What is the correct response?', 'Stop accessing the content immediately, do not alter or delete anything, report to management, and preserve evidence.', 'Accessing illegal content further could implicate the technician legally. The chain of custody must be preserved — do not delete, move, or copy the content. Report to direct management, who will involve legal and potentially law enforcement. Document what was observed, when, and how it was discovered without disturbing the evidence. For 220-1202 know the correct sequence: stop > do not alter > report to management > preserve evidence > law enforcement if required by policy.'), (354, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.11 Thin Clients and VDI', 'What is a thin client, and how does it differ from a traditional desktop PC in a VDI environment?', 'A thin client is a minimal endpoint device that connects to a centralized server for all processing; it has no local OS/apps.', 'In a VDI (Virtual Desktop Infrastructure) environment, virtual machines run on centralized servers and users access them via thin clients over RDP or similar protocols. Thin clients reduce cost, power consumption, and maintenance since software and data reside on the server. Security is improved because data never leaves the data center. Management is centralized — updates and patches apply once on the server. For 220-1202 know that VDI = virtual desktops on servers accessed by thin clients, and benefits include centralized management, security, and easy provisioning.'), (355, 'core2', '2.0 Networking', '2.9 VLAN Security Segmentation', 'Why would a network administrator configure IoT devices on a separate VLAN from workstations?', 'To isolate IoT devices so a compromised device cannot access workstations or sensitive network resources.', 'VLANs (Virtual LANs) segment a physical network into logical networks at Layer 2 of the OSI model. Traffic between VLANs requires a Layer 3 device (router or Layer 3 switch) with ACLs controlling what can cross. IoT devices often lack security updates, making them easy targets; a guest/IoT VLAN limits blast radius. VLAN tagging uses IEEE 802.1Q. For 220-1202 know that VLANs provide logical segmentation, inter-VLAN routing requires a router, and guest/IoT VLANs reduce attack surface.'), (356, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.7 WSUS', 'What is WSUS and what problem does it solve for enterprise environments?', 'Windows Server Update Services — centralizes Windows update management, allowing admins to approve/deny updates before deployment.', 'Without WSUS, each client downloads updates directly from Microsoft, consuming internet bandwidth. WSUS acts as an internal update server; clients check WSUS instead of Windows Update. Admins can approve updates, schedule deployment, and target specific computer groups. Failed updates and compliance reports are visible in the WSUS console. WSUS is configured via Group Policy (GPUPDATE). For 220-1202 know that WSUS = centralized update management for enterprises, reduces bandwidth, and allows staged rollouts with approval control.'), (357, 'core2', '4.0 Security', '4.1 Separation of Duties', 'What is separation of duties and why is it important in IT security?', 'No single person can complete a sensitive process alone — tasks are divided to prevent fraud, errors, and insider threats.', 'Separation of duties (SoD) ensures that completing a critical action requires cooperation of multiple people. Examples: one admin can create accounts but another must approve them; a developer cannot deploy their own code to production. This prevents a single malicious insider from causing unchecked damage. Audit trails ensure accountability. Related concepts: least privilege and need-to-know. For 220-1202 know that SoD prevents single points of abuse, requires multiple people for sensitive tasks, and is enforced through role-based access controls and audit logs.'), (358, 'core2', '4.0 Security', '4.8 Input Validation and Injection Attacks', 'A web application allows users to enter a name field which is used in a database query. An attacker enters SQL code and retrieves all records. What attack is this, and how is it prevented?', 'SQL injection — prevented by input validation, parameterized queries (prepared statements), and least-privilege DB accounts.', 'SQL injection occurs when user-supplied input is inserted into a SQL query without sanitization. Attackers can retrieve, modify, or delete data. Prevention: use parameterized queries/prepared statements (separates code from data), validate and sanitize all inputs, use WAF, and run the database with minimal privileges. XSS (Cross-Site Scripting) is a similar injection attack targeting browsers by injecting malicious scripts. For 220-1202 know SQLi = database injection, XSS = browser script injection, both prevented by input validation.'), (359, 'core2', '3.0 Mobile Devices', '3.5 Mobile Device Synchronization', 'A user''s iPhone contacts, calendars, and photos are not syncing to their new iPhone. What should be checked first?', 'Verify iCloud sync is enabled for those data types under Settings > [Name] > iCloud on both devices.', 'iOS uses iCloud for cloud-based synchronization of contacts, calendars, photos, notes, and more. Each data category can be toggled individually in iCloud settings. The Apple ID must be the same on both devices. Google accounts sync Android data via Google Account sync settings. For enterprise email, ActiveSync (Exchange ActiveSync / EAS) syncs email, contacts, and calendars to corporate servers. For 220-1202 know: iOS sync = iCloud, Android sync = Google Account, corporate email/calendar sync = ActiveSync/EAS.'), (360, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.10 macOS Disk Utility', 'A Mac user reports disk errors and slow performance. What built-in macOS tool is equivalent to Windows CHKDSK?', 'Disk Utility > First Aid — checks and repairs disk errors and directory structure on macOS.', 'Disk Utility''s First Aid function verifies and repairs the disk directory, similar to CHKDSK /f on Windows. It can repair permissions on HFS+ volumes (less relevant on APFS where permissions are handled differently). For drives that cannot be repaired while mounted, boot from macOS Recovery (Cmd+R) and run First Aid from there. ''diskutil'' is the CLI equivalent. For 220-1202 know that macOS uses Disk Utility First Aid for disk repair, and macOS Recovery (Cmd+R at startup) is the macOS equivalent of WinRE.'), (361, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.12 Linux Editors', 'A Linux technician opens a file with vi and needs to save and exit. What is the correct command sequence?', 'Press Esc, then type '':wq'' and press Enter to write (save) and quit.', 'vi has two modes: command mode (navigate, delete) and insert mode (type text). Press ''i'' to enter insert mode, Esc to return to command mode. '':w'' saves without quitting, '':q'' quits, '':wq'' saves and quits, '':q!'' force-quits without saving. nano is simpler: Ctrl+O saves, Ctrl+X exits. nano displays shortcuts at the bottom of the screen. For 220-1202 know vi mode switching (i = insert, Esc = command), :wq to save/exit, and that nano is more beginner-friendly with on-screen shortcuts.'), (362, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.2 Windows Settings vs Control Panel', 'In Windows 10/11, where would you go to change the display resolution and join a domain, respectively?', 'Display resolution: Settings > System > Display. Domain join: Control Panel > System (or Settings > System > About > Advanced system settings).', 'Microsoft is gradually migrating functionality from Control Panel to the Settings app in Windows 10/11. Display, sound, network, and privacy settings are primarily in Settings. Some legacy tasks still require Control Panel: advanced sharing settings, Device Manager (also in Settings), user profiles, and administrative tools. Domain join is still accessible via both paths but Control Panel''s System applet remains commonly used. For 220-1202 know that Settings is the modern interface, Control Panel is legacy, and some functions (like certain admin tools) still require Control Panel.'), (363, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.5 Startup Repair and Recovery', 'A Windows 10 PC fails to boot twice in a row. What happens automatically, and where does it take the user?', 'Windows automatically launches Startup Repair from WinRE (Windows Recovery Environment) after repeated boot failures.', 'After two consecutive boot failures, Windows 10/11 automatically enters the WinRE and offers Startup Repair. Startup Repair fixes issues like corrupted BCD (Boot Configuration Data), missing boot files, and driver problems. It can be manually triggered by booting from Windows installation media or pressing F8/Shift+F8 for advanced options. Startup Repair does NOT fix hardware failures or missing Windows installations. For 220-1202 know that WinRE launches automatically after failed boots, and Startup Repair fixes BCD/boot file corruption but not hardware issues.'), (364, 'core2', '1.0 Operating Systems', '1.6 Group Policy Software Deployment', 'An administrator wants to automatically install an MSI application on all computers in an OU when they start up. Which GPO configuration is used?', 'Computer Configuration > Software Settings > Software Installation — assign the MSI package.', 'Group Policy software deployment supports MSI packages. ''Assigned'' software installs automatically at computer startup (Computer Config) or user logon (User Config). ''Published'' software (User Config only) appears in Add/Remove Programs for optional installation. Computer Configuration settings apply regardless of which user logs in. User Configuration settings follow the user to any machine. For 220-1202 know: Computer Config = applies at startup/to all users on that machine; User Config = follows the user; Assigned = mandatory; Published = optional (user config only).'), (365, 'core2', '2.0 Networking', '2.5 Network Troubleshooting Tools', 'A technician runs ''ipconfig /all'' and sees the DNS server is set to 192.168.1.1 but name resolution fails. What should be tested next?', 'Test if the DNS server is responsive using ''nslookup'' or ''ping 192.168.1.1'', then try an alternate DNS (e.g., 8.8.8.8).', 'If the default gateway/router is the DNS server, it may be down or its DNS relay may be failing. Use ''nslookup google.com 8.8.8.8'' to test resolution against a known public DNS server. If that works, the local DNS server is the problem. ''nslookup'' with no arguments enters interactive mode. ''ipconfig /flushdns'' clears cached bad DNS entries. For 220-1202 know nslookup syntax, that you can specify an alternate DNS server to isolate DNS server vs. connectivity issues, and that /flushdns resolves stale cache problems.'), (1001, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.1 OSI Model', 'What mnemonic represents the OSI model layers from top (Layer 7) to bottom (Layer 1)?', 'All People Seem To Need Data Processing', 'Each word maps to a layer: Application (7), Presentation (6), Session (5), Transport (4), Network (3), Data Link (2), Physical (1). The OSI model provides a common framework for describing how data traverses a network.'), (1002, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.1 OSI Model', 'At which OSI layer does SSL/TLS encryption and decryption processing occur?', 'Layer 6 — Presentation Layer', 'The Presentation layer handles data formatting, character encoding, and encryption/decryption. SSL/TLS is processed here. It is often discussed together with the Application layer (Layer 7) since many implementations combine their functions.'), (1003, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.1 OSI Model', 'What type of address does the Data Link layer (Layer 2) use, and what devices operate at this layer?', 'MAC (Media Access Control) addresses; switches and wireless adapters operate at Layer 2.', 'Layer 2 is the ''switching layer.'' It communicates between adjacent devices using hardware MAC addresses in EUI-48 or EUI-64 format. Ethernet NICs, bridges, and switches all operate at Layer 2.'), (1004, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.1 OSI Model', 'What is the Protocol Data Unit (PDU) name at each of the lower four OSI layers?', 'Layer 4 = Segment, Layer 3 = Packet, Layer 2 = Frame, Layer 1 = Bit', 'PDU names describe the data at each layer: Transport (L4) creates Segments, Network (L3) creates Packets, Data Link (L2) creates Frames, and Physical (L1) transmits Bits. Understanding PDUs helps when reading packet captures and troubleshooting.'), (1005, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.1 OSI Model', 'A technician says a router operates at Layer 3. What does this mean in practice?', 'The router makes forwarding decisions based on IP addresses (Layer 3 logical addressing) and routes packets between different IP subnets.', 'Layer 3 is the Network layer. Routers read the destination IP address in the packet header and consult their routing table to determine which interface to forward the packet out of. Routers also separate broadcast domains.'), (1006, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.2 Network Appliances', 'What is the key operational difference between an IDS and an IPS?', 'IDS (Intrusion Detection System) is passive — it monitors and alerts but does not block. IPS (Intrusion Prevention System) is inline — it actively blocks malicious traffic before it enters the network.', 'Because an IPS sits inline in the traffic path, a misconfigured IPS can block legitimate traffic. An IDS uses a SPAN port or tap and cannot block traffic. Both identify exploits, buffer overflows, and injection attacks using signatures or anomaly detection.'), (1007, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.2 Network Appliances', 'What is the difference between NAS and SAN storage technologies?', 'NAS (Network-Attached Storage) provides file-level access — entire files must be transferred. SAN (Storage Area Network) provides block-level access — only the changed block needs to be updated.', 'NAS uses standard network protocols (SMB, NFS) and is simpler to deploy. SAN uses Fibre Channel or iSCSI and is better suited for databases and applications needing high-performance storage. Both typically use isolated, high-bandwidth networks.'), (1008, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.2 Network Appliances', 'What hardware technology allows network switches to make very fast forwarding decisions?', 'ASICs (Application-Specific Integrated Circuits)', 'Unlike routers that may use software-based forwarding for some functions, switches use dedicated ASICs that can process frames at wire speed. This hardware-based approach makes switches significantly faster than general-purpose CPUs for Layer 2 forwarding.'), (1009, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.2 Network Appliances', 'What is the role of a Wireless LAN Controller (WLC) and what protocol does it use to communicate with APs?', 'A WLC centrally manages multiple access points — handling configuration deployment, monitoring, and performance reporting. It uses CAPWAP (Control and Provisioning of Wireless Access Points) to communicate with thin/lightweight APs.', 'Thin APs offload intelligence to the WLC rather than operating independently (fat/autonomous AP model). This simplifies large-scale deployments: change policy once on the WLC and it propagates to all APs.'), (1010, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.4 Ports and Protocols', 'FTP uses two port numbers. What is each port used for?', 'TCP port 21 — control channel (commands and authentication); TCP port 20 — data transfer in active mode.', 'FTP''s split control/data architecture means the connection for commands and the connection for file data are separate. FTP transmits credentials and data in cleartext. SFTP (Secure FTP) uses SSH on TCP port 22 and encrypts everything.'), (1011, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.4 Ports and Protocols', 'Which port does HTTPS use, and which port does SMTP use for encrypted client submission?', 'HTTPS uses TCP port 443. SMTP encrypted submission uses TCP port 587.', 'HTTP uses TCP 80 (cleartext). HTTPS uses TCP 443 (TLS encrypted). SMTP server-to-server uses TCP 25. Encrypted client-to-server email submission uses TCP 587 (STARTTLS). SMTPS uses TCP 465.'), (1012, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.4 Ports and Protocols', 'Why does DNS use both UDP and TCP port 53, and when is each used?', 'UDP 53 for standard queries (fast, low overhead). TCP 53 for zone transfers between DNS servers and for responses larger than 512 bytes.', 'Most DNS lookups use UDP because it is faster and DNS queries/responses are small. When a secondary DNS server replicates a full zone from a primary server (zone transfer), TCP is used for its reliability. Large DNSSEC responses may also require TCP.'), (1013, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.4 Ports and Protocols', 'What are the SNMP port numbers and what is the difference between polling and a trap?', 'UDP 161 for polling (manager queries agent). UDP 162 for traps (agent sends proactive alert to manager when a threshold is exceeded).', 'Polling requires the manager to repeatedly ask each device for data. Traps are device-initiated and only sent when something happens (e.g., link down, high CPU), reducing unnecessary traffic. SNMPv2c adds Inform — an acknowledged trap.'), (1014, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.4 Ports and Protocols', 'What is the difference between TCP and UDP? Give a use case for each.', 'TCP is connection-oriented with acknowledgments, error recovery, and flow control — used for HTTP, SMTP. UDP is connectionless with no acknowledgments or error recovery — used for DNS queries, DHCP, VoIP, and video streaming.', 'TCP uses a three-way handshake (SYN, SYN-ACK, ACK) to establish a session. UDP sends datagrams without setup, making it faster but unreliable. Applications requiring speed over reliability (video, DNS) use UDP. Applications requiring guaranteed delivery use TCP.'), (1015, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.4 Ports and Protocols', 'What port and protocol does RDP use, and what is a security best practice for it?', 'TCP port 3389. Best practice: do not expose RDP directly to the internet — place it behind a VPN or Remote Desktop Gateway.', 'RDP provides GUI-based remote access to Windows systems. Exposed RDP on port 3389 is a major attack surface and frequently targeted by brute-force and ransomware campaigns. Using a VPN or RD Gateway adds an authentication layer before RDP is accessible.'), (1016, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.4 Ports and Protocols', 'What ports do LDAP and LDAPS use?', 'LDAP uses TCP port 389. LDAPS (LDAP over SSL/TLS) uses TCP port 636.', 'LDAP (Lightweight Directory Access Protocol) is used to query directory services like Active Directory. Standard LDAP transmits data in cleartext. LDAPS encrypts the connection. Many organizations also use LDAP with STARTTLS on port 389 as an alternative to LDAPS.'), (1017, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.5 Transmission Media', 'What are the core diameter differences between single-mode and multimode fiber, and what does this affect?', 'Single-mode: 9µm core (laser, long distance). Multimode: 50µm or 62.5µm core (LED/VCSEL, shorter distance). All fiber has 125µm cladding.', 'The smaller single-mode core allows only one light path, eliminating modal dispersion and supporting distances over 100 km. Multimode allows multiple light paths, causing dispersion that limits distance. Mixing fiber types causes signal errors. Cable markings indicate type and size.'), (1018, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.5 Transmission Media', 'What is Twinax cable, what speeds does it support, and what is its maximum distance?', 'Twinax (Twin Axial) is a passive copper cable with two conductors typically attached to SFP+ connectors, supporting 10 Gbps Ethernet at up to approximately 5 meters.', 'Twinax (DAC — Direct Attach Copper) is cheaper than optical transceivers for very short connections like server-to-top-of-rack switch in data centers. It supports full-duplex communication. AOC (Active Optical Cable) extends range with built-in optical transceivers.'), (1019, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.5 Transmission Media', 'What minimum cable category is required for 1000BASE-T and for 10GBASE-T?', '1000BASE-T (1 Gbps): minimum Cat5, up to 100m. 10GBASE-T (10 Gbps): minimum Cat6 (up to 55m) or Cat6A (up to 100m).', 'Cat6A features additional spacers between pairs to reduce alien crosstalk, enabling 10 Gbps over the full 100-meter horizontal run. The IEEE standard specifies minimum requirements; TIA sets manufacturing standards.'), (1020, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.5 Transmission Media', 'What is plenum-rated cable and when is it required?', 'Plenum-rated cable uses a fire-retardant jacket (FEP or low-smoke PVC) instead of standard PVC, required in air-handling spaces (ceiling plenums and raised floors) by fire codes.', 'Standard PVC jackets produce toxic smoke when burning. Air-handling plenums circulate that smoke throughout a building. Plenum-rated cable (also called CMP) must be used in these spaces. It is more expensive than standard (CMR/riser or CMG) cable.'), (1021, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.6 Network Topologies', 'What is a spine-leaf data center architecture and what traffic pattern does it optimize for?', 'Spine-leaf is a two-tier topology where every leaf switch connects to every spine switch. It optimizes East-West (server-to-server) traffic with predictable, consistent latency.', 'Traditional three-tier (Core → Distribution → Access) was designed for North-South (client-to-server) traffic. Modern data center workloads are predominantly server-to-server. Spine-leaf ensures any server can reach any other server in exactly two hops through a spine switch.'), (1022, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.7 IPv4 Addressing', 'What are the three RFC 1918 private IP address ranges?', '10.0.0.0/8 (10.0.0.0–10.255.255.255), 172.16.0.0/12 (172.16.0.0–172.31.255.255), 192.168.0.0/16 (192.168.0.0–192.168.255.255)', 'Private IP addresses are defined in RFC 1918 and are not routed on the internet. Devices using private IPs require NAT (Network Address Translation) to communicate with public internet addresses. These ranges are available for any organization to use internally.'), (1023, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.7 IPv4 Addressing', 'What IP address range does APIPA use, and under what condition does a device assign itself an APIPA address?', '169.254.1.0 through 169.254.254.255 (the 169.254.0.0/16 range). APIPA activates when a device cannot reach a DHCP server.', 'APIPA (Automatic Private IP Addressing) is a Windows feature (also implemented in other OSes as Link-Local Addressing). An APIPA address allows local-segment communication only — the device cannot reach the default gateway or internet. It is a sign of DHCP failure.'), (1024, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.7 IPv4 Addressing', 'What is the IPv4 loopback address range, and what is it used for?', '127.0.0.1 through 127.255.255.254 (the 127.0.0.0/8 range). Used to test the local IP stack without sending traffic on the physical network.', '127.0.0.1 is the most commonly used loopback address. Pinging 127.0.0.1 verifies the TCP/IP stack is functioning on the local machine. Traffic sent to a loopback address never leaves the device.'), (1025, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.8 Network Environments', 'What is Software-Defined Networking (SDN) and how does it differ from traditional networking?', 'SDN separates the control plane (routing/forwarding decisions) from the data plane (packet forwarding), centralizing control in a software-based controller rather than distributing it across individual devices.', 'In traditional networks, each device independently makes forwarding decisions. SDN allows the entire network to be programmatically configured from a central controller, enabling automation, faster changes, and network virtualization. It is foundational to concepts like SD-WAN and SDDC.'), (1026, 'netplus', '1.0 Networking Concepts', '1.8 Network Environments', 'What is Zero Trust and what assumption does it make about the network?', 'Zero Trust is a security model that assumes no user or device is inherently trusted, regardless of network location. Every access request must be verified before access is granted.', 'Traditional perimeter security assumed everything inside the firewall was trusted. Zero Trust eliminates implicit trust — verification happens for every request to every resource. This is especially important with cloud services and remote work where the traditional perimeter no longer exists.'), (2001, 'netplus', '2.0 Network Implementation', '2.1 Routing Technologies', 'What is administrative distance (AD) and what are the AD values for directly connected, static, OSPF, EIGRP, and RIP routes?', 'AD indicates how trusted a routing source is — lower is preferred. Connected=0, Static=1, EIGRP=90, OSPF=110, RIP=120.', 'When a router learns the same destination from multiple sources, AD determines which route is installed in the routing table. If a static route and an OSPF route exist for the same destination, the static route wins (AD 1 < 110). Metric is only compared between routes from the same protocol.'), (2002, 'netplus', '2.0 Network Implementation', '2.1 Routing Technologies', 'When a router has entries for 10.0.0.0/8 and 10.0.30.0/24 in its routing table, which route does traffic to 10.0.30.5 use?', 'The 10.0.30.0/24 route — the longest prefix match (most specific route) is always preferred.', 'Routers always choose the most specific matching route, regardless of administrative distance or metric. The /24 is more specific than /8. This is called longest-prefix-match (LPM) and is fundamental to how all IP routing works.'), (2003, 'netplus', '2.0 Network Implementation', '2.1 Routing Technologies', 'What problem does FHRP (First Hop Redundancy Protocol) solve, and what are two examples?', 'FHRP provides default gateway redundancy by sharing a virtual IP between active and standby routers. Examples: HSRP (Cisco) and VRRP (open standard).', 'Without FHRP, a device with a single default gateway IP loses internet access if that router fails. FHRP assigns a virtual IP that clients use as their gateway. When the active router fails, the standby takes over the virtual IP — clients require no reconfiguration.'), (2004, 'netplus', '2.0 Network Implementation', '2.1 Routing Technologies', 'What is a router subinterface and what is ''router-on-a-stick''?', 'A subinterface is a virtual interface on a physical port (e.g., Gi0/0.10). Router-on-a-stick uses subinterfaces on a trunk link to route between multiple VLANs over a single physical cable.', 'Each subinterface is assigned a VLAN ID (encapsulation dot1Q) and an IP address serving as the gateway for that VLAN. The switch port connecting to the router must be a trunk. This avoids needing a separate physical router port per VLAN.'), (2005, 'netplus', '2.0 Network Implementation', '2.2 Switching Technologies', 'What does the 802.1Q standard define, and what fields does the VLAN tag contain?', '802.1Q defines VLAN trunking. It inserts a 4-byte tag into the Ethernet frame containing a TPID (0x8100) and TCI which includes a 12-bit VLAN ID, supporting 4,094 VLANs (1–4094).', 'The 12-bit VLAN ID field allows 2^12 = 4,096 values, but VLAN 0 and 4095 are reserved, leaving 4,094 usable VLANs. When a frame crosses a trunk port, the switch inserts this tag so the receiving switch knows which VLAN the frame belongs to.'), (2006, 'netplus', '2.0 Network Implementation', '2.2 Switching Technologies', 'What is the native VLAN on a trunk port, and what is the security risk if it is left as the default?', 'The native VLAN carries untagged traffic across a trunk. Leaving it as VLAN 1 (default) enables double-tagging VLAN hopping attacks, since VLAN 1 is the attacker''s default access VLAN.', 'A double-tagging attack embeds two 802.1Q tags in a frame. The outer tag (matching the native VLAN) is stripped by the first switch; the inner tag targets another VLAN. Mitigation: change the native VLAN to an unused VLAN on all trunk ports.'), (2007, 'netplus', '2.0 Network Implementation', '2.2 Switching Technologies', 'How long does it take STP (802.1D) to converge vs. RSTP (802.1W)?', 'STP (802.1D) takes 30–50 seconds to converge. RSTP (802.1W) converges in approximately 6 seconds. RSTP is backwards compatible with STP.', 'STP convergence involves Listening (15s) and Learning (15s) states before Forwarding. RSTP uses a negotiation mechanism between switches that bypasses these timers. RSTP maintains the same loop-prevention concept but dramatically reduces the time devices are down after a topology change.'), (2008, 'netplus', '2.0 Network Implementation', '2.2 Switching Technologies', 'What are the three STP port roles and what does each do?', 'Root Port (RP): the port closest to the root bridge; Designated Port: the port on each segment that forwards traffic toward the root; Blocked Port: disabled to eliminate loops.', 'The root bridge is elected by the lowest Bridge ID (priority + MAC). Every non-root switch has exactly one root port. Each network segment has one designated port. All remaining ports are blocked. RSTP renames Blocked to Discarding and adds Alternate and Backup roles.'), (2009, 'netplus', '2.0 Network Implementation', '2.3 Wireless Technologies', 'What are the three non-overlapping channels on the 2.4 GHz Wi-Fi band, and why does this matter?', 'Channels 1, 6, and 11. They are the only channels spaced far enough apart (25 MHz) to avoid co-channel interference in the 2.4 GHz band.', 'Adjacent APs must use non-overlapping channels to avoid interference. The 2.4 GHz band only has three non-overlapping channels, making it congested in dense environments. The 5 GHz band has 25+ non-overlapping channels, which is one reason to prefer it for high-density deployments.'), (2010, 'netplus', '2.0 Network Implementation', '2.3 Wireless Technologies', 'What encryption protocol does WPA2 use versus WPA3?', 'WPA2 uses CCMP (Counter Mode with CBC-MAC Protocol) with AES encryption. WPA3 uses GCMP (Galois Counter Mode Protocol) with AES encryption and GMAC for integrity.', 'WEP was deprecated due to serious cryptographic flaws. WPA was a temporary fix. WPA2 (since 2004) is widely deployed. WPA3 (2018) adds SAE (Simultaneous Authentication of Equals) for personal networks, providing resistance to offline dictionary attacks and forward secrecy.'), (2011, 'netplus', '2.0 Network Implementation', '2.3 Wireless Technologies', 'What consumer-friendly names correspond to 802.11ac and 802.11ax?', '802.11ac = Wi-Fi 5. 802.11ax = Wi-Fi 6 (and Wi-Fi 6E for the 6 GHz extension). 802.11be = Wi-Fi 7.', 'The Wi-Fi Alliance introduced consumer naming to simplify marketing. Wi-Fi 6 (802.11ax) supports the 2.4, 5, and 6 GHz bands and introduces OFDMA for more efficient spectrum usage. Wi-Fi 6E extends Wi-Fi 6 into the uncongested 6 GHz band.'), (2012, 'netplus', '2.0 Network Implementation', '2.3 Wireless Technologies', 'What does DFS (Dynamic Frequency Selection) do in wireless networking?', 'DFS automatically selects non-conflicting frequencies for APs, particularly to avoid interference with radar systems that have priority on certain 5 GHz channels.', 'DFS is defined in 802.11h. Channels in the U-NII-2 and U-NII-2e 5 GHz ranges are shared with weather and military radar. APs using DFS must monitor for radar and switch channels if detected. TPC (Transmit Power Control) works alongside DFS to manage power levels.'), (2013, 'netplus', '2.0 Network Implementation', '2.3 Wireless Technologies', 'What is band steering and why is it beneficial?', 'Band steering directs dual-band capable clients to the 5 GHz band instead of letting them choose based purely on signal strength, optimizing use of the less congested 5 GHz spectrum.', 'Without band steering, capable clients often latch onto 2.4 GHz due to its stronger signal through walls. Band steering pushes them toward 5 GHz for better throughput and less interference, while leaving 2.4 GHz for legacy or IoT devices.'), (2014, 'netplus', '2.0 Network Implementation', '2.4 Physical Installations', 'What is the difference between an MDF and an IDF in a structured cabling system?', 'MDF (Main Distribution Frame) is the central equipment room housing core infrastructure. IDFs (Intermediate Distribution Frames) are per-floor wiring closets that connect back to the MDF via backbone (vertical) cabling.', 'This hierarchical design follows TIA-568 standards. The MDF connects to the building entrance and houses routers, core switches, and servers. IDFs serve as aggregation points for horizontal cabling to workstations and APs on each floor.'), (3001, 'netplus', '3.0 Network Operations', '3.2 Network Monitoring', 'What are the three versions of SNMP and how do they differ in security?', 'SNMPv1: cleartext, community strings. SNMPv2c: cleartext, improved bulk data queries, community strings. SNMPv3: encryption, message integrity, authentication using hashed username/password.', 'The default community strings for v1/v2c are ''public'' (read-only) and ''private'' (read-write) — these must be changed in production. SNMPv3 is the only version that provides real security. Organizations should avoid v1/v2c on production networks or restrict them to a dedicated management VLAN.'), (3002, 'netplus', '3.0 Network Operations', '3.2 Network Monitoring', 'What is the MIB in SNMP and what does an OID identify?', 'MIB (Management Information Base) is the database of all variables accessible on a network device. An OID (Object Identifier) is a dotted-number sequence uniquely identifying a specific variable within the MIB.', 'Example OID: 1.3.6.1.2.1.11.28.0 — each number represents a level in the hierarchy. MIB-II (RFC 1213) is a standardized MIB providing common OIDs across all vendors. Vendors add their own private OIDs for device-specific metrics. MIB walker software can enumerate all OIDs on a device.'), (3003, 'netplus', '3.0 Network Operations', '3.2 Network Monitoring', 'What is the difference between an SNMP poll and an SNMP trap?', 'A poll is manager-initiated: the manager queries the agent on UDP 161. A trap is agent-initiated: the device sends an unsolicited alert to the manager on UDP 162 when a threshold is crossed.', 'Polling every device constantly creates management overhead. Traps reduce this by only alerting when something changes (link down, high CPU, CRC errors). SNMPv2c added Inform messages — these are like traps but require an acknowledgment from the manager for guaranteed delivery.'), (3004, 'netplus', '3.0 Network Operations', '3.3 Disaster Recovery', 'What is the difference between RTO and RPO?', 'RTO (Recovery Time Objective) is the maximum acceptable downtime — how fast services must be restored. RPO (Recovery Point Objective) is the maximum acceptable data loss measured in time — how old a backup can be.', 'Example: RTO=1 hour means the web server must be online within 1 hour of failure. RPO=30 minutes means no more than 30 minutes of data can be lost. Critical systems (banking, healthcare) require very low RPOs, often requiring continuous replication to a hot site.'), (3005, 'netplus', '3.0 Network Operations', '3.3 Disaster Recovery', 'What are the three DR site types, and how do they differ in cost and recovery speed?', 'Cold site: empty facility (cheapest, slowest — hours/days to recover). Warm site: partial infrastructure (moderate cost/speed). Hot site: fully replicated mirror (most expensive, near-instant failover).', 'A cold site requires procuring and configuring hardware before recovery can begin. A warm site has racks, power, and some infrastructure but needs data restore. A hot site uses continuous replication and can fail over in minutes. The 3-2-1 backup rule (3 copies, 2 media types, 1 offsite) applies to all.'), (3006, 'netplus', '3.0 Network Operations', '3.3 Disaster Recovery', 'What do MTTR and MTBF measure, and which should be high vs. low?', 'MTBF (Mean Time Between Failures) measures expected operational lifespan — higher is better (more reliable). MTTR (Mean Time to Repair) measures average time to restore service — lower is better (faster recovery).', 'A firewall with a 20-year MTBF is very reliable and needs minimal redundant spares. A device with a 1-year MTBF needs more spare units and closer monitoring. MTTR informs staffing levels, spare parts inventory, and support contract choices.'), (3007, 'netplus', '3.0 Network Operations', '3.4 IP Services', 'Describe the DNS recursive resolution process from a client making a query to receiving an answer.', 'Client → Local DNS resolver → Root servers (13 clusters) → TLD nameserver → Authoritative nameserver → IP returned, cached per TTL.', 'Root servers only know where TLD servers are (.com, .org, etc.). TLD servers know which nameserver is authoritative for a domain. The authoritative server has the actual record. The local resolver caches the result for the TTL duration (e.g., 300 seconds = 5 minutes), reducing future lookup time.'), (3008, 'netplus', '3.0 Network Operations', '3.4 IP Services', 'What is DNSSEC and what two additional DNS encryption methods protect DNS in transit?', 'DNSSEC digitally signs DNS records to prevent spoofing/cache poisoning. DNS over TLS (DoT) uses TCP port 853. DNS over HTTPS (DoH) uses TCP port 443, tunneling DNS inside HTTPS.', 'Original DNS was unauthenticated and unencrypted. DNSSEC adds cryptographic signatures verifying record authenticity but does not encrypt queries. DoT and DoH both encrypt the query/response. DoH is preferred by browsers because it uses port 443 and is indistinguishable from regular HTTPS traffic.'), (3009, 'netplus', '3.0 Network Operations', '3.5 Network Access', 'What is the difference between split tunneling and full tunnel VPN, and what is the security tradeoff?', 'Split tunneling: only corporate traffic goes through VPN; internet traffic exits locally (better performance, but internet not inspected). Full tunnel: all traffic goes through VPN (corporate filters apply, but higher latency and VPN load).', 'Split tunneling improves VPN performance and reduces bandwidth cost but means user internet browsing bypasses corporate security controls. Full tunnel gives IT visibility into all traffic but requires adequate VPN capacity. Zero Trust Network Access (ZTNA) is increasingly replacing both.'), (4001, 'netplus', '4.0 Network Security', '4.1 Security Concepts', 'What is the CIA triad in information security?', 'Confidentiality (only authorized parties access data), Integrity (data is unaltered and accurate), Availability (services are accessible when needed).', 'The CIA triad is the foundational framework for all security decisions. Security controls are evaluated by how they protect one or more CIA properties. For example, encryption protects confidentiality; hashing protects integrity; redundancy protects availability.'), (4002, 'netplus', '4.0 Network Security', '4.1 Security Concepts', 'What does PKI stand for and what is a Certificate Authority?', 'PKI (Public Key Infrastructure) is the framework of policies governing digital certificates. A Certificate Authority (CA) issues and digitally signs certificates, establishing trust for encryption and authentication.', 'PKI is used to add encryption keys to web servers (HTTPS), authenticate users and devices, and sign code. Organizations can use internal CAs for intranet services where all clients trust the internal CA, or external/commercial CAs for public-facing services.'), (4003, 'netplus', '4.0 Network Security', '4.1 Security Concepts', 'What is geofencing and how is it used in network access control?', 'Geofencing restricts or permits network access based on a user''s physical location, determined by IP address, GPS, or wireless network identification.', 'Example: block all logins from countries where the organization has no employees. Or require step-up MFA when access comes from outside the home country. Geofencing is a complementary control, not a standalone security measure, since IP geolocation can be circumvented with VPNs.'), (4004, 'netplus', '4.0 Network Security', '4.1 Security Concepts', 'What is Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) and how is it implemented in Windows?', 'RBAC assigns permissions to roles (e.g., manager, technician) rather than to individual users. In Windows, it is implemented by placing users in groups that have the appropriate permissions assigned.', 'RBAC is the practical implementation of least privilege at scale. Instead of managing permissions for hundreds of individual users, permissions are set on a handful of roles. Users inherit permissions from their group membership. This simplifies auditing and reduces misconfiguration.'), (4005, 'netplus', '4.0 Network Security', '4.2 Attack Types', 'What is a DNS amplification attack and what protocols are commonly exploited?', 'An attacker sends small queries (e.g., 28-byte DNS request) to open resolvers using a spoofed victim source IP, generating large responses (e.g., 1,300 bytes) that flood the victim. DNS, NTP, and ICMP are commonly exploited.', 'This is a reflection + amplification DDoS technique. The 46:1 amplification ratio means the attacker sends 1 unit of traffic and the victim receives 46. Botnets coordinate thousands of compromised devices to overwhelm targets. Mitigations: BCP38 (anti-spoofing), rate-limiting DNS resolvers.'), (4006, 'netplus', '4.0 Network Security', '4.2 Attack Types', 'What makes a DDoS attack an ''asymmetric threat''?', 'Attackers with minimal resources can disable systems with vastly greater capability by coordinating thousands of compromised devices (a botnet) to collectively overwhelm the target.', 'A single attacker can rent botnet time or control a large number of compromised IoT devices. A DoS can also be accidental — a network loop without STP, a broadcast storm, or a misconfigured device can cause a denial of service without any malicious intent.'), (4007, 'netplus', '4.0 Network Security', '4.2 Attack Types', 'What is MAC flooding and how does it compromise switch security?', 'MAC flooding overwhelms a switch''s MAC address table with fake entries. When the table is full, the switch enters fail-open mode and floods all traffic to all ports, acting like a hub — allowing an attacker to capture traffic meant for other devices.', 'Normal switch operation sends unicast frames only to the destination port. Fail-open flooding exposes all traffic to every port. Mitigation: port security — limit the number of MAC addresses allowed per port, and shut down or restrict ports that exceed the limit.'), (4008, 'netplus', '4.0 Network Security', '4.2 Attack Types', 'What is ARP poisoning and how does it enable a man-in-the-middle attack?', 'ARP poisoning sends unsolicited ARP replies that map the attacker''s MAC address to a legitimate IP, causing victims to send traffic to the attacker. The attacker can read, modify, or forward the traffic (MITM).', 'ARP has no authentication. Any device can send a gratuitous ARP claiming any IP-to-MAC mapping. Dynamic ARP Inspection (DAI) on switches validates ARP packets against the DHCP snooping database and drops invalid mappings. ARP poisoning only affects devices on the same Layer 2 segment.'), (4009, 'netplus', '4.0 Network Security', '4.2 Attack Types', 'What are the two methods of VLAN hopping?', '1. Double-tagging: embed two 802.1Q tags — the outer tag strips at the first switch, the inner tag delivers to the target VLAN. 2. Switch spoofing: trick a switch into forming a trunk via DTP, gaining access to all VLANs.', 'Double-tagging only works one-way (the return traffic can''t reach the attacker''s VLAN directly) but can still send packets to restricted VLANs. Mitigations: change the native VLAN away from VLAN 1, disable DTP on all access ports, and restrict trunk VLANs explicitly.'), (4010, 'netplus', '4.0 Network Security', '4.3 Security Features', 'What does DHCP snooping do, and what attack does it prevent?', 'DHCP snooping filters DHCP messages on switch ports — only trusted (uplink/server) ports may send DHCP offers. This prevents a rogue DHCP server from handing out malicious gateway or DNS addresses.', 'A rogue DHCP server attack redirects clients to the attacker''s gateway for MITM traffic interception. DHCP snooping marks switch ports as trusted or untrusted. Untrusted ports that send DHCP offers are shut down. The snooping binding table (IP+MAC+port) also feeds Dynamic ARP Inspection and IP Source Guard.'), (4011, 'netplus', '4.0 Network Security', '4.3 Security Features', 'What is Dynamic ARP Inspection (DAI) and what does it rely on?', 'DAI validates ARP packets on untrusted switch ports against the DHCP snooping binding table, dropping ARP replies that don''t match the known IP-to-MAC mappings.', 'DAI depends on the DHCP snooping binding table. Ports with statically configured IPs must be added to the ARP ACL or marked trusted, since they won''t appear in the DHCP snooping table. Together with DHCP snooping and IP Source Guard, DAI creates a comprehensive Layer 2 security stack.'), (4012, 'netplus', '4.0 Network Security', '4.1 Security Concepts', 'What is TLS used for and what is IPsec used for in terms of data protection?', 'TLS (Transport Layer Security) encrypts data in transit for application protocols (HTTPS, SMTPS). IPsec encrypts data in transit at the network layer, commonly used for VPN tunnels.', 'Both protect data in motion. TLS operates at Layer 4–7 and is application-layer aware. IPsec operates at Layer 3 and can encrypt all IP traffic between two endpoints, making it ideal for site-to-site VPNs. Full-disk encryption and database encryption protect data at rest.'), (5001, 'netplus', '5.0 Network Troubleshooting', '5.1 Troubleshooting Methodology', 'What are the seven steps of the CompTIA network troubleshooting methodology?', '1. Identify the problem, 2. Establish theories of probable cause, 3. Test the theory, 4. Establish a plan of action, 5. Implement the solution, 6. Verify full system functionality, 7. Document findings and outcomes.', 'The methodology emphasizes structure over random changes. Step 1 involves gathering info from users and asking what changed. Step 4 must include a rollback plan. Step 7 (documentation) is critical for institutional knowledge and preventing recurring issues.'), (5002, 'netplus', '5.0 Network Troubleshooting', '5.1 Troubleshooting Methodology', 'What are the three main troubleshooting approaches, and when is each most appropriate?', 'Bottom-up (start at Layer 1): use when physical cause is suspected. Top-down (start at Layer 7): use when application-specific. Divide-and-conquer (start at Layer 3): use when uncertain — ping first, then move up or down.', 'Bottom-up checks cables and link lights before complex config review. Top-down is efficient for application errors. Divide-and-conquer is the most common approach — a successful ping rules out Layers 1–3 and narrows the search to Layers 4–7. Following-the-path traces the specific traffic route.'), (5003, 'netplus', '5.0 Network Troubleshooting', '5.2 Physical Issues', 'What is the difference between NEXT, FEXT, and alien crosstalk in copper cabling?', 'NEXT (Near-End CrossTalk): interference at the same end as the signal source. FEXT (Far-End CrossTalk): interference at the far end of the cable. Alien crosstalk: interference from adjacent cables (not the same cable''s pairs).', 'Crosstalk is caused by electromagnetic induction between wire pairs. Maintaining the twist near terminations reduces it. Cat6A spacers reduce alien crosstalk at 10 Gbps speeds. The ACR (Attenuation-to-Crosstalk Ratio) measures signal quality by comparing signal strength to crosstalk level.'), (5004, 'netplus', '5.0 Network Troubleshooting', '5.2 Physical Issues', 'What is a split pair in copper cabling and why is it difficult to detect?', 'A split pair occurs when wires from different twisted pairs are used together (e.g., pin 1 from pair 1 and pin 1 from pair 2). It passes a continuity test but causes severe crosstalk and fails a performance test.', 'The twist in each pair is what cancels interference. When you mix wires from different pairs, the cancellation no longer works. A basic wire-map tester (continuity only) won''t catch this — you need a cable analyzer that tests for crosstalk to identify split pairs.'), (5005, 'netplus', '5.0 Network Troubleshooting', '5.2 Physical Issues', 'What is 1000BASE-T''s maximum cable distance and what cabling standard supports 10GBASE-T to full 100 meters?', '1000BASE-T: up to 100 meters on Cat5 minimum. 10GBASE-T: Cat6A supports the full 100 meters; Cat6 only supports up to 55 meters at 10 Gbps.', 'Cat6 crosstalk increases at higher frequencies, limiting 10 Gbps range. Cat6A''s additional physical separation between pairs (via spacers or thicker jacket) controls alien crosstalk, enabling 10 Gbps at the full 100-meter horizontal run defined by TIA-568.'), (5006, 'netplus', '5.0 Network Troubleshooting', '5.3 Network Services', 'What does `arp -a` display and what security anomaly can it reveal?', '`arp -a` displays the local ARP cache — a table of IP address to MAC address mappings. Multiple IP addresses mapping to the same MAC address can indicate ARP poisoning.', 'The ARP cache is populated as devices communicate on the local subnet. `arp -a` works on Windows, Linux, and macOS. After pinging a device, its mapping appears in the cache. Stale or incorrect entries can cause routing issues and should be cleared with `arp -d`.'), (5007, 'netplus', '5.0 Network Troubleshooting', '5.5 Tools and Protocols', 'What does the `ping` command use at Layer 3, and what can the TTL value in a ping response reveal?', 'Ping uses ICMP (Internet Control Message Protocol) Echo Request/Reply. The TTL value can indicate the OS: Windows defaults to TTL 128, Linux/macOS default to TTL 64.', 'Each router hop decrements TTL by 1. By seeing the returned TTL, you can estimate how many hops away the device is and what OS it likely runs. Ctrl+C stops a continuous ping and displays summary statistics including packets sent, received, and lost.'), (5008, 'netplus', '5.0 Network Troubleshooting', '5.5 Tools and Protocols', 'How does traceroute/tracert work mechanically?', 'It sends probes with incrementally increasing TTL values (starting at 1). When TTL=0 at a router, that router returns an ICMP TTL-Exceeded message identifying itself. Each round maps one hop, building the full path.', 'Windows uses `tracert` (ICMP by default). Linux/macOS use `traceroute` (UDP by default, ICMP with -I flag). Each hop typically shows 3 response time samples. An asterisk (*) means that router is filtering ICMP — it doesn''t necessarily mean a problem.'), (5009, 'netplus', '5.0 Network Troubleshooting', '5.5 Tools and Protocols', 'What is tcpdump and what format does it save captures in?', 'tcpdump is a command-line packet capture tool for Linux and macOS that captures network packets and saves them in pcap format, compatible with Wireshark for graphical analysis.', 'WinDump is the Windows equivalent. tcpdump can display output in real time or save to file for later analysis. Wireshark can open pcap files and provides protocol dissection, filtering, and conversation analysis. Together they are the primary tools for deep-dive traffic analysis.'), (5010, 'netplus', '5.0 Network Troubleshooting', '5.5 Tools and Protocols', 'What additional information does `ipconfig /all` provide over plain `ipconfig` on Windows?', 'Device name, MAC address (physical address), DHCP enabled/disabled, DHCP server IP, lease obtained/expiry times, and DNS server addresses.', '`ipconfig /release` and `/renew` manage DHCP leases. `ipconfig /flushdns` clears the DNS resolver cache. The Linux equivalent is `ifconfig` (legacy) or `ip address` (modern). Checking `ipconfig /all` is one of the first steps when troubleshooting IP connectivity.'), (5011, 'netplus', '5.0 Network Troubleshooting', '5.5 Tools and Protocols', 'What does `netstat -an` show and what does each flag add?', '`netstat -a` shows all active connections and listening ports. Adding `-n` displays addresses as IP numbers instead of resolving hostnames (faster output). `-b` on Windows also shows the executable associated with each connection.', 'netstat is essential for identifying which services are listening (open ports on the local machine), active connections, and their states (ESTABLISHED, LISTEN, TIME_WAIT). `ss` is the modern Linux replacement for netstat, providing the same information faster.'), (5012, 'netplus', '5.0 Network Troubleshooting', '5.5 Tools and Protocols', 'What is the difference between `nslookup` and `dig` for DNS troubleshooting?', 'Both query DNS servers for name resolution. `nslookup` is cross-platform but deprecated. `dig` is the modern replacement on Linux/macOS, providing more detailed output including TTL, record types, authority sections, and query time.', '`dig` output includes a full answer section, authority section (which nameserver is authoritative), and additional section. It also shows query time and which DNS server responded. Both can be directed to a specific DNS server: `nslookup hostname 8.8.8.8` or `dig @8.8.8.8 hostname`.');